WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.400
[Amit Varma]: When we think of geopolitics, when we look at our neighbourhood, it's natural to first

00:00:08.400 --> 00:00:13.320
[Amit Varma]: think of Pakistan. India and Pakistan have been in conflict since these nation states

00:00:13.320 --> 00:00:19.160
[Amit Varma]: existed. It may be a hard conflict to resolve. It may even be an impossible conflict to resolve.

00:00:19.160 --> 00:00:24.280
[Amit Varma]: But it is a conflict we understand. We get the motivations on either side. We know where

00:00:24.280 --> 00:00:29.480
[Amit Varma]: the roots of this conflict lie. We know both the what and the why. We also know the limits

00:00:29.480 --> 00:00:34.960
[Amit Varma]: of our engagement. But we know none of this about our relationship with China. Are India

00:00:34.960 --> 00:00:40.720
[Amit Varma]: and China friends or enemies? Are we engaged more in combat or more in cooperation? Do

00:00:40.720 --> 00:00:46.160
[Amit Varma]: the two sides look at this as a zero-sum game or a positive-sum game, a win-win situation?

00:00:46.160 --> 00:00:50.320
[Amit Varma]: What do the Chinese want from us? What do we want from them? Do we even know what we

00:00:50.320 --> 00:00:55.560
[Amit Varma]: want from them? These are important questions to understand, especially because China is

00:00:55.560 --> 00:01:00.560
[Amit Varma]: way more powerful than us in every possible sense. And while there was relative peace

00:01:00.560 --> 00:01:05.160
[Amit Varma]: between India and China in the decades since the 1962 war, things have been heating up

00:01:05.160 --> 00:01:10.600
[Amit Varma]: in the last few years. This is a problem. And before we solve it, we have to understand

00:01:10.600 --> 00:01:14.320
[Unknown]: it.

00:01:14.320 --> 00:01:19.760
[Unknown]: Welcome to The Seen and The Unseen, our weekly podcast on economics, politics and behavioural

00:01:19.760 --> 00:01:26.880
[Amit Varma]: science. Please welcome your host, Amit Bharma.

00:01:26.880 --> 00:01:31.440
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to The Seen and The Unseen. My guest today is a remarkable scholar, Kanthi Bajpai,

00:01:31.440 --> 00:01:36.760
[Amit Varma]: whose new book is called India vs China, Why They Are Not Friends. I've done many episodes

00:01:36.760 --> 00:01:41.240
[Amit Varma]: on China before, including a deep dive into the history of our interactions. So when I

00:01:41.240 --> 00:01:45.440
[Amit Varma]: first started reading Kanthi's book, I didn't imagine I would find much that was new in

00:01:45.440 --> 00:01:51.360
[Amit Varma]: it. But I did. This lucid and insightful book does the one thing that I enjoy in nonfiction

00:01:51.360 --> 00:01:56.880
[Amit Varma]: books. It gets meta. Specifically, this book builds a frame through which we can examine

00:01:56.880 --> 00:02:02.320
[Amit Varma]: the India-China relationship. It's built around what he terms the four P's, perception,

00:02:02.320 --> 00:02:07.720
[Amit Varma]: perimeters, partnerships and power. If you find China to be a bit of a mystery and don't

00:02:07.720 --> 00:02:11.800
[Amit Varma]: quite understand the contours of this conflict, then this book is for you. But Kanthi and

00:02:11.800 --> 00:02:17.040
[Amit Varma]: I don't only talk about the book. I love delving into the personal and intellectual

00:02:17.040 --> 00:02:21.720
[Amit Varma]: journey of my guests. And Kanthi had tons of insight for me about academia, being a

00:02:21.720 --> 00:02:27.640
[Amit Varma]: public intellectual, how one learns, why it is important to forget the inessential, how

00:02:27.640 --> 00:02:33.760
[Amit Varma]: writing and teaching make you a better thinker, and so on. There's tons of dope in this conversation.

00:02:33.760 --> 00:02:39.440
[Amit Varma]: But before we get to it, let's take a quick commercial break.

00:02:39.440 --> 00:02:44.340
[Amit Varma]: Long before I was a podcaster, I was a writer. In fact, chances are that many of you first

00:02:44.340 --> 00:02:50.080
[Amit Varma]: heard of me because of my blog India Uncut, which was active between 2003 and 2009 and

00:02:50.080 --> 00:02:54.720
[Amit Varma]: became somewhat popular at the time. I love the freedom the form gave me, and I feel I

00:02:54.720 --> 00:03:00.360
[Amit Varma]: was shaped by it in many ways. I exercise my writing muscle every day and was forced

00:03:00.360 --> 00:03:04.820
[Amit Varma]: to think about many different things because I wrote about many different things. Well,

00:03:04.820 --> 00:03:09.960
[Amit Varma]: that phase in my life ended for various reasons, and now it is time to revive it. Only now,

00:03:09.960 --> 00:03:17.240
[Amit Varma]: I'm doing it through a newsletter. I have started the India Uncut newsletter at indiancut.substack.com

00:03:17.240 --> 00:03:21.600
[Amit Varma]: where I will write regularly about whatever catches my fancy. I'll write about some of

00:03:21.600 --> 00:03:28.680
[Amit Varma]: the themes I cover in this podcast and about much else. So please do head on over to indiancut.substack.com

00:03:28.680 --> 00:03:33.600
[Amit Varma]: and subscribe. It is free. Once you sign up, each new installment that I write will land

00:03:33.600 --> 00:03:39.200
[Amit Varma]: up in your email inbox. You don't need to go anywhere. So subscribe now for free. The

00:03:39.200 --> 00:03:44.640
[Amit Varma]: India Uncut newsletter at indiancut.substack.com. Thank you.

00:03:44.640 --> 00:03:47.720
[Amit Varma]: Kanti, welcome to the scene and the unseen.

00:03:47.720 --> 00:03:49.280
[Amit Varma]: Thank you very much. It's great to be here.

00:03:49.280 --> 00:03:55.280
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I'm honored to have you here. And also, like I start my episodes, generally delving

00:03:55.280 --> 00:04:00.160
[Amit Varma]: deeper into, you know, a person's journey right from where they went to school, which

00:04:00.160 --> 00:04:04.720
[Amit Varma]: in your case is interesting, because you ended up becoming a headmaster for you went to school.

00:04:04.720 --> 00:04:09.200
[Amit Varma]: But you know, before I go back into the distant past, how have the last few months been for

00:04:09.200 --> 00:04:13.680
[Amit Varma]: you? Like Singapore's been on a sort of a trajectory of its own. And right now, it seems

00:04:13.680 --> 00:04:18.360
[Amit Varma]: to have coped with it really well compared to many others. And, you know, there was this

00:04:18.360 --> 00:04:22.080
[Amit Varma]: recent announcement by the Singapore government that hey, we're just going to treat this as

00:04:22.080 --> 00:04:26.760
[Amit Varma]: endemic after a certain point in time and and not do contact tracing and quarantine

00:04:26.760 --> 00:04:32.000
[Amit Varma]: and all of that. But quite apart from that aspect of it personally, how has this time

00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:36.240
[Amit Varma]: been for you where you can't go out so much and you teach and I guess you can't talk to

00:04:36.240 --> 00:04:41.040
[Amit Varma]: students so much. You can't interact physically with other scholars, you've actually written

00:04:41.040 --> 00:04:46.200
[Amit Varma]: a book during this period, in some kind of isolation, I'm guessing. What has it been

00:04:46.200 --> 00:04:47.200
[Guest]: like?

00:04:47.200 --> 00:04:51.040
[Guest]: Well, actually, I mean, I'm glad you asked that because I think this book would never

00:04:51.040 --> 00:04:58.080
[Guest]: have got written if I hadn't had the lockdown or semi lockdown. And the fact that it came

00:04:58.080 --> 00:05:03.320
[Guest]: along at a certain time, and coincidentally, juggernaut books approach me to write the

00:05:03.320 --> 00:05:09.280
[Guest]: book. I'm quite disciplined. But I think if I don't get a smart kick in the pants and

00:05:09.280 --> 00:05:15.320
[Guest]: in an environment where there's pressure on me, very long pieces of writing, I tend to

00:05:15.320 --> 00:05:20.360
[Guest]: start bracketing them and putting them aside. I write a lot of chapters and books and try

00:05:20.360 --> 00:05:25.840
[Guest]: and publish in journals. But those are, you know, fairly short pieces. This was supposed

00:05:25.840 --> 00:05:31.760
[Guest]: to be 50,000 words, and it ballooned in my hands to about 75,000 words. And I think juggernaut

00:05:31.760 --> 00:05:37.360
[Guest]: got quite nervy about the whole thing. But I think I needed the discipline or the semi

00:05:37.360 --> 00:05:44.560
[Guest]: lockdown environment, where we weren't completely stopped from moving out. By July of last year,

00:05:44.560 --> 00:05:50.040
[Guest]: when I began this, we could go to restaurants, there was hybrid teaching, I could go out

00:05:50.040 --> 00:05:55.520
[Guest]: shopping and so on, so forth, and under certain conditions, even see a movie. But in fact,

00:05:55.520 --> 00:06:00.980
[Guest]: it became quite complex to do all of that and rather artificial and sometimes stressful,

00:06:00.980 --> 00:06:07.200
[Guest]: because you're worried about being infected. Oddly enough, ironically, the COVID contributed

00:06:07.200 --> 00:06:13.400
[Guest]: to my staying parked at home within these four walls in a small study and banging the

00:06:13.400 --> 00:06:20.400
[Guest]: book out. So I'd say, you know, the kind of collateral of it for me was that it concentrated

00:06:20.400 --> 00:06:25.240
[Guest]: the mind wonderfully. And I just banged out the book in three months. I have a bit of

00:06:25.240 --> 00:06:28.600
[Guest]: a library. You know, my kids always say, you buy so many books, what do you do with all

00:06:28.600 --> 00:06:34.160
[Guest]: of them, dad? And partly, I mean, I do read all of them. But I bank them, I bank them

00:06:34.160 --> 00:06:40.560
[Guest]: for when I will need to reach for that volume, when I need to check a fact or a perspective.

00:06:40.560 --> 00:06:44.360
[Guest]: And of course, the internet rides to your rescue. So even though I couldn't get to the

00:06:44.360 --> 00:06:49.880
[Guest]: library and discuss things with colleagues all that much on the book, I could always

00:06:49.880 --> 00:06:55.520
[Guest]: turn to Professor Google, who had lots of information and ideas for me. And so that's

00:06:55.520 --> 00:06:57.960
[Amit Varma]: how the book got written, really.

00:06:57.960 --> 00:07:01.360
[Amit Varma]: So you know, we'll take a digression here before we go to your history and talk about

00:07:01.360 --> 00:07:05.480
[Amit Varma]: the act of writing and researching because, you know, when I picked up this book of yours,

00:07:05.480 --> 00:07:10.480
[Amit Varma]: which by the way, I love reading, so enlightening, and so lucidly written, you know, when I picked

00:07:10.480 --> 00:07:13.880
[Amit Varma]: it up, my assumption was I haven't read anything else by you except maybe columns here and

00:07:13.880 --> 00:07:17.880
[Amit Varma]: there. But then I realized that one of your earlier books, The Roots of Terrorism, which

00:07:17.880 --> 00:07:22.240
[Amit Varma]: I think you wrote in the early 2000s, I had actually read that while researching for a

00:07:22.240 --> 00:07:26.920
[Amit Varma]: review I wrote of Alan Kruger's book on what makes a terrorist. And I realized that I did

00:07:26.920 --> 00:07:31.440
[Amit Varma]: not remember anything of your book, or in fact of Kruger's book. And also, I have done

00:07:31.440 --> 00:07:36.240
[Amit Varma]: a number of episodes on China in the past. And I realized that while reading your book

00:07:36.240 --> 00:07:40.360
[Amit Varma]: and taking notes and all of that, that there was very little I remembered of them either.

00:07:40.360 --> 00:07:43.720
[Amit Varma]: And this is something I find as I'm coming into middle age that, you know, one may read

00:07:43.720 --> 00:07:48.560
[Amit Varma]: a lot and one may try to absorb a lot of knowledge, but it's one you forget. And obviously, by

00:07:48.560 --> 00:07:53.040
[Amit Varma]: osmosis, you know, some, you know, the frame of how you think about things and the way

00:07:53.040 --> 00:07:57.200
[Amit Varma]: you look at the world might be affected by osmosis in ways you don't consciously realize,

00:07:57.200 --> 00:08:02.120
[Amit Varma]: but nevertheless, you forget so much, you lose so much. So in your case, you know, do

00:08:02.120 --> 00:08:08.040
[Amit Varma]: you have any ways of, for example, doing knowledge management, trying to, you know, make sure

00:08:08.040 --> 00:08:12.520
[Amit Varma]: you assimilate all the information that you take in all the books that you read? Tell

00:08:12.520 --> 00:08:16.360
[Amit Varma]: me a little bit about, you know, how you do your knowledge management. And after that,

00:08:16.360 --> 00:08:18.560
[Amit Varma]: you know, we can discuss how you go about writing a book.

00:08:18.560 --> 00:08:23.860
[Guest]: Actually, you know, you made an important point, which you phrased a bit pejoratively,

00:08:23.860 --> 00:08:28.640
[Guest]: in the sense that you said, well, you know, I tend to forget, but actually forgetting

00:08:28.640 --> 00:08:34.680
[Guest]: is a rather important way of managing knowledge. I think the brain partly automatically does

00:08:34.680 --> 00:08:41.880
[Guest]: that. If it's not terribly telling stuff, your brain edits it out. It doesn't stay in

00:08:41.880 --> 00:08:47.280
[Guest]: long term memory. And that's useful, because otherwise, you would be filled with all kinds

00:08:47.280 --> 00:08:53.540
[Guest]: of stuff that you really don't need. And what you do, the space you need to process more

00:08:53.540 --> 00:09:00.120
[Guest]: recent readings and knowledge would kind of degrade or be compromised. So I think a good

00:09:00.120 --> 00:09:05.600
[Guest]: part of knowledge management, in fact, is creative or periodic forgetting. And so I'm

00:09:05.600 --> 00:09:10.800
[Guest]: quite comfortable with that. I mean, I think partly, I just feel if I need something, which

00:09:10.800 --> 00:09:16.920
[Guest]: has now disappeared from my memory banks, I'll just reach for the book or go back to

00:09:16.920 --> 00:09:24.400
[Guest]: the computer. The other strategy, of course, is that I think periodically, as I read, I

00:09:24.400 --> 00:09:30.440
[Guest]: do kind of do a tick mark to myself mentally, which is to say, what is the value add of

00:09:30.440 --> 00:09:35.640
[Guest]: this? I mean, does it just reinforce stuff that I already know pretty well, in which

00:09:35.640 --> 00:09:41.780
[Guest]: case it's dismissible, forgettable. But if it offers something that's somewhat different,

00:09:41.780 --> 00:09:47.400
[Guest]: then I think I tick it off in my brain. And at least it stays as a kind of gestalt, you

00:09:47.400 --> 00:09:54.100
[Guest]: know, a kind of a quick picture or an image that remains in my brain of a value add that

00:09:54.100 --> 00:09:59.720
[Guest]: came from a book. I mean, take an example in my field, and it's referenced in the book.

00:09:59.720 --> 00:10:04.360
[Guest]: You read so much, but recently, 10 years ago, let's say, I think we all encountered Joseph

00:10:04.360 --> 00:10:09.840
[Guest]: Nye, the Harvard political scientist's idea of soft power. And I mean, I don't bother

00:10:09.840 --> 00:10:14.960
[Guest]: to remember every argument he made about soft power. But basically, the concept of soft

00:10:14.960 --> 00:10:20.120
[Guest]: power, how it differed from other forms of power remained, and I just tick marked it.

00:10:20.120 --> 00:10:27.160
[Guest]: Didn't make much use of it, to be honest, until it came to this book. And so I had one

00:10:27.160 --> 00:10:32.960
[Guest]: of his books. I refreshed my memory quickly on some of the details related to it. And

00:10:32.960 --> 00:10:39.380
[Guest]: I think that's how I manage it. I try to consciously tick mark a value add without stressing myself

00:10:39.380 --> 00:10:44.440
[Guest]: about remaining every twist and turn in the tale. And I think that's probably what happened

00:10:44.440 --> 00:10:50.440
[Guest]: with you with my earlier book, which you probably said, hmm, something here, but I'm not sure

00:10:50.440 --> 00:10:56.160
[Guest]: it really necessarily advances the cause tremendously. And I think your brain quite rightly just ticked

00:10:56.160 --> 00:11:01.320
[Guest]: it off as something that you wouldn't really need to preserve. And to be honest, I'm not

00:11:01.320 --> 00:11:04.960
[Guest]: sure I could summarize that book any longer very well either. All the bits and pieces

00:11:04.960 --> 00:11:08.560
[Guest]: of it are now seeping back in now that you mentioned it.

00:11:08.560 --> 00:11:12.560
[Amit Varma]: I think you're being too harsh on your book and too kind on my brain, because I tend to

00:11:12.560 --> 00:11:16.680
[Amit Varma]: forget too much. I came across a really nice cartoon a couple of days ago where a man is

00:11:16.680 --> 00:11:20.160
[Amit Varma]: basically asking his wife, hey, what's the password to our computer? And she says, it's

00:11:20.160 --> 00:11:26.080
[Amit Varma]: our anniversary. And, you know, so he's forced to remember it. So I think a lot of wives,

00:11:26.080 --> 00:11:30.480
[Amit Varma]: including perhaps mine, listening to this will will be like, oh, that's why he forgets.

00:11:30.480 --> 00:11:36.200
[Amit Varma]: It's not important. But do you use any technology or stuff for taking notes and all of that?

00:11:36.200 --> 00:11:40.440
[Amit Varma]: Like earlier, what I would do is I would take copious notes in Microsoft Word, for example,

00:11:40.440 --> 00:11:44.880
[Amit Varma]: when researching for an episode or something I was writing, but it would just be a long

00:11:44.880 --> 00:11:50.320
[Amit Varma]: linear collation of text. And now I use something called Rome Research, which, you know, has

00:11:50.320 --> 00:11:55.520
[Amit Varma]: nested entries, bi-directional linking, it becomes much easier to kind of categorize

00:11:55.520 --> 00:11:59.920
[Amit Varma]: and search for keywords within everything that you've ever done, and all of that. So

00:11:59.920 --> 00:12:03.720
[Amit Varma]: do you feel that there is a need for that? Or do you feel that no, you know, whenever

00:12:03.720 --> 00:12:07.080
[Amit Varma]: you get down to writing something, you kind of broadly know that, oh, I need to read this

00:12:07.080 --> 00:12:11.960
[Guest]: and this and this, and then you go and do that? Yeah, I'm the old fashioned kind. So

00:12:11.960 --> 00:12:16.720
[Guest]: and I'm a hypocrite lector. I mean, I tell my students, please use technology, please

00:12:16.720 --> 00:12:21.560
[Guest]: be very assiduous about taking notes when I'm speaking or others are speaking when you

00:12:21.560 --> 00:12:28.080
[Guest]: read and all of that. But myself, I'm I'm a hopeless note taker. I either slavishly

00:12:28.080 --> 00:12:32.560
[Guest]: write down every single thing that somebody says, or that I've underlined when I first

00:12:32.560 --> 00:12:38.680
[Guest]: scan a book or a piece of writing, and I can't see the woods for the trees, or I'm so lazy

00:12:38.680 --> 00:12:45.220
[Guest]: that I just give up completely and hope that if it's interesting enough, stuff will stay

00:12:45.220 --> 00:12:50.300
[Guest]: in my brain, as I said earlier, as a kind of gestalt, an image, or that little bits

00:12:50.300 --> 00:12:54.000
[Guest]: and pieces will remain, and I'll go back to the source when I need it, like you say, when

00:12:54.000 --> 00:13:01.000
[Guest]: I need it, I'll go back to the source, take notes. Even then, I'm a pen and paper kind

00:13:01.000 --> 00:13:10.960
[Guest]: of guy. And so I will just yank out my little pad and pen and take horrible scribbly notes.

00:13:10.960 --> 00:13:14.960
[Guest]: And in fact, technology has undermined me, because I've got so used to working on a keyboard

00:13:14.960 --> 00:13:21.120
[Guest]: now that I can hardly, you know, handwrite anymore. And often when I do my notes, I can't

00:13:21.120 --> 00:13:26.240
[Guest]: even I can't make sense of my own notes. So I go along as I write, I have a broad sense

00:13:26.240 --> 00:13:33.240
[Guest]: of where I'm going. And I write quite sort of ambitiously, I make assertions. And then

00:13:33.240 --> 00:13:36.960
[Guest]: I start to go back and look at whether the evidence really bears out what I'm saying,

00:13:36.960 --> 00:13:39.840
[Guest]: and do I need to modify it?

00:13:39.840 --> 00:13:43.520
[Amit Varma]: You made an aside, and I'll make an aside based on that. And your side was that technology

00:13:43.520 --> 00:13:47.840
[Amit Varma]: is kind of undermined your habit of taking handwritten notes, and so on. And, you know,

00:13:47.840 --> 00:13:52.120
[Amit Varma]: I teach an online writing course. And after one of the webinars of that recently, one

00:13:52.120 --> 00:13:55.160
[Amit Varma]: of the participants asked me an interesting question, which got me to thinking because

00:13:55.160 --> 00:14:00.440
[Amit Varma]: I hadn't really thought about it. And her question was that, is what you write different?

00:14:00.440 --> 00:14:05.120
[Amit Varma]: Or is it shaped by whether you are typing it on a keyboard and, you know, actually handwriting

00:14:05.120 --> 00:14:10.040
[Amit Varma]: it by pen? And at one level, obviously, the answer is no, because words are words. And

00:14:10.040 --> 00:14:13.920
[Amit Varma]: I've always held that, you know, for me, for example, a book is a words and author writes

00:14:13.920 --> 00:14:17.160
[Amit Varma]: everything else is packaging. So whether I'm holding a physical book or a Kindle, the words

00:14:17.160 --> 00:14:21.360
[Amit Varma]: are words. But on the other hand, if you you know, look at the way that you write like

00:14:21.360 --> 00:14:25.280
[Amit Varma]: there are some people, there'll be videos on YouTube about how you can type as fast

00:14:25.280 --> 00:14:31.920
[Amit Varma]: as you think. And the act of writing physically on paper is much slower. And therefore, you

00:14:31.920 --> 00:14:35.960
[Amit Varma]: would imagine that your thinking also has to slow down to match the pace of your writing

00:14:35.960 --> 00:14:39.880
[Amit Varma]: when you're writing by hand. And that may change the form of your thinking. Now, I don't

00:14:39.880 --> 00:14:43.520
[Amit Varma]: know in what way and I'm kind of thinking aloud, you know, maybe it brings some kind

00:14:43.520 --> 00:14:47.560
[Amit Varma]: of tear off to your thinking and helps it maybe it harms it because you're not, you

00:14:47.560 --> 00:14:51.520
[Amit Varma]: know, you're going along slower than you would. But since you just mentioned your habit of

00:14:51.520 --> 00:14:54.880
[Amit Varma]: writing by hand and how technology has undermined it, I thought I'd bring it up and see if you

00:14:54.880 --> 00:14:55.880
[Guest]: have any thoughts.

00:14:55.880 --> 00:15:00.920
[Guest]: Yeah, you know, I've gone through a strange, although perhaps others have as well, but

00:15:00.920 --> 00:15:07.640
[Guest]: a strange kind of transition. I began by saying what most people say, I guess of my generation

00:15:07.640 --> 00:15:14.000
[Guest]: or somewhat younger, which is that I could only compose by writing log hand with pen

00:15:14.000 --> 00:15:19.560
[Guest]: and paper. And then I used to type it in the old days when there were typewriters, I couldn't

00:15:19.560 --> 00:15:24.160
[Guest]: compose in a typewriter. And when computers came, again, I wrote longhand. I remember

00:15:24.160 --> 00:15:30.240
[Guest]: most of my PhD initially was written by longhand back in the 80s. And then I tapped it all

00:15:30.240 --> 00:15:37.520
[Guest]: out on a computer. And I just couldn't think and compose properly unless I did longhand.

00:15:37.520 --> 00:15:43.240
[Guest]: Now I've got to the point where it's the reverse. I really can't do the handwriting. I can take

00:15:43.240 --> 00:15:49.320
[Guest]: notes handwriting. I can't really take notes typing stuff out, but I can only take notes

00:15:49.320 --> 00:15:57.600
[Guest]: handwritten. On the other hand, I can't now compose coherent text handwriting. My arm

00:15:57.600 --> 00:16:06.640
[Guest]: hurts, it gets squiggly. And I like now the white screen or the slightly yellow screen.

00:16:06.640 --> 00:16:14.120
[Guest]: I like the clickety-click of the keyboard. I bought one of those clackety old-fashioned

00:16:14.120 --> 00:16:18.200
[Guest]: keyboards, which are now newfangled keyboards, because I like the clickety-click and the

00:16:18.200 --> 00:16:25.720
[Guest]: pushback from the keys. So there was something tactile and noisy that I need now as a feedback

00:16:25.720 --> 00:16:33.320
[Guest]: or as a feeling when I compose. And I must say, so it's reversed for me. I do much better

00:16:33.320 --> 00:16:39.320
[Guest]: when I type out the text originally, and then just use handwritten notes as a supplement.

00:16:39.320 --> 00:16:41.440
[Guest]: So that's where I am.

00:16:41.440 --> 00:16:46.640
[Amit Varma]: And you've written so many books, you're a prolific columnist and essayist and so on.

00:16:46.640 --> 00:16:49.840
[Amit Varma]: You know, you mentioned the white screen, which often to me is like the white screen

00:16:49.840 --> 00:16:54.600
[Amit Varma]: of death, because so often I will, you know, sit down to write and it'll just be a struggle

00:16:54.600 --> 00:16:58.060
[Amit Varma]: and that clickety-clack of the keyboards, which you mentioned, is what I aspire to.

00:16:58.060 --> 00:17:02.120
[Amit Varma]: But I'm just sitting there and there's a white screen. And obviously, there are, you know,

00:17:02.120 --> 00:17:06.920
[Amit Varma]: various hacks, writers have to beat this. And I myself, when I teach my writing course,

00:17:06.920 --> 00:17:10.560
[Amit Varma]: perhaps a little hypocritically, because I don't know my own struggles so well, I tell

00:17:10.560 --> 00:17:14.160
[Amit Varma]: them about how, you know, most of the act of writing is just getting your butt on the

00:17:14.160 --> 00:17:20.000
[Amit Varma]: chair and just actually getting the work done. Tell me a little bit about your working habits,

00:17:20.000 --> 00:17:24.920
[Amit Varma]: because you know, when one writes, initially, I guess, there are, one has to deal with the

00:17:24.920 --> 00:17:29.080
[Amit Varma]: anxieties of what other people will think of your writing. And when you're a young scholar,

00:17:29.080 --> 00:17:32.760
[Amit Varma]: you want to impress others, and you have to get past that, and that can sometimes come

00:17:32.760 --> 00:17:38.440
[Amit Varma]: in the way. Later on, you have to handle things like the curse of knowledge, where, you know,

00:17:38.440 --> 00:17:41.520
[Amit Varma]: you know so much that you assume that is, you know, is this even worth writing about?

00:17:41.520 --> 00:17:45.640
[Amit Varma]: Surely everybody knows it? Am I stating the obvious? You know, which I would imagine will

00:17:45.640 --> 00:17:50.240
[Amit Varma]: happen to anyone in any field when they are so deep into it, that everything seems common

00:17:50.240 --> 00:17:54.080
[Amit Varma]: knowledge to them. So what's kind of your work ethic like? What are the problems you

00:17:54.080 --> 00:17:58.700
[Amit Varma]: have faced in your writing life? Like if one looks at your body of work, it's incredibly

00:17:58.700 --> 00:18:02.960
[Amit Varma]: impressive and one imagines that, oh, Mr. Bajpai just sits down and he just hammers

00:18:02.960 --> 00:18:06.920
[Amit Varma]: out book after book. But that's never the case, right? So tell me about the kind of

00:18:06.920 --> 00:18:11.600
[Amit Varma]: problems you faced, how you overcome them, and what your work ethic is like, like writing

00:18:11.600 --> 00:18:15.200
[Amit Varma]: this book, for example, during the pandemic, you knocked it off in three months, you've,

00:18:15.200 --> 00:18:18.560
[Amit Varma]: I think you mentioned that in, you know, in your episode with Milan Vaishnav on Grand

00:18:18.560 --> 00:18:22.960
[Amit Varma]: Tamasha, which I'll link from the show notes. So, you know, is that kind of your normal

00:18:22.960 --> 00:18:26.440
[Amit Varma]: process? Or is the normal process a little more drawn out and stuff?

00:18:26.440 --> 00:18:33.360
[Guest]: Yeah, you know, I think that I need to get going quickly. And if I postpone writing too

00:18:33.360 --> 00:18:39.520
[Guest]: much, if I think it over to too much, then it slows me down, it paralyzes me a bit. I

00:18:39.520 --> 00:18:45.000
[Guest]: think when I was an undergraduate in Canada, and, and a bit thereafter, I had this kind

00:18:45.000 --> 00:18:51.640
[Guest]: of sense that you really have to develop a full outline, fill in the subsectors of virtually

00:18:51.640 --> 00:18:57.160
[Guest]: every section. And then when you've got a grand scheme set up almost on a board in front

00:18:57.160 --> 00:19:03.520
[Guest]: of you with connective sort of lines and vectors, and got it all figured out, that's when you

00:19:03.520 --> 00:19:09.240
[Guest]: really get going. And you write very carefully, very systematically proceeding from A to B

00:19:09.240 --> 00:19:15.000
[Guest]: and end up at Z. And I think as an undergrad, in one paper, I remember, particularly in

00:19:15.000 --> 00:19:20.440
[Guest]: my English literature class, urged on by a friend of mine, a girlfriend of mine at the

00:19:20.440 --> 00:19:25.920
[Guest]: time, I tried to follow that I got the most miserable grade I ever got. And I just had

00:19:25.920 --> 00:19:31.940
[Guest]: a kind of moment there where I realized that I don't work that way, I have to kind of get

00:19:31.940 --> 00:19:38.600
[Guest]: into it and then amend and edit and change. And, and the faster I get to it, the more

00:19:38.600 --> 00:19:44.440
[Guest]: likely I'm to do something a bit more original, and actually finish it and, and probably do

00:19:44.440 --> 00:19:50.440
[Guest]: a fairly polished product. And when I got to grad school, I somewhat, that is for my

00:19:50.440 --> 00:19:57.560
[Guest]: PhD in America, I somewhat went back to that idea that I had to get everything worked out

00:19:57.560 --> 00:20:02.800
[Guest]: in toto before I began to write anything. And then I remember that there was a moment,

00:20:02.800 --> 00:20:06.680
[Guest]: well, partly under the stress of writing so much in American grad school, you couldn't

00:20:06.680 --> 00:20:11.920
[Guest]: quite afford to do that. But I remember a moment when it got to my thesis, where I was

00:20:11.920 --> 00:20:17.760
[Guest]: still somewhat struggling with, you know, these different models. And my late supervisor,

00:20:17.760 --> 00:20:24.840
[Guest]: now late supervisor, Steve Cohen, was remarkably productive, saying to me, look, Gandhi, you'll

00:20:24.840 --> 00:20:31.920
[Guest]: never finish the PhD if you don't figure out how to proceed, you know, efficiently. And

00:20:31.920 --> 00:20:37.000
[Guest]: he said, what I can teach you is not the substance of what you're going to write, but how to

00:20:37.000 --> 00:20:42.600
[Guest]: get this thing done. It's a finite task, you'll never write something that is the definitive

00:20:42.600 --> 00:20:47.760
[Guest]: work for all time. That's not how knowledge works. So throw that out of the window. Don't

00:20:47.760 --> 00:20:55.200
[Guest]: be a perfectionist. Write what you know, quickly and hard and fast. Don't stop writing. If

00:20:55.200 --> 00:21:01.440
[Guest]: you get stuck in one section, move on to the next one. Write every day, don't lose the

00:21:01.440 --> 00:21:09.640
[Guest]: momentum. Write ungrammatically, write dot points, write fluently and floridly when things

00:21:09.640 --> 00:21:14.840
[Guest]: are going well. You'll have to come back to those to edit and, you know, amend. Because

00:21:14.840 --> 00:21:20.080
[Guest]: what looks wonderful on Monday begins to look terrible on Wednesday, and be prepared to

00:21:20.080 --> 00:21:25.400
[Guest]: do that. And finally, he said, you know, when you got something done, and you're reasonably

00:21:25.400 --> 00:21:31.480
[Guest]: happy with it, put it away in a drawer for at least a week. If it's a substantial piece

00:21:31.480 --> 00:21:35.600
[Guest]: of writing, come back to it. In the meantime, go on to something else. And, you know, looking

00:21:35.600 --> 00:21:40.800
[Guest]: at his example and how productive he was, and he wrote brilliantly as well, I just decided

00:21:40.800 --> 00:21:45.520
[Guest]: I've got to give that a try. Plus, of course, you know, he said, if you don't give me the

00:21:45.520 --> 00:21:51.360
[Guest]: first chapter in the next week, you're out of this program. So I mean, you know, the

00:21:51.360 --> 00:21:56.640
[Guest]: prospect of a hanging concentrates your mind wonderfully, as Johnson said, and I wrote

00:21:56.640 --> 00:22:00.720
[Guest]: it in a week. And after that, I think I never looked back. By the way, I should say, you're

00:22:00.720 --> 00:22:06.320
[Guest]: very kind. I haven't written that many books at all. In fact, one of the stains on my record

00:22:06.320 --> 00:22:12.360
[Guest]: is that I co-wrote one book. The book you very kindly mentioned on Roots of Terrorism

00:22:12.360 --> 00:22:16.960
[Guest]: was written likewise in about four weeks in a fellowship in Australia. And this one was

00:22:16.960 --> 00:22:20.880
[Guest]: written in three months. I've edited a lot of books, and I've written chapters for books

00:22:20.880 --> 00:22:26.920
[Guest]: of other people and so on. But I'm a bit of a lazy guy that way. I mean, I need someone

00:22:26.920 --> 00:22:34.280
[Guest]: to really push me and slap me around and kick me in the pants. And I write a lot for friends.

00:22:34.280 --> 00:22:39.560
[Guest]: So if an academic friend says, oh, give me a chapter on this or write a piece for that,

00:22:39.560 --> 00:22:45.240
[Guest]: or even this book, Nandini Mehta, who was an old friend at Juggernaut, said, come on,

00:22:45.240 --> 00:22:50.400
[Guest]: Kanthi, I've asked you a couple of times, write this book quickly. It's time. And I

00:22:50.400 --> 00:22:54.320
[Guest]: wouldn't say I did it out of a sense of obligation. I did it out of a sense of friendship and

00:22:54.320 --> 00:23:00.080
[Guest]: not wanting to let her down one more time. So, you know, I'm a bit of an externally driven

00:23:00.080 --> 00:23:09.360
[Guest]: writer. If you get me by the throat and shake me up a bit and shame me, I'll write.

00:23:09.360 --> 00:23:13.320
[Amit Varma]: And that's pretty much the problem I face as well. If I have a deadline to give a column

00:23:13.320 --> 00:23:17.520
[Amit Varma]: by, I'll give it. But if I have to be like internally driven, it's a bit of a problem

00:23:17.520 --> 00:23:21.320
[Amit Varma]: though. I, you know, I keep telling my students, obviously about the, you know, the constant

00:23:21.320 --> 00:23:24.880
[Amit Varma]: trade off that everything involves between getting it done and getting it right. And

00:23:24.880 --> 00:23:28.640
[Amit Varma]: my point always is when it comes to the first draft, you have to get it done. You know,

00:23:28.640 --> 00:23:33.560
[Amit Varma]: getting it right is something that you do in subsequent edits and so on. Now, I'm also

00:23:33.560 --> 00:23:38.360
[Amit Varma]: intrigued by the notion that you moved away from the thought that you have to have everything

00:23:38.360 --> 00:23:43.240
[Amit Varma]: figured out before you write. And I'm reminded of this quote by the economist Deirdre McCloskey,

00:23:43.240 --> 00:23:46.560
[Amit Varma]: when she said, quote, don't wait until the research is done to begin writing because

00:23:46.560 --> 00:23:51.520
[Amit Varma]: writing is a way of thinking. Research is writing, stop quote, her italics, she italicized

00:23:51.520 --> 00:23:57.680
[Amit Varma]: is research is writing. Now, to what extent does writing and also teaching actually help

00:23:57.680 --> 00:24:02.000
[Amit Varma]: your thinking with the subject like one of the things I liked about this book and that,

00:24:02.000 --> 00:24:06.440
[Amit Varma]: you know, contributed to its lucidity was that there's a very clear framework through

00:24:06.440 --> 00:24:11.400
[Amit Varma]: which you are looking at India China relations, you know, the four P's as it were, which we'll

00:24:11.400 --> 00:24:15.840
[Amit Varma]: talk about in detail, you know, do you kind of begin with a framework does that sort of

00:24:15.840 --> 00:24:20.400
[Amit Varma]: framework or the way of looking at a problem that getting meta about a problem as it were

00:24:20.400 --> 00:24:25.320
[Amit Varma]: emerge while teaching while writing, and then you flesh it out? And do you think for that

00:24:25.320 --> 00:24:31.320
[Amit Varma]: reason that those who write more will inevitably be better thinkers and those who write less?

00:24:31.320 --> 00:24:36.400
[Amit Varma]: Because writing forces you to think that much more clearly and that much more deeply?

00:24:36.400 --> 00:24:42.160
[Guest]: Yeah, I think you've raised a lot of interesting issues there. For me, I mean, with this book,

00:24:42.160 --> 00:24:48.080
[Guest]: I know we'll get to it. But just in terms of the process, the publisher said, you know,

00:24:48.080 --> 00:24:52.200
[Guest]: write something that's for a general audience, first of all, so don't have a big, complicated

00:24:52.200 --> 00:24:57.080
[Guest]: theoretical framework that leads you into the subject and informs it and so on. But

00:24:57.080 --> 00:25:01.080
[Guest]: on the other hand, I realized that, you know, what I would end up with as a result, then

00:25:01.080 --> 00:25:06.080
[Guest]: might be just a long list of topics. And there are many things that are missing in the book,

00:25:06.080 --> 00:25:11.200
[Guest]: the river water problem, Pakistan as an issue between India and China, trade and financial

00:25:11.200 --> 00:25:15.160
[Guest]: relations between the countries. And they were all there in my original list. And I

00:25:15.160 --> 00:25:19.240
[Guest]: think juggernaut books probably hope that some of those would all be addressed in the

00:25:19.240 --> 00:25:25.440
[Guest]: book. But I realized fairly early on that I would just have a list. And I would knock

00:25:25.440 --> 00:25:30.400
[Guest]: off all these topics, for instance, also the whole issue of India, China in different regions,

00:25:30.400 --> 00:25:36.160
[Guest]: Southeast Asia, South Asia, Africa, Latin America. And, you know, first of all, I wouldn't

00:25:36.160 --> 00:25:41.840
[Guest]: meet the wordage. But secondly, it would just be a list. And so it seems to me that one

00:25:41.840 --> 00:25:46.840
[Guest]: of the things we're trained in an academic life, particularly is, you've got to try and

00:25:46.840 --> 00:25:51.760
[Guest]: develop some kind of an argument. And that can come from two places, although I think

00:25:51.760 --> 00:25:57.560
[Guest]: they're kind of linked. One place, you get your way knowing out of ideas is you go to

00:25:57.560 --> 00:26:04.400
[Guest]: theory. And you sort of say, well, what would theory expect us to think about in terms of

00:26:04.400 --> 00:26:09.960
[Guest]: the India, China relationship? Why they're in conflict? Why do they occasionally cooperate?

00:26:09.960 --> 00:26:14.160
[Guest]: And there are some answers there, obviously, from international relations theory. The other

00:26:14.160 --> 00:26:21.480
[Guest]: way is the other source of a sort of framework is to be a bit more inductive, bit more playful.

00:26:21.480 --> 00:26:26.240
[Guest]: From what you know, if you're immersed in the area that you're going to write about,

00:26:26.240 --> 00:26:32.160
[Guest]: you kind of throw up a set of topics, start to sort of group them and categorize them

00:26:32.160 --> 00:26:36.840
[Guest]: and see whether something emanates from that. Now, pure methodologists in academic life

00:26:36.840 --> 00:26:43.040
[Guest]: will tell you, never do that. Induction can never lead you to knowledge. But I think that's

00:26:43.040 --> 00:26:49.560
[Guest]: hogwash. And I think there's actually a dialectic between the two. Nobody is tabula rasa. We

00:26:49.560 --> 00:26:55.800
[Guest]: bring some theoretical assumptions, perspectives, arguments always to bear, because in a complex

00:26:55.800 --> 00:27:00.720
[Guest]: world, you wouldn't see the woods for the trees. You couldn't put one foot forward in

00:27:00.720 --> 00:27:04.920
[Guest]: front of the other, unless you had a theory of walking and where you're going. So you

00:27:04.920 --> 00:27:11.640
[Guest]: need some proto-theory, and we always already have it. But you also need to be a bit playful,

00:27:11.640 --> 00:27:16.800
[Guest]: and you're always receptive to experience the empirical test. Things are bubbling around

00:27:16.800 --> 00:27:22.840
[Guest]: you and they impact on your sense experience. They modify your theory. So in this book and

00:27:22.840 --> 00:27:29.120
[Guest]: in a lot of writing, I think I do what my supervisor did as well. He would say to me,

00:27:29.120 --> 00:27:35.400
[Guest]: just chuck out a bunch of initial ideas that you have, a set of topics, literally spread

00:27:35.400 --> 00:27:41.640
[Guest]: them out on the page with your pen and paper, your computer, and then start to sort of cohere

00:27:41.640 --> 00:27:48.200
[Guest]: them into boxes, into categories. And he always quoted, I think, Aristotle to me saying, Aristotle

00:27:48.200 --> 00:27:54.440
[Guest]: said that the first move in science is to put things in boxes. And I'm sure Indian forms

00:27:54.440 --> 00:28:00.480
[Guest]: of knowledge and so on would probably give you some similar, very sensible advice. And

00:28:00.480 --> 00:28:06.320
[Guest]: for me, I think I do go with that. I've got some working ideas. I don't work at them too

00:28:06.320 --> 00:28:12.400
[Guest]: much. I don't develop them too much. And then I throw out literally sort of a bunch of words

00:28:12.400 --> 00:28:16.920
[Guest]: on a piece of paper. And then I begin to cohere them. And I began to think of what kind of

00:28:16.920 --> 00:28:23.320
[Guest]: boxes are them and linkages between them. And how many of these can I really handle?

00:28:23.320 --> 00:28:28.520
[Guest]: How much of these make for some coherence? What will I have to throw out? Where is it

00:28:28.520 --> 00:28:32.680
[Guest]: too much work? And I'm simply not an expert enough. And it's not the kind of area I should

00:28:32.680 --> 00:28:36.920
[Guest]: delve into. Otherwise, I'd make a fool of myself, you know. And I think that's how the

00:28:36.920 --> 00:28:43.600
[Guest]: four P's emanated. And throughout a bunch of topics, I reworked stuff that Juggernaut

00:28:43.600 --> 00:28:50.400
[Guest]: had kind of pushed at me. And the four P's kind of popped up. And I tried to give them

00:28:50.400 --> 00:28:56.160
[Guest]: some clothing to link them up a bit more conceptually back with my discipline. Juggernaut didn't

00:28:56.160 --> 00:28:59.800
[Guest]: like it very much. They said it was a bit too much for the general reader. We had a

00:28:59.800 --> 00:29:05.320
[Guest]: friendly disagreement. But, you know, ultimately, for a general readership, I think their instinct

00:29:05.320 --> 00:29:10.480
[Guest]: was correct. And so I didn't elaborate these four P's and where they come from very much.

00:29:10.480 --> 00:29:15.000
[Guest]: I could probably do that if you push me, or even if you don't, and say a little bit about

00:29:15.000 --> 00:29:20.560
[Guest]: why I think they are the four important areas. And so I think that's how I operate in my

00:29:20.560 --> 00:29:24.880
[Guest]: writing. One other thing that you touched on, which is quite nice, and one that I insist

00:29:24.880 --> 00:29:30.360
[Guest]: on is the link between teaching and writing or research. And I think it's a very important

00:29:30.360 --> 00:29:36.560
[Guest]: one. Sometimes you hear from academic colleagues that, you know, there's teaching and, oh gosh,

00:29:36.560 --> 00:29:42.500
[Guest]: it's such a bore. And it takes time away from research. And I just don't buy that. My best

00:29:42.500 --> 00:29:50.400
[Guest]: ideas have come to me when I've taught and I've had to explain in the most direct, sensible,

00:29:50.400 --> 00:29:55.120
[Guest]: clear way to students, what are some of the fundamentals we're dealing with here? And

00:29:55.120 --> 00:30:02.160
[Guest]: I've understood my discipline better when I've done that. And so, and you know, when

00:30:02.160 --> 00:30:07.200
[Guest]: you do that, also, you kind of, when you're preparing slides or a lecture, you suddenly

00:30:07.200 --> 00:30:11.920
[Guest]: realize that there are enormous gaps in knowledge. You think that there are all kinds of handy

00:30:11.920 --> 00:30:16.040
[Guest]: dandy books and articles that will answer a certain question, and then you realize there

00:30:16.040 --> 00:30:20.560
[Guest]: aren't. And that indicates that there's a gap and an opportunity to write something.

00:30:20.560 --> 00:30:25.360
[Guest]: So I think that that's very important. But equally, research is very important to teaching,

00:30:25.360 --> 00:30:31.320
[Guest]: which is to say, the best moment in teaching is when you can bring to bear an area that

00:30:31.320 --> 00:30:37.860
[Guest]: you're mining in your research into the classroom. It just, you know, there's a, then a kind

00:30:37.860 --> 00:30:43.440
[Guest]: of authenticity to what you say and do and a richness to it. Students can feel that you

00:30:43.440 --> 00:30:49.360
[Guest]: have chewed on this and have really made sense of it. And I think they can feel the kind

00:30:49.360 --> 00:30:51.520
[Guest]: of passion and excitement you bring them.

00:30:51.520 --> 00:30:56.000
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, that's, that's fascinating. It's something I can relate to in the sense that, you know,

00:30:56.000 --> 00:30:59.760
[Amit Varma]: I felt that I began to understand writing better when I actually started teaching it

00:30:59.760 --> 00:31:04.280
[Amit Varma]: and not so much before that. And equally, when I taught podcasting as someone who actually

00:31:04.280 --> 00:31:09.120
[Amit Varma]: does a podcast, it just came that much more naturally and it also fed back. So it wasn't

00:31:09.120 --> 00:31:14.480
[Amit Varma]: just that my doing of podcasting helped my teaching of it. But while teaching it, I began

00:31:14.480 --> 00:31:19.160
[Amit Varma]: to think more at a meta level, for example, about the nature of interviewing and, you

00:31:19.160 --> 00:31:23.200
[Amit Varma]: know, the different kinds of approaches you can take to conversations and all of that,

00:31:23.200 --> 00:31:28.320
[Amit Varma]: which I think also helped my craft as a practitioner. Now, here's a question, when you write a book

00:31:28.320 --> 00:31:33.440
[Amit Varma]: and not just this book, but when you write any other book in a field where a lot of growth

00:31:33.440 --> 00:31:38.500
[Amit Varma]: in terms of knowledge is sort of incremental, you know, gradually the layers come over years

00:31:38.500 --> 00:31:44.420
[Amit Varma]: and decades and so on and so forth. It strikes me that there might be, therefore, two competing

00:31:44.420 --> 00:31:48.860
[Amit Varma]: pressures that you might face. And one pressure would be that I have to say something new

00:31:48.860 --> 00:31:53.060
[Amit Varma]: that I have to in some way, add to this body of knowledge, which could be dangerous because

00:31:53.060 --> 00:31:57.060
[Amit Varma]: it could lead to someone trying too hard, for example. Or there could be a pressure

00:31:57.060 --> 00:32:00.980
[Amit Varma]: which would probably, you know, maybe come from a publisher who might, you know, want

00:32:00.980 --> 00:32:04.740
[Amit Varma]: to pitch a book for the masses or whatever. And there the pressure might be that come

00:32:04.740 --> 00:32:09.900
[Amit Varma]: up with something definitive. Like if you're writing a book on India versus China, be definitive

00:32:09.900 --> 00:32:14.100
[Amit Varma]: about the why, be definitive about the what will happen going ahead, which of course you

00:32:14.100 --> 00:32:19.580
[Amit Varma]: can't, because it's incredibly messy and muddy. And, you know, every good scholar will have

00:32:19.580 --> 00:32:23.940
[Amit Varma]: that humility to accept that, especially in a field like this, that there is so much that

00:32:23.940 --> 00:32:28.660
[Amit Varma]: may never be known. How do you deal with these sort of competing pressures? Is this stuff

00:32:28.660 --> 00:32:32.740
[Amit Varma]: that you've thought about? Have you ever as a young academic, perhaps aired on one side

00:32:32.740 --> 00:32:33.740
[Guest]: or the other?

00:32:33.740 --> 00:32:42.180
[Guest]: I suppose I have. I mean, I increasingly have become kind of, what's the word? I mean, slightly,

00:32:42.180 --> 00:32:47.940
[Guest]: slightly more modest is the word that springs to mind right at the moment. And or moderate,

00:32:47.940 --> 00:32:53.300
[Guest]: in a way, a different way of saying it is, I've stopped taking myself so seriously. And

00:32:53.300 --> 00:33:00.820
[Guest]: what that means in the writing is that I'm committed to trying to present stuff clearly,

00:33:00.820 --> 00:33:05.620
[Guest]: use the word kindly about the book, Lucidity. And I think that's an important thing to do

00:33:05.620 --> 00:33:11.180
[Guest]: now more and more. And take the example of this book. I think those two pressures are

00:33:11.180 --> 00:33:17.340
[Guest]: exactly right, which is that on the one hand, as academics, we're always taught, you know,

00:33:17.340 --> 00:33:23.060
[Guest]: value add, look for something quite original that you're trying to say and communicate.

00:33:23.060 --> 00:33:27.220
[Guest]: Others don't bother. I mean, you're just adding to the noise in the system and overloading

00:33:27.220 --> 00:33:33.380
[Guest]: it. On the other hand, you know, I think the publishers set me a time limit, which meant

00:33:33.380 --> 00:33:38.620
[Guest]: that I couldn't do, you know, a very original research. I couldn't delve into some archival

00:33:38.620 --> 00:33:43.300
[Guest]: material that nobody else had touched or brought to light. I didn't have the time to come up

00:33:43.300 --> 00:33:48.300
[Guest]: with a grand theoretical proposition or a set of concepts that are used to interrogate

00:33:48.300 --> 00:33:53.500
[Guest]: relatively familiar materials and give us a different perspective on it. So I didn't

00:33:53.500 --> 00:33:58.900
[Guest]: have that leeway either. And so it seemed to me that, you know, I ought to kind of make

00:33:58.900 --> 00:34:06.780
[Guest]: a virtue out of all of these different constraints or opportunities and settle for the kind of

00:34:06.780 --> 00:34:12.940
[Guest]: book in a way that Juggernaut were urging on me, which is in three months, can I pull

00:34:12.940 --> 00:34:18.820
[Guest]: together quite a lot of stuff that's already out there that's quite well known and put

00:34:18.820 --> 00:34:25.940
[Guest]: it into some sort of a framework, nothing too revolutionary, nothing too rigorous and

00:34:25.940 --> 00:34:31.220
[Guest]: stringent intellectually such that I would have to get into very convoluted arguments

00:34:31.220 --> 00:34:37.340
[Guest]: about theories and concepts and to show that, you know, here was a brilliant new incision

00:34:37.340 --> 00:34:42.140
[Guest]: into the problem and a way of thinking about not just India-China relations, but perhaps

00:34:42.140 --> 00:34:47.860
[Guest]: all these kinds of enduring rivalries. So it seemed to me that I needed to strike a

00:34:47.860 --> 00:34:56.340
[Guest]: balance somewhere in between. And I think if the book has success, then it may have

00:34:56.340 --> 00:35:04.300
[Guest]: struck that balance. I pulled together relatively respectable, well-known materials already

00:35:04.300 --> 00:35:11.940
[Guest]: out there and pulled it into a simple framework, nothing too, too sophisticated. And that made

00:35:11.940 --> 00:35:17.780
[Guest]: it fairly quick and easy to write. I think it makes it, and it may solve your problem

00:35:17.780 --> 00:35:23.780
[Guest]: of someday remembering something about this book. The four Ps may stain your brain for

00:35:23.780 --> 00:35:29.660
[Guest]: a while. And I think, you know, that might allow me to clothe the material in a way that

00:35:29.660 --> 00:35:35.460
[Guest]: was easy on the eye of the beholder. I mean, I could dress in a very jazzy way when I go

00:35:35.460 --> 00:35:42.060
[Guest]: out. But if you dress simply, perhaps the image of you walking around will endure. So

00:35:42.060 --> 00:35:49.540
[Guest]: I think I tried to use the four Ps idea to make it simpler for a reader and yet provide

00:35:49.540 --> 00:35:55.220
[Guest]: some kind of a scaffolding with which to arrange the empirical materials.

00:35:55.220 --> 00:36:00.300
[Amit Varma]: Yeah. And you've absolutely succeeded in that in my view, but we'll talk about that as we

00:36:00.300 --> 00:36:04.700
[Amit Varma]: go along. Let's go back to your personal history, which is also very fascinating because you

00:36:04.700 --> 00:36:08.860
[Amit Varma]: are the son of a diplomat. You know, your father was a very famous diplomat, Girija

00:36:08.860 --> 00:36:14.260
[Amit Varma]: Shankar Bajpai, who, you know, that's your grandfather. Sorry, that's what I meant. Yeah.

00:36:14.260 --> 00:36:19.580
[Amit Varma]: And a famous photograph of him with Nehru as well at a 1948 conference and so on. And

00:36:19.580 --> 00:36:22.980
[Amit Varma]: you travel the world, like in your book, you've written about how, you know, when the China

00:36:22.980 --> 00:36:28.380
[Amit Varma]: War happened in 62, you were in London and it was cold and you were freezing. And that

00:36:28.380 --> 00:36:34.820
[Amit Varma]: strikes me as, you know, traveling around the world and all of that as a very consequential

00:36:34.820 --> 00:36:39.980
[Amit Varma]: childhood to have, because it means you are different from all the other kids your age

00:36:39.980 --> 00:36:44.060
[Amit Varma]: at that point. And one can speculate about why that may be the case. Maybe you are less

00:36:44.060 --> 00:36:49.260
[Amit Varma]: ossified in your ways of thinking about your people and other people and so on. Maybe there's

00:36:49.260 --> 00:36:54.860
[Amit Varma]: a natural sense of curiosity that can evolve from there and so on and so forth. So, you

00:36:54.860 --> 00:36:59.540
[Amit Varma]: know, looking back, what was your childhood like? And is there something to the sense

00:36:59.540 --> 00:37:04.780
[Amit Varma]: that you feel that it shaped you differently from what it would have, say, had you just

00:37:04.780 --> 00:37:06.580
[Guest]: grown up in Delhi, for example?

00:37:06.580 --> 00:37:12.420
[Guest]: Yeah, so I'm a diplomat's kid, foreign service brat. And I think those kids all over the

00:37:12.420 --> 00:37:18.000
[Guest]: world from whichever foreign service they're in, they do tend to be more ecumenical, perhaps

00:37:18.000 --> 00:37:23.620
[Guest]: more liberal is the word or cosmopolitan. I think through their schooling as they move

00:37:23.620 --> 00:37:29.820
[Guest]: around with their parents, inevitably, they're forced to look through other worldviews. You

00:37:29.820 --> 00:37:36.020
[Guest]: go to school, you encounter foreigners, you in part take on their worldviews inevitably,

00:37:36.020 --> 00:37:40.420
[Guest]: and see the world through their eyes as well. Curiously, of course, the other side of it

00:37:40.420 --> 00:37:49.260
[Guest]: is that as a diplomat's kid, you're also immersed in your nationalism, your country perspective,

00:37:49.260 --> 00:37:54.700
[Guest]: around the dinner table with your parents, your siblings, the other kids in the embassy,

00:37:54.700 --> 00:38:00.260
[Guest]: the other members of the embassy. There's a very Indian kind of, you know, national

00:38:00.260 --> 00:38:07.060
[Guest]: environment as well. And there's that lens simultaneously. So I think the thing with

00:38:07.060 --> 00:38:15.180
[Guest]: diplomat's kids is that from almost the day of mother's milk, they're always bifocal,

00:38:15.180 --> 00:38:20.500
[Guest]: always looking through things through that national lens, which they're immersed in,

00:38:20.500 --> 00:38:27.060
[Guest]: and their heart beats to it. But they're also constantly encountering other views, how others

00:38:27.060 --> 00:38:32.260
[Guest]: see us, how others see our country, how others see other countries, third countries, and

00:38:32.260 --> 00:38:37.460
[Guest]: of course, their own country. And you as a diplomat's son have a certain perspective

00:38:37.460 --> 00:38:43.500
[Guest]: on the host country. And then you get a picture of the host country refracted through the

00:38:43.500 --> 00:38:49.500
[Guest]: lens of the citizens of that country that you encounter. I think diplomat's kids are

00:38:49.500 --> 00:38:56.180
[Guest]: like that. And they have to be open to that. I mean, they have to fit in in both environments

00:38:56.180 --> 00:39:01.780
[Guest]: and make sense of both environments constantly. So they're constantly testing reality against

00:39:01.780 --> 00:39:07.980
[Guest]: both these lenses. And I mean, I think it's a good thing. I mean, I don't mean to say

00:39:07.980 --> 00:39:14.020
[Guest]: that those who haven't had that opportunity don't have their own kind of strength, perhaps

00:39:14.020 --> 00:39:19.780
[Guest]: are more unifocal and know what they know and are not easily deflected and have great

00:39:19.780 --> 00:39:24.100
[Guest]: certainty about things that they do and think. And we need people like that in the world

00:39:24.100 --> 00:39:30.260
[Guest]: as well. But we also need people who want to roll things around their tongue, who want

00:39:30.260 --> 00:39:36.880
[Guest]: to be more playful, who want to be experimental intellectually. I mean, I don't mean to say

00:39:36.880 --> 00:39:41.060
[Guest]: that I'm the most creative human being in the world by any means because of this upbringing.

00:39:41.060 --> 00:39:46.180
[Guest]: I wouldn't say that's true. And there are other forces that operate on that issue. But

00:39:46.180 --> 00:39:53.260
[Guest]: I think my reflexive starting point, as it were, is that I don't like to go with the

00:39:53.260 --> 00:40:00.940
[Guest]: herd, with any herd. And I'm always, my antenna always go up when people are too insistent

00:40:00.940 --> 00:40:06.940
[Guest]: on a singular point of view. And I think that, you know, that was a bit of a struggle for

00:40:06.940 --> 00:40:12.860
[Guest]: me in my childhood. The first 11 years or so, my parents were outside India. They continued

00:40:12.860 --> 00:40:18.340
[Guest]: to be, but they did feel when I was 11 years old that I had to come back to India and be

00:40:18.340 --> 00:40:25.900
[Guest]: in an Indian environment, partly because they felt that I was losing touch with Indian reality

00:40:25.900 --> 00:40:31.500
[Guest]: and also because they were moving around constantly and the schools were, you know, an unsettling

00:40:31.500 --> 00:40:35.380
[Guest]: experience if you keep moving schools every three or four years. And so I went back to

00:40:35.380 --> 00:40:39.620
[Guest]: boarding school in Delhi and then Dehradun. And I think it was a fabulous thing that my

00:40:39.620 --> 00:40:47.100
[Guest]: parents did. And so I had an upbringing as a diplomat's kid where I sort of was raised

00:40:47.100 --> 00:40:53.420
[Guest]: to be uncomfortable with herd mentalities, with givens, with an orthodoxy. And I think

00:40:53.420 --> 00:40:58.580
[Guest]: that's remained with me. When I started out in more public life as an academic on television

00:40:58.580 --> 00:41:04.460
[Guest]: in the eighties and nineties, when I was pretty active in Delhi, you know, I exited into a

00:41:04.460 --> 00:41:09.140
[Guest]: period when I was very certain about stuff. And I argued very stringently about things

00:41:09.140 --> 00:41:15.340
[Guest]: like India's nuclear weapons options and so on. I think actually after that period, an

00:41:15.340 --> 00:41:20.380
[Guest]: intermittent phase of being so singular, I've come back to now rolling things around my

00:41:20.380 --> 00:41:28.300
[Guest]: tongue, I think a bit more. And that's recovering that sort of diploma early, early immersion

00:41:28.300 --> 00:41:30.780
[Guest]: in this bifocal world that I grew up in.

00:41:30.780 --> 00:41:35.620
[Amit Varma]: So just just sort of thinking aloud. I mean, this brings me to another sort of question

00:41:35.620 --> 00:41:39.700
[Amit Varma]: that often strikes me, like when I look at young people growing up today, so many of

00:41:39.700 --> 00:41:45.020
[Amit Varma]: them choose to do all their thinking and their talking and their posturing and whatever it

00:41:45.020 --> 00:41:49.060
[Amit Varma]: is in public, which strikes me as something dangerous, because, you know, if everything

00:41:49.060 --> 00:41:53.700
[Amit Varma]: that I thought or wrote in my teens or twenties was, you know, on Twitter, and people took

00:41:53.700 --> 00:41:58.220
[Amit Varma]: screenshots and all of that, one, of course, it would not be fair, because young people

00:41:58.220 --> 00:42:02.060
[Amit Varma]: need that kind of space to grow up and change their mind and roll things on their tongue

00:42:02.060 --> 00:42:07.140
[Amit Varma]: as you put it so well. But the other thing that it can do is that it can ossify you into

00:42:07.140 --> 00:42:11.820
[Amit Varma]: positions, like when you're 17 or 18, you might go online, you might find a tribe, and

00:42:11.820 --> 00:42:15.340
[Amit Varma]: you might join that tribe, and you're part of an echo chamber. And then you raise your

00:42:15.340 --> 00:42:20.740
[Amit Varma]: status within that echo chamber with harsher and harsher pronouncements and, you know,

00:42:20.740 --> 00:42:25.020
[Amit Varma]: by signaling virtue more vociferously than the next guy and so on and so forth. And because

00:42:25.020 --> 00:42:30.540
[Amit Varma]: you take those chances, you start believing them, they become much harder than they would

00:42:30.540 --> 00:42:36.800
[Amit Varma]: otherwise have been. And to me, that strikes me as a danger and a shame that like once

00:42:36.800 --> 00:42:41.020
[Amit Varma]: you write something down definitively, once you identify yourself with a certain way of

00:42:41.020 --> 00:42:46.420
[Amit Varma]: thinking, then you change, you change to the extent that you're more likely to hold on

00:42:46.420 --> 00:42:51.980
[Amit Varma]: to that. And so do you think that that's a danger in these modern times where a position

00:42:51.980 --> 00:42:56.380
[Amit Varma]: once taken actually ends up shaping who you are, like in your case, you said, you know,

00:42:56.380 --> 00:43:00.060
[Amit Varma]: you had more certainty about certain positions in the 80s or whatever, when you would be

00:43:00.060 --> 00:43:04.340
[Amit Varma]: on television as a talking head, but those clips don't exist on YouTube, right? People

00:43:04.340 --> 00:43:08.940
[Amit Varma]: are not going to put screenshots of your old article saying, hey, you said this in 1983.

00:43:08.940 --> 00:43:14.420
[Amit Varma]: So you have any thoughts on the changing times and how they can change a person's development

00:43:14.420 --> 00:43:18.060
[Amit Varma]: of self even because you're just so much more out there?

00:43:18.060 --> 00:43:24.820
[Guest]: Yeah, isn't it an irony that this technology that came along of the social media and all

00:43:24.820 --> 00:43:31.980
[Guest]: of that, and the unending, limitless kind of memory now with cloud and so on that's

00:43:31.980 --> 00:43:38.520
[Guest]: there, I suppose the promise was that this would lead to kind of enormous liberalization

00:43:38.520 --> 00:43:43.020
[Guest]: of thought that people would be able to express themselves who otherwise would not be able

00:43:43.020 --> 00:43:46.700
[Guest]: to because they couldn't write a column for a newspaper. They wouldn't be asked on television

00:43:46.700 --> 00:43:50.940
[Guest]: as a talking head, but now they can. I mean, because there's so many platforms where they

00:43:50.940 --> 00:43:57.440
[Guest]: can be heard. And so I guess, I mean, I went along with that thought that there's something

00:43:57.440 --> 00:44:03.300
[Guest]: greatly liberalizing that would happen as a result of this. Although I wasn't much until

00:44:03.300 --> 00:44:09.460
[Guest]: very recently on social media platforms or any of those kinds of instruments. But it's

00:44:09.460 --> 00:44:16.100
[Guest]: turned out that, as you say, I mean, they've become kind of silos, echo chambers. They've

00:44:16.100 --> 00:44:22.700
[Guest]: become platforms for insulting people. And when you insult someone, I mean, there are

00:44:22.700 --> 00:44:26.940
[Guest]: a couple of reactions. One is they could exit the system, though that seems to be quite

00:44:26.940 --> 00:44:34.460
[Guest]: hard to do. You just become aloof and exit. The other is that, you know, you fight back

00:44:34.460 --> 00:44:40.820
[Guest]: and you fight back, you dig in to your point of view even more stringently and become more

00:44:40.820 --> 00:44:49.300
[Guest]: stubborn and lose your plasticity and openness to disconfirming facts or to alternative perspectives.

00:44:49.300 --> 00:44:54.260
[Guest]: And the third, of course, is that, you know, you do sort of on the platforms themselves,

00:44:54.260 --> 00:45:03.020
[Guest]: you know, show that you can change your mind and change over time, more or less. And I

00:45:03.020 --> 00:45:10.500
[Guest]: think that it seems to me that all three are quite difficult. But I would like to think

00:45:10.500 --> 00:45:16.620
[Guest]: that I would try and do the third, which is try to signal that if you do make a point

00:45:16.620 --> 00:45:22.100
[Guest]: about my work or something I've just said, which holds promise of even a critique of

00:45:22.100 --> 00:45:27.020
[Guest]: me, that I'm open to it. And, you know, I went on Twitter when this book was coming

00:45:27.020 --> 00:45:33.180
[Guest]: online because Jagannath said, come on, Kanthi, you've got to just get out there and move

00:45:33.180 --> 00:45:37.900
[Guest]: with the times. And of course, it's good for the book and your ideas. And I've already

00:45:37.900 --> 00:45:43.020
[Guest]: had people challenge me, sometimes dismissively, sometimes slightly insultingly, sometimes

00:45:43.020 --> 00:45:50.420
[Guest]: generously, but with disagreement. And I think one has to deal with that. And I hope it hasn't

00:45:50.420 --> 00:45:55.620
[Guest]: been huge, but I've tried to deal with it by sort of saying, yeah, you may have something

00:45:55.620 --> 00:46:01.820
[Guest]: there. The book was a first cut at this problem. It's not the last cut on the problem. It's

00:46:01.820 --> 00:46:06.340
[Guest]: not the definitive word. And by the way, what is a definitive word in, you know, in such

00:46:06.340 --> 00:46:11.540
[Guest]: a complicated world? But if it's provoking and fostering a conversation, as long as we

00:46:11.540 --> 00:46:16.860
[Guest]: keep it more or less polite, let's proceed. So I think, you know, to my mind, we're stuck

00:46:16.860 --> 00:46:20.260
[Guest]: with these platforms. I mean, whether we like it or not, I don't think we're going to resile

00:46:20.260 --> 00:46:25.660
[Guest]: and move away from them very much. And there's something emancipatory and celebratory about

00:46:25.660 --> 00:46:32.180
[Guest]: them. And I think we have to work our way through to a place where some of the really

00:46:32.180 --> 00:46:41.140
[Guest]: dark tonalities will reduce. And people will learn that, you know, insulting, terribly

00:46:41.140 --> 00:46:47.460
[Guest]: stubborn kinds of sticking to your points of view, being dismissive about others, really

00:46:47.460 --> 00:46:53.100
[Guest]: it just doesn't work. And I still have that positive progressive view that dialogue in

00:46:53.100 --> 00:46:57.020
[Guest]: itself, they'll be learning from it. And I think, you know, I'm just getting a sense

00:46:57.020 --> 00:47:01.700
[Guest]: in the last few months that I've been on Twitter, that something like that is already perhaps

00:47:01.700 --> 00:47:06.940
[Guest]: beginning to happen. And the last point I would make is that, you know, I mean, nobody

00:47:06.940 --> 00:47:12.220
[Guest]: can be consistent over their entire lifetime, and it would be idiotic to be so. I think

00:47:12.220 --> 00:47:17.420
[Guest]: that was addressed to Gandhi on his, you know, his change of view of violence and war and

00:47:17.420 --> 00:47:23.700
[Guest]: his participation. You know, back in the day, he had come out in favor of recruiting troops

00:47:23.700 --> 00:47:27.660
[Guest]: for the British cause in the early part of the 20th century. He had tried to recruit

00:47:27.660 --> 00:47:34.420
[Guest]: people for the Boer War. He had, you know, participated as an ambulance person in the

00:47:34.420 --> 00:47:40.940
[Guest]: First World War, I think, or the Boer War. So people said to him, well, I mean, back

00:47:40.940 --> 00:47:44.860
[Guest]: then you did that. And now you're preaching nonviolent, you're not consistent. And, you

00:47:44.860 --> 00:47:51.100
[Guest]: know, he said, Yeah, I mean, I'm not consistent. Times change, I change. Why would you expect

00:47:51.100 --> 00:47:56.220
[Guest]: me to be consistent? And I think Keynes said it more. Was it Keynes who said something

00:47:56.220 --> 00:47:57.220
[Amit Varma]: like, you know,

00:47:57.220 --> 00:48:00.380
[Amit Varma]: Keynes, if the facts change, I change my mind. So what do you do?

00:48:00.380 --> 00:48:06.180
[Guest]: Yeah, well done. I mean, you said it much. Yeah, that's exactly. And I usually push that

00:48:06.180 --> 00:48:10.940
[Guest]: out there as well. So I think that's a useful thing to say.

00:48:10.940 --> 00:48:15.260
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, no, I think you've kind of largely had a sort of a lucky experience on Twitter, because

00:48:15.260 --> 00:48:18.940
[Amit Varma]: a lot of your interactions would kind of be self selected, like people who are a already

00:48:18.940 --> 00:48:23.320
[Amit Varma]: interested in your work, and therefore a certain kind of person and be when you follow a lot

00:48:23.320 --> 00:48:27.100
[Amit Varma]: of scholars you admire, they follow you back, you're kind of curating your feed, I think

00:48:27.100 --> 00:48:31.340
[Amit Varma]: one of the essential ways of tackling Twitter is curate your feed very carefully. And you

00:48:31.340 --> 00:48:36.040
[Amit Varma]: can get enormous insight and have great conversations that way. But by and large, the other thing

00:48:36.040 --> 00:48:39.780
[Amit Varma]: that I noticed about Twitter, which is interesting is that, you know, we tend to think that the

00:48:39.780 --> 00:48:44.140
[Amit Varma]: whole space is incredibly toxic. Now, the truth is that there are these vocal minorities

00:48:44.140 --> 00:48:48.620
[Amit Varma]: who are incredibly toxic, because they are caught in these echo chambers and always posturing

00:48:48.620 --> 00:48:52.940
[Amit Varma]: and so on. But there's a vast silent majority, which is not like that at all, which is something

00:48:52.940 --> 00:48:57.500
[Amit Varma]: that I realized through my podcast and through the courses that I've done where, you know,

00:48:57.500 --> 00:49:01.540
[Amit Varma]: I popularize them through Twitter, people sign on you, you realize what those people

00:49:01.540 --> 00:49:05.380
[Amit Varma]: are like, and then you look on Twitter where everyone is shouting. And I'm kind of baffled

00:49:05.380 --> 00:49:10.980
[Amit Varma]: by just the fundamental rudeness that Twitter brings to the discourse, like the act of quote

00:49:10.980 --> 00:49:14.900
[Amit Varma]: tweeting, for example, where you quote tweet someone and you mock them. And that's so incredibly

00:49:14.900 --> 00:49:18.900
[Amit Varma]: rude. Because you know, if you and I were talking at a party, and I said something that

00:49:18.900 --> 00:49:23.980
[Amit Varma]: you disagreed with, you would not immediately turn to our neighbor and point at me and say,

00:49:23.980 --> 00:49:28.420
[Amit Varma]: look, this guy is a fool. This guy is a moron. He's saying this. That's just so incredibly

00:49:28.420 --> 00:49:33.040
[Amit Varma]: rude. It's so bizarre, you know, that we have to not take anything in good faith at all.

00:49:33.040 --> 00:49:37.540
[Amit Varma]: But this is a digression. Why should we talk about these times where we still have the

00:49:37.540 --> 00:49:41.620
[Amit Varma]: past to talk about? So tell me a little bit more about your childhood. Did you like to

00:49:41.620 --> 00:49:46.060
[Amit Varma]: read you studied at Doon School also for a while? What was that like? Because on the

00:49:46.060 --> 00:49:49.420
[Amit Varma]: one hand, you pointed out that your parents wanted you to be back home because they felt

00:49:49.420 --> 00:49:54.640
[Amit Varma]: that you were being away from the realities of India as it were. Now, when I look back

00:49:54.640 --> 00:49:59.220
[Amit Varma]: on my also privileged childhood as a son of a civil servant, although I didn't live all

00:49:59.220 --> 00:50:03.220
[Amit Varma]: over the world in India itself, but nevertheless massively privileged childhood and going

00:50:03.220 --> 00:50:08.940
[Amit Varma]: to good schools and so on. And as I grew into adulthood, I realized what a blinkered view

00:50:08.940 --> 00:50:14.100
[Amit Varma]: of the world I had been given just by, you know, the occasion of my privilege that okay,

00:50:14.100 --> 00:50:19.540
[Amit Varma]: I am the child of these people. You know, I'm using my dad's car to go here or to go

00:50:19.540 --> 00:50:24.020
[Amit Varma]: there. This is the kind of school I am everyone else is also incredibly pampered kid. And

00:50:24.020 --> 00:50:29.060
[Amit Varma]: this is like one view of India from one particular vantage point. And you kind of grow older

00:50:29.060 --> 00:50:35.020
[Amit Varma]: each adulthood and, and you realize that there's so much more to this. And so one what was

00:50:35.020 --> 00:50:41.260
[Amit Varma]: Doon School like and two, I presume that everyone you studied with at the time would be present

00:50:41.260 --> 00:50:45.700
[Amit Varma]: day elites. Like I did an episode with Ramchandra Guha where he told me about his time in college

00:50:45.700 --> 00:50:52.500
[Amit Varma]: in Delhi where his classmates, his list of classmates is like a who's who of, you know,

00:50:52.500 --> 00:50:56.780
[Amit Varma]: India today, a small group of people. So tell me a bit about that experience and how your

00:50:56.780 --> 00:51:00.980
[Amit Varma]: thinking kind of evolves through that. And then we'll move on to your personal journey

00:51:00.980 --> 00:51:03.140
[Amit Varma]: and you know, what you studied and all of that.

00:51:03.140 --> 00:51:08.780
[Guest]: Well, first of all, Ram Guha was with me at school at Doon School. He was one year behind

00:51:08.780 --> 00:51:14.620
[Guest]: me. And there you are. So, but I think that, you know, first of all, when I came back to

00:51:14.620 --> 00:51:20.380
[Guest]: India, I went to St. Xavier's School in Delhi, in Civil Lines in Delhi. It had a boarding

00:51:20.380 --> 00:51:25.040
[Guest]: section in those days, and quite a number of diplomats kids, Indian Foreign Service

00:51:25.040 --> 00:51:30.220
[Guest]: kids were there. And that's where I started out. Although my father was a Doon School

00:51:30.220 --> 00:51:34.380
[Guest]: boy. In fact, he was the first school captain of the school. So, you know, I had a link

00:51:34.380 --> 00:51:38.320
[Guest]: to the school, my brother had been there, my uncles had been there, but my father didn't

00:51:38.320 --> 00:51:44.580
[Guest]: actually send me there. He was posted to Pakistan at that time in the deputy high commissionership

00:51:44.580 --> 00:51:50.820
[Guest]: of in Karachi. And he would come to Delhi periodically. And he thought that my transition

00:51:50.820 --> 00:51:55.820
[Guest]: back to India along with my two elder brothers and my younger sister, that he would see us

00:51:55.820 --> 00:52:00.980
[Guest]: occasionally and that would help us transition back to Indian life. So I was in St. Xavier's

00:52:00.980 --> 00:52:06.500
[Guest]: for three and a half years. And when they decided to close the boarding, he then petitioned

00:52:06.500 --> 00:52:12.380
[Guest]: Doon School to take me because I joined the school quite late in comparison to other boys.

00:52:12.380 --> 00:52:15.840
[Guest]: So I think the experience of the two schools were very different. I mean, St. Xavier's was

00:52:15.840 --> 00:52:22.660
[Guest]: basically a huge day school with this little boarding element. And as you know, it's a

00:52:22.660 --> 00:52:28.380
[Guest]: Jesuit school. So there was a very, very different kind of atmosphere. I wouldn't say it was

00:52:28.380 --> 00:52:33.340
[Guest]: a religious atmosphere in the sense of, you know, we all had to keep to sort of Catholic

00:52:33.340 --> 00:52:37.300
[Guest]: orthodoxies or anything like that. It wasn't shoved down our throat. Although there was

00:52:37.300 --> 00:52:41.340
[Guest]: an evening prayer and you could say it or you could just hold your hands and say your

00:52:41.340 --> 00:52:48.660
[Guest]: own prayer quietly and so on. But I think, you know, there was studying and there was

00:52:48.660 --> 00:52:55.540
[Guest]: a bit of stuff on the sports field and that was pretty much your life. And it was very

00:52:55.540 --> 00:53:01.520
[Guest]: disciplined in the sense that every moment of your day was metered and clearly your studies

00:53:01.520 --> 00:53:08.120
[Guest]: were the primary thing. And the students there, they were all mostly kids from Delhi who for

00:53:08.120 --> 00:53:12.260
[Guest]: one reason or another, you know, couldn't be day students. Maybe they lived too far

00:53:12.260 --> 00:53:17.300
[Guest]: away in Delhi. They were people from outside Delhi, but from in and around Delhi, not very

00:53:17.300 --> 00:53:23.380
[Guest]: far away. Some diplomat's kids as well. But Dhoon School was very different. And, you

00:53:23.380 --> 00:53:28.260
[Guest]: know, I think we think that, and there's a view, popular view, that Dhoon School, Mayo

00:53:28.260 --> 00:53:34.140
[Guest]: College, Ajmer, Sindhia School in Gwalior, these so-called public schools, they're the

00:53:34.140 --> 00:53:41.340
[Guest]: Baba Lok school. But actually the picture is rather different. It's the big day schools

00:53:41.340 --> 00:53:47.680
[Guest]: that are the Baba Lok schools, because the big business guys, the very senior civil servants,

00:53:47.680 --> 00:53:53.940
[Guest]: the politicians' kids, they tend to go to the big day schools, Modern School in Delhi,

00:53:53.940 --> 00:54:01.220
[Guest]: St. Columbus, St. Xavier's in Bombay, Campion and schools like that. Whereas the kids who

00:54:01.220 --> 00:54:06.540
[Guest]: go to Dhoon School or Mayo College, these are people who are from the second and third

00:54:06.540 --> 00:54:12.300
[Guest]: tier towns mostly of India. And in Dhoon School, they are mostly from the second and third

00:54:12.300 --> 00:54:19.820
[Guest]: tier towns of UP, now Uttarakhand as well, Haryana, Punjab, sometimes from Bihar, UP,

00:54:19.820 --> 00:54:26.800
[Guest]: Madhya Pradesh, some kids from Southern India, and later some students from Northeast India.

00:54:26.800 --> 00:54:33.220
[Guest]: But Delhi Party, so-called, or Bombay Party or Calcutta Party, these were really a distinct

00:54:33.220 --> 00:54:40.660
[Guest]: minority of the school. And the reason for that is that it was the students from these

00:54:40.660 --> 00:54:46.220
[Guest]: small towns, Saharanpur, places like that, Bhatinda, et cetera, et cetera, who didn't

00:54:46.220 --> 00:54:51.940
[Guest]: have a lot of facilities, whose local schools weren't necessarily all that great. And these

00:54:51.940 --> 00:54:58.220
[Guest]: second, third tier elites who wanted to give their kids an imprimatur, a better school

00:54:58.220 --> 00:55:05.540
[Guest]: experience as well, then looked to boarding schools like Dhoon School. And so actually,

00:55:05.540 --> 00:55:11.540
[Guest]: most of the students, even in my time, I wouldn't say they were the greatest elite types. There

00:55:11.540 --> 00:55:16.540
[Guest]: were some Maharaja's kids, there were some big business kids, there were some senior

00:55:16.540 --> 00:55:22.140
[Guest]: civil servants kids, but there were a lot of kids from small businesses or farmers'

00:55:22.140 --> 00:55:27.700
[Guest]: children. I mean, I don't mean small farmers, but medium-sized farmer families and so on

00:55:27.700 --> 00:55:33.400
[Guest]: and so forth. People who were in second and third tier towns from services backgrounds,

00:55:33.400 --> 00:55:39.060
[Guest]: that is to say they provided some service locally, the tea estates in Assam and so on.

00:55:39.060 --> 00:55:44.060
[Guest]: And actually, that's grown. When I was headmaster of the school, we did a survey of the kinds

00:55:44.060 --> 00:55:49.020
[Guest]: of students. And I can tell you that most of the children overwhelmingly were from the

00:55:49.020 --> 00:55:55.780
[Guest]: second and third tier towns. And contrary to the view, I would say a very large proportion,

00:55:55.780 --> 00:56:01.220
[Guest]: more so than when I was at the school as a boy, were comfortable in Hindi primarily.

00:56:01.220 --> 00:56:04.860
[Guest]: And certainly their parents were more comfortable in Hindi. I would say more than 50% of the

00:56:04.860 --> 00:56:09.100
[Guest]: kids at Dhoon School, their parents would be more comfortable in expressing themselves

00:56:09.100 --> 00:56:15.100
[Guest]: in Hindi. And so that was one part of the school that it actually wasn't that Babalu

00:56:15.100 --> 00:56:21.620
[Guest]: elite mostly. And I think the other thing was about Dhoon School was that it forced

00:56:21.620 --> 00:56:26.940
[Guest]: you out of, I mean, of course, the school is a gated community, but you have to get

00:56:26.940 --> 00:56:33.020
[Guest]: out and live your life also in Dehradun on outings, for instance. And it's not Delhi.

00:56:33.020 --> 00:56:39.080
[Guest]: The school has no amenities of the kind that you have in the big cities. I mean, in those

00:56:39.080 --> 00:56:44.620
[Guest]: days in Dehradun, and even until recently, there were no malls, there were no multiplexes,

00:56:44.620 --> 00:56:49.980
[Guest]: there was certainly no discos and all of that. And the other experience was that particular

00:56:49.980 --> 00:56:54.780
[Guest]: to Dhoon School was that from the beginning, thanks to the first two headmasters we had

00:56:54.780 --> 00:57:00.340
[Guest]: and the Indian teachers of the time, they insisted on two things that forced you out

00:57:00.340 --> 00:57:08.060
[Guest]: into the community. One was from the beginning, what later got to be called in India, SUPW,

00:57:08.060 --> 00:57:11.980
[Guest]: Essentially Useful Productive Work. And I think it was probably pretty much started

00:57:11.980 --> 00:57:16.900
[Guest]: at Dhoon School and a few other schools like that, which is, there was an insistence that

00:57:16.900 --> 00:57:22.940
[Guest]: the students had to go out and do community work in villages in particular. And that was

00:57:22.940 --> 00:57:26.740
[Guest]: a requirement of the school, you had a little logbook, and you had to write down how much

00:57:26.740 --> 00:57:30.940
[Guest]: of that you did, you could do some of that within the school as well. But quite a lot

00:57:30.940 --> 00:57:38.300
[Guest]: of it was going out into the community. The second was that every term for five days,

00:57:38.300 --> 00:57:44.300
[Guest]: you had to go trekking in the hills. And you went to very remote places and locales from

00:57:44.300 --> 00:57:51.340
[Guest]: Dehradun northwards. And I mean, I don't want to oversell it as a kind of foray into ordinary

00:57:51.340 --> 00:57:58.420
[Guest]: India, but it was at one level. I mean, you came up against just, you know, nature, the

00:57:58.420 --> 00:58:04.900
[Guest]: mountains, the hills, ordinary people in villages who often helped you as you were, you know,

00:58:04.900 --> 00:58:09.500
[Guest]: dealing with the terrain and geography and so on out there. So I think that in some ways,

00:58:09.500 --> 00:58:14.220
[Guest]: it was more of an experience of getting out of metropolitan life that I had grown up in,

00:58:14.220 --> 00:58:19.740
[Guest]: because I grew up in Paris and London, before I came home to Delhi. And then if I got out

00:58:19.740 --> 00:58:25.620
[Guest]: of St. Xavier's School, it was Delhi of the 1960s. But Dehradun of the 1960s was something

00:58:25.620 --> 00:58:31.740
[Guest]: very different. And the mountains and hills and surrounding villages, I mean, it was not

00:58:31.740 --> 00:58:38.220
[Guest]: a metropolitan life in that sense at all. And I think the school still gives people

00:58:38.220 --> 00:58:43.660
[Guest]: a bit of a connect to an India that's outside metropolitan life. And one reason I took the

00:58:43.660 --> 00:58:48.780
[Guest]: headmastership, and I'll just end the segment with that thought, perhaps, is that I wanted

00:58:48.780 --> 00:58:55.220
[Guest]: my children who were growing up kind of the Baba Logue life in JNU, where I was a warden

00:58:55.220 --> 00:59:00.460
[Guest]: of a hostel, and where they were going to, you know, kind of Baba Logue schools, the

00:59:00.460 --> 00:59:05.420
[Guest]: new schools, the Vasant Valleys, or the Sriram schools, where all the kids were businessmen's

00:59:05.420 --> 00:59:11.220
[Guest]: kids or very senior civil servants kids who were all very metropolitan and cosmopolitan.

00:59:11.220 --> 00:59:15.540
[Guest]: Whereas when they got to Doon School and Wellam Girls, my daughter went to Wellam Girls, later

00:59:15.540 --> 00:59:20.380
[Guest]: my son went to Doon School. I mean, it was a very different set of parents and boys.

00:59:20.380 --> 00:59:25.500
[Guest]: And I thought my kids needed that they needed to get out of Delhi.

00:59:25.500 --> 00:59:31.140
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, that's fascinating a lot to think about. You know, I must confess here that I had that

00:59:31.140 --> 00:59:35.300
[Amit Varma]: impression of Doon being a Baba Logue kind of school as well. You hear about, you know,

00:59:35.300 --> 00:59:38.860
[Amit Varma]: the Gandhi's going there and so on and so forth. And that's what we imagine. So this

00:59:38.860 --> 00:59:43.460
[Amit Varma]: is quite fascinating. So, you know, we'll take another digression before we get back

00:59:43.460 --> 00:59:48.140
[Amit Varma]: to our narrative of personal biography. And this, you know, I'm struck by the phrase,

00:59:48.140 --> 00:59:52.340
[Amit Varma]: it was not like the Delhi of the 1960s. And obviously, I understand the contrast, which

00:59:52.340 --> 00:59:58.540
[Amit Varma]: you're talking about between 1960s Delhi and 1960s Dehradun. But, you know, for someone

00:59:58.540 --> 01:00:04.340
[Amit Varma]: who lives in Delhi today, for a young person today, how would you describe 1960s Delhi?

01:00:04.340 --> 01:00:08.460
[Amit Varma]: Like how has it changed? What was it like back then? Because I would find it impossible,

01:00:08.460 --> 01:00:12.340
[Amit Varma]: for example, very hard, not impossible to describe 1980s Delhi, which I know a little

01:00:12.340 --> 01:00:16.220
[Amit Varma]: bit better. But what was 1960s really like? I'm also curious.

01:00:16.220 --> 01:00:21.300
[Guest]: It was a very quiet town. And I literally mean that. I don't mean it metaphorically.

01:00:21.300 --> 01:00:28.180
[Guest]: It was quiet. You could go out into, you know, central Delhi, Lutyens' Delhi, and walk around

01:00:28.180 --> 01:00:33.220
[Guest]: there with, there was no hubbub. There weren't, you know, pile driving cars and trucks and

01:00:33.220 --> 01:00:39.100
[Guest]: buses and honking and all of that. It was a quiet city. It was gracious in the sense

01:00:39.100 --> 01:00:46.140
[Guest]: that there wasn't this kind of very aggressive sort of scenes and moments that you felt,

01:00:46.140 --> 01:00:52.260
[Guest]: you feel now, or even in 1980s Delhi. And I think it was a Delhi, I think, to be fair,

01:00:52.260 --> 01:00:59.420
[Guest]: it was a Lutyens' Delhi in the sense of an elite that was more Anglicized, more Westernized,

01:00:59.420 --> 01:01:05.100
[Guest]: living in bungalow life and in the few select colonies. It was a much cleaner Delhi. It

01:01:05.100 --> 01:01:10.140
[Guest]: was a very livable city at that level. There weren't any fancy malls, obviously, or fancy

01:01:10.140 --> 01:01:15.060
[Guest]: cineplexes. There were very few foreign goods. There was none of that. If you went to Khan

01:01:15.060 --> 01:01:22.020
[Guest]: Market, there were no shop hoardings visible, pretty much. There were a few cars and motorbikes.

01:01:22.020 --> 01:01:28.860
[Guest]: And you went into shops where everything was available in cupboards, behind glass cupboards.

01:01:28.860 --> 01:01:34.160
[Guest]: And it was very unglamorous, all Indian goods, basically. So it was a very different kind

01:01:34.160 --> 01:01:40.860
[Guest]: of Delhi. I think it was comfortable at that level. And it was a pretty Westernized, elitist

01:01:40.860 --> 01:01:46.140
[Guest]: Delhi. And for a diplomat's kids, and you know, my father's family had been in Delhi

01:01:46.140 --> 01:01:51.740
[Guest]: since New Delhi was built in the 1920s. My grandfather had come from UP at that time.

01:01:51.740 --> 01:01:56.500
[Guest]: And so, personally, of course, when I did get out of St. Xavier's School, I came back

01:01:56.500 --> 01:02:01.260
[Guest]: from Dhoom School briefly on my way to see my parents wherever they were abroad. It was

01:02:01.260 --> 01:02:06.900
[Guest]: a Delhi where I knew a lot of people through family connections and so on. So it was a

01:02:06.900 --> 01:02:11.300
[Guest]: different experience, I think. And there's a sort of a sense of nostalgia about it. It

01:02:11.300 --> 01:02:15.700
[Guest]: was a very tractable Delhi. It wasn't very big, I think. I mean, when I went from St.

01:02:15.700 --> 01:02:20.580
[Guest]: Xavier's School to visit my grandmother in South Delhi, you know, she had a plot of land

01:02:20.580 --> 01:02:25.260
[Guest]: in Friends Colony. My friends who used to laugh at me and say, oh, you're going off

01:02:25.260 --> 01:02:31.240
[Guest]: to Faridabad, you know. So it was the edge of town. And a really big adventurous outing

01:02:31.240 --> 01:02:36.820
[Guest]: was to go to South Extension. When my parents would come from Pakistan to visit for a time,

01:02:36.820 --> 01:02:41.380
[Guest]: they would take me to South Extension. And my friends would be very excited about, you

01:02:41.380 --> 01:02:44.740
[Guest]: know, you're going to the edge of the town. And Vasant Vihar, I mean, if you looked out

01:02:44.740 --> 01:02:49.340
[Guest]: for Modern Bazaar, the shop there, there was nothing but farmland there. So, you know,

01:02:49.340 --> 01:02:54.340
[Guest]: the landscape was very, very, very different in Delhi. Delhi was civil lines and North

01:02:54.340 --> 01:02:59.620
[Guest]: Delhi and all of that. And then, you know, Rajpath and Lachchind's Delhi and Defence

01:02:59.620 --> 01:03:05.180
[Guest]: Colony, Friends Colony were the outer limits. And so I think it was very tractable. I would

01:03:05.180 --> 01:03:11.700
[Guest]: walk sometimes. I could walk from my uncle's house at Wellesley Road, from the Armed Forces

01:03:11.700 --> 01:03:17.500
[Guest]: Officers Mess there to Connaught Place. Connaught Place was a centre for, you know, things happening,

01:03:17.500 --> 01:03:24.480
[Guest]: discotheques and shops and fast food, such as it was. And, you know, I would think nothing

01:03:24.480 --> 01:03:29.820
[Guest]: of walking there as a 14-year-old or a 15-year-old, getting into a scooter. And, you know, you

01:03:29.820 --> 01:03:35.220
[Guest]: would be on a street, waiting for a scooter, and it would be pin drop silence. And then

01:03:35.220 --> 01:03:40.620
[Guest]: you would hear a car come. If I could very badly mimic the sense of it, of a kind of

01:03:40.620 --> 01:03:48.900
[Guest]: eeeewwwwww, a car would go and then there would be silence again. That's unimaginable,

01:03:48.900 --> 01:03:55.220
[Guest]: I think, almost anywhere in Delhi today. So, yeah, that was Delhi. And I miss it. But,

01:03:55.220 --> 01:03:59.980
[Guest]: you know, Delhi today has its own excitement and vibrancy, I think. So, you can't live

01:03:59.980 --> 01:04:00.980
[Guest]: in the past.

01:04:00.980 --> 01:04:05.100
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, yeah, you can't live in the past. You also mentioned that you went to Dehradun because

01:04:05.100 --> 01:04:08.780
[Amit Varma]: I mean, one reason was that you wanted your kids to have a life outside the Baba Log life

01:04:08.780 --> 01:04:12.820
[Amit Varma]: and all that. Baba Log, by the way, would be such a lovely name for a novel because

01:04:12.820 --> 01:04:16.660
[Amit Varma]: you can read it both ways, right? Baba Log and Baba Log. And that's one reason why you

01:04:16.660 --> 01:04:22.340
[Amit Varma]: went there. But I guess another reason for why a place like that would be extremely attractive

01:04:22.340 --> 01:04:26.780
[Amit Varma]: is like you said, the quietness of it, the pace of life being so slow, the hills around

01:04:26.780 --> 01:04:31.860
[Amit Varma]: and so on. And, you know, at an abstract level, many of us aspire to that. We say, nahi yaar

01:04:31.860 --> 01:04:36.340
[Amit Varma]: paharo mein jaake rahenge and we'll, you know, live a quiet life like that. But at the same

01:04:36.340 --> 01:04:40.340
[Amit Varma]: time, the kind of life you might want to live in the abstract collides with the kind of

01:04:40.340 --> 01:04:44.220
[Amit Varma]: things you want to do in the concrete, which often require being in a big city, which are

01:04:44.220 --> 01:04:48.580
[Amit Varma]: often not just work, but often just other things, meeting friends regularly and so on

01:04:48.580 --> 01:04:51.900
[Amit Varma]: and so forth. Is that something you've thought about? Because when I was just reading the

01:04:51.900 --> 01:04:56.620
[Amit Varma]: bare facts of your sort of biography, it struck me that you bounced around a lot that, you

01:04:56.620 --> 01:05:00.380
[Amit Varma]: know, you've travelled with your diplomat father, you've been in Doon School and all

01:05:00.380 --> 01:05:05.460
[Amit Varma]: of that, you've done the schooling here, your sort of BA and MA at British Columbia, then

01:05:05.460 --> 01:05:09.380
[Amit Varma]: your PhD at Illinois, then you come back to Doon School and in between you've taught at

01:05:09.380 --> 01:05:14.420
[Amit Varma]: Doon School, you come back there as a headmaster, then you come back to Delhi, you're at JNU

01:05:14.420 --> 01:05:19.180
[Amit Varma]: and now you're in Singapore. So how does one think of that? Like, does one think of how

01:05:19.180 --> 01:05:25.860
[Amit Varma]: one wants to live one's life purely in terms of career goals, that these are the things

01:05:25.860 --> 01:05:31.220
[Amit Varma]: I want to study or explore, or this would be an interesting institution to be part of?

01:05:31.220 --> 01:05:36.740
[Amit Varma]: Or have you also had other considerations while kind of planning your life out that

01:05:36.740 --> 01:05:40.100
[Amit Varma]: this is also where I want to be, this kind of life suits me?

01:05:40.100 --> 01:05:46.220
[Guest]: I think, I mean, I'd love to say that, you know, I was a person who thought that bouncing

01:05:46.220 --> 01:05:52.780
[Guest]: around and moving jobs and so on was, I mean, that I kind of was ahead of the curve. I mean,

01:05:52.780 --> 01:05:57.300
[Guest]: who stays in a job for very long now? It seems to be the norm that you move around and you're

01:05:57.300 --> 01:06:02.820
[Guest]: hyper mobile between jobs, between locales. But I don't think I was that clever or imaginative

01:06:02.820 --> 01:06:07.700
[Guest]: or adventurous. I just went where the jobs were. I mean, my father was a civil servant.

01:06:07.700 --> 01:06:12.180
[Guest]: He had a plot of land that he inherited, but he had no money to give me. He was not really

01:06:12.180 --> 01:06:17.460
[Guest]: willing to exert himself to get me a job of any kind. And the one time he tried, I mean,

01:06:17.460 --> 01:06:22.700
[Guest]: it was a farcical and it didn't suit me anyway. So I had to make my way in the world. And

01:06:22.700 --> 01:06:27.980
[Guest]: I just went where I thought somebody would actually want me. And my first foray to Doon

01:06:27.980 --> 01:06:34.060
[Guest]: School in 1979-80 was, I mean, basically, I mean, my dad made it fairly clear that I

01:06:34.060 --> 01:06:38.780
[Guest]: couldn't be on the payroll for very long. And I had to get off and start arranging my

01:06:38.780 --> 01:06:43.420
[Guest]: life and my finances. And when I said, no, I'm not interested in sitting for the civil

01:06:43.420 --> 01:06:50.540
[Guest]: service or going into business, then he was like, OK, beta, then better make some plans

01:06:50.540 --> 01:06:58.300
[Guest]: of moving on. You can't live with me forever. And not being adventurous, I just looked for

01:06:58.300 --> 01:07:02.540
[Guest]: who would want me. I hoped that someone in journalism might want me, but there weren't

01:07:02.540 --> 01:07:07.820
[Guest]: many places in those days. So I wrote off to my old school. And so I went to Doon School

01:07:07.820 --> 01:07:12.660
[Guest]: to teach for a year. But what I realized was that I'm not really a schoolmaster per se.

01:07:12.660 --> 01:07:18.900
[Guest]: And so after a year, I went on to do the Ph.D. in America. But when I was finishing at Illinois,

01:07:18.900 --> 01:07:25.620
[Guest]: finishing the Ph.D., what I did know was that I didn't want to live in America. I thoroughly

01:07:25.620 --> 01:07:31.820
[Guest]: enjoyed my time in the U.S. and earlier in Canada. But it just didn't seem to me that

01:07:31.820 --> 01:07:37.500
[Guest]: America was really deep in my heart that way. And American lifestyles suited me, even though,

01:07:37.500 --> 01:07:42.300
[Guest]: you know, up to that point, most of my life had been in the West. But I just thought that

01:07:42.300 --> 01:07:49.780
[Guest]: there was something in terms of lifestyles and the future that didn't work for me. And

01:07:49.780 --> 01:07:54.020
[Guest]: my wife was Canadian, white Canadian. And I think she sort of had a little bit of a

01:07:54.020 --> 01:08:00.620
[Guest]: sense that she would like to be back in North America for the longer time. But she was very,

01:08:00.620 --> 01:08:07.540
[Guest]: very kind to me and I think indulged me a lot. And she agreed that, you know, we would

01:08:07.540 --> 01:08:14.300
[Guest]: move back to India. And I was encouraged by my supervisor, Steve Cohen, who wanted to

01:08:14.300 --> 01:08:19.700
[Guest]: train Indian and other South Asian students to go back so that they could hopefully make

01:08:19.700 --> 01:08:23.900
[Guest]: a contribution to the intellectual life of their own country, particularly academic life.

01:08:23.900 --> 01:08:31.100
[Guest]: And so with his encouragement, also, I thought about coming back to India as soon as I finished.

01:08:31.100 --> 01:08:36.100
[Guest]: And my first job, actually, you missed it, but I don't blame you, but it was in Baroda

01:08:36.100 --> 01:08:42.140
[Guest]: at MS University in Baroda. And that was partly because although JNU was a natural habitat

01:08:42.140 --> 01:08:47.540
[Guest]: for me, it has such a massive School of International Studies, one of the biggest in the world,

01:08:47.540 --> 01:08:53.940
[Guest]: and 85 faculty members at the time that I finally went there. But I still had an instinct

01:08:53.940 --> 01:09:00.660
[Guest]: that I wanted to start out decentred from the centre. I wanted to be away from Delhi.

01:09:00.660 --> 01:09:05.900
[Guest]: And I'd had my first child, she was very young, my daughter Gayatri. And I think my wife,

01:09:05.900 --> 01:09:10.460
[Guest]: Bobby, was a bit dubious, living in a small town in India. She knew Delhi, she'd lived

01:09:10.460 --> 01:09:14.660
[Guest]: in Dehradun with me for a while. But I thought that it would be a bit of an adventure and

01:09:14.660 --> 01:09:19.020
[Guest]: it would be nice to see another part of India. And I had a cousin there who taught in the

01:09:19.020 --> 01:09:24.220
[Guest]: history department. And she told me about the job opening. And there weren't too many

01:09:24.220 --> 01:09:29.540
[Guest]: other jobs in international relations. I applied for it. I got it. And I remember I finished

01:09:29.540 --> 01:09:35.500
[Guest]: defending my PhD thesis on a Saturday morning or some such. And I was back in India on the

01:09:35.500 --> 01:09:40.780
[Guest]: Wednesday and I think I joined MS University on a Friday. I mean, I may have got the days

01:09:40.780 --> 01:09:45.060
[Guest]: a week and all that mixed up, but it was within four or five days of finishing the PhD. I

01:09:45.060 --> 01:09:51.260
[Guest]: was back in India and in harness, as it were. And, you know, from there, I moved back to

01:09:51.260 --> 01:09:56.220
[Guest]: the States for a while. I thought the university, which had been glorious for two or three years,

01:09:56.220 --> 01:10:01.820
[Guest]: was going in a direction that I wasn't enjoying, ultimately. And that's a slightly different

01:10:01.820 --> 01:10:06.100
[Guest]: story. It was getting a bit too nativist for me, but they were good years. I had a second

01:10:06.100 --> 01:10:11.860
[Guest]: child and I went back essentially to Illinois for about a year. But again, with no thought

01:10:11.860 --> 01:10:15.820
[Guest]: of really staying there, although, again, I think my wife would have quite liked to

01:10:15.820 --> 01:10:21.460
[Guest]: be back in North America with her family. But again, I mean, one day I got a phone call

01:10:21.460 --> 01:10:26.860
[Guest]: sitting in Illinois in my office and it was Abid Hussain, the famous Indian civil servant

01:10:26.860 --> 01:10:32.020
[Guest]: and ex-ambassador to the US. And he'd been, I think, deputy chairman of the planning commission

01:10:32.020 --> 01:10:39.460
[Guest]: or some such. And I had never met him. And he just said, Babu. And I said, I'm sorry,

01:10:39.460 --> 01:10:46.700
[Guest]: who is this? He said, I'm Abid. Abid Hussain. And of course, I'd heard of him, but he spoke

01:10:46.700 --> 01:10:51.780
[Guest]: to me in such a familiar way that I was kind of drawn to him and into his world almost

01:10:51.780 --> 01:10:57.180
[Guest]: immediately. And he was vice chairman of the Rajiv Gandhi Foundation and the Rajiv Gandhi

01:10:57.180 --> 01:11:03.220
[Guest]: Institute of Contemporary Studies, which is the think tank wing of the RGF. And he said,

01:11:03.220 --> 01:11:10.340
[Guest]: I've heard about you from Steve Cohen, who's here at the Ford Foundation in Delhi. And

01:11:10.340 --> 01:11:16.060
[Guest]: he said, you're very keen to come back to India and come for a couple of years and help

01:11:16.060 --> 01:11:22.620
[Guest]: me with this think tank. And then you can do what you like. And I mean, a few, I finished

01:11:22.620 --> 01:11:28.620
[Guest]: the semester. A few weeks later, I packed my bags. And Bobby and I and the babies headed

01:11:28.620 --> 01:11:33.180
[Guest]: home. So I think, you know, I mean, I won't tell you every step of the way of what happened

01:11:33.180 --> 01:11:39.980
[Guest]: since then. But I think I went where serendipitously jobs opened up. I think there was a broad

01:11:39.980 --> 01:11:45.300
[Guest]: trajectory, which was that I always wanted to be home in India, doing something in India.

01:11:45.300 --> 01:11:50.580
[Guest]: I was comfortable. So it was a personal kind of comfort issue. I did have a bit of a sense

01:11:50.580 --> 01:11:54.300
[Guest]: of, can I do something for my country? But I mean, I'm not trying to dress myself up

01:11:54.300 --> 01:12:00.300
[Guest]: as being somebody overly noble and all of that. But I just sort of felt comfortable

01:12:00.300 --> 01:12:06.020
[Guest]: and good. And it seemed to work for me. And I would say it sort of paid off, you know,

01:12:06.020 --> 01:12:12.620
[Guest]: my whole professional life developed and flowered really in India. And I'm tremendously grateful

01:12:12.620 --> 01:12:17.620
[Guest]: to the institutions that took a chance on me, my students that helped make me what I

01:12:17.620 --> 01:12:24.780
[Guest]: am, the media in the 1980s that gave me an opportunity to make a bit of a name for myself

01:12:24.780 --> 01:12:29.500
[Guest]: and all the rest of it. I mean, my colleagues. And that's how all again, why did I go to

01:12:29.500 --> 01:12:34.860
[Guest]: Doon School? I got a call one day as I was rushing off to do my early morning lectures,

01:12:34.860 --> 01:12:39.780
[Guest]: which I'm never good at in early in the morning. And somebody just said, Dr. Bajpai. And I

01:12:39.780 --> 01:12:44.860
[Guest]: said, yeah, I said, I'm so and so from a search company. And somebody mentioned that you might

01:12:44.860 --> 01:12:49.660
[Guest]: be a candidate for the headmastership of the school. It's your old school. And I said,

01:12:49.660 --> 01:12:53.620
[Guest]: oh, my gosh, well, I'm running off to class. I mean, I can't discuss it. But no, I never

01:12:53.620 --> 01:12:58.780
[Guest]: thought about it and said, well, are you kind of open to it? And I said, well, which old

01:12:58.780 --> 01:13:03.780
[Guest]: boy wouldn't be? But not really. No, not at this point. And he said, but would you like

01:13:03.780 --> 01:13:08.260
[Guest]: to have a chat later about it? And I said, well, of course, I can't say no to that. And

01:13:08.260 --> 01:13:14.980
[Amit Varma]: so you know, another serendipitous thing happened. And that took me off to there.

01:13:14.980 --> 01:13:18.780
[Amit Varma]: That's fascinating. And what's also fascinating is when you talk about these two phone calls,

01:13:18.780 --> 01:13:22.580
[Amit Varma]: and I you know, I must remind our listeners that today when we say received a phone call,

01:13:22.580 --> 01:13:26.100
[Amit Varma]: it means you know, you've got your mobile phone and mine is always on silent. So if

01:13:26.100 --> 01:13:30.180
[Amit Varma]: I get a phone call, it's because I'm looking at my phone already maybe going through Twitter

01:13:30.180 --> 01:13:34.220
[Amit Varma]: like a junkie and you know, the phone flashes and I pick it up. But otherwise, I'm not going

01:13:34.220 --> 01:13:37.740
[Amit Varma]: to pick it up. And in at the time you would have got the phone call, it would have been

01:13:37.740 --> 01:13:42.220
[Amit Varma]: a physical instrument, it would have rung two or three times, you move towards it, you

01:13:42.220 --> 01:13:46.980
[Amit Varma]: wonder who's calling, there's no caller ID, you pick it up, and then the person says what

01:13:46.980 --> 01:13:52.380
[Amit Varma]: they say. And that's also such a charming recounting Mr. Hussain saying Babu, it's like,

01:13:52.380 --> 01:13:56.660
[Amit Varma]: it's so cinematic, almost a scene that you kind of described. So maybe after the biography

01:13:56.660 --> 01:14:01.860
[Amit Varma]: for movie is made on your life, that could be a pivotal scene, maybe add some dramatic

01:14:01.860 --> 01:14:05.940
[Amit Varma]: elements to it, look outside after the phone call and your car blows up, something like

01:14:05.940 --> 01:14:10.140
[Amit Varma]: that. Anyways, let's sort of go back to the final strand of your personal journey that

01:14:10.140 --> 01:14:15.580
[Amit Varma]: I'm curious about, which is that how did you get into the specific areas that you got into?

01:14:15.580 --> 01:14:19.660
[Amit Varma]: Like when people are kids, you know, they'll dream of being a pilot or an ice cream seller,

01:14:19.660 --> 01:14:24.940
[Amit Varma]: or a movie star, they won't dream of being like a foreign policy scholar or a noted academic

01:14:24.940 --> 01:14:30.100
[Amit Varma]: and so on. So how did this kind of happen? Was it again serendipitous that you do one

01:14:30.100 --> 01:14:34.460
[Amit Varma]: thing at a time and it takes you to that final destination? Or did you have a sense at some

01:14:34.460 --> 01:14:39.460
[Amit Varma]: point that these are the things that I find fascinating, that I want to go deeper into,

01:14:39.460 --> 01:14:43.020
[Amit Varma]: that I want to wake up in the morning and look forward to the day and reading these

01:14:43.020 --> 01:14:47.100
[Amit Varma]: kind of books, studying this kind of subject will give me that happiness? How was that

01:14:47.100 --> 01:14:48.100
[Guest]: for you?

01:14:48.100 --> 01:14:51.260
[Guest]: I think there was no straight line for me as there probably isn't for most people, you

01:14:51.260 --> 01:14:57.500
[Guest]: know. And as I said, I was not a person who knew so definitively everything that I thought

01:14:57.500 --> 01:15:04.300
[Guest]: and wanted to do and how I looked at the world. But I think quite early, I had a sense that

01:15:04.300 --> 01:15:09.380
[Guest]: something to do with the written word always was very important for me. My eldest brother

01:15:09.380 --> 01:15:16.540
[Guest]: Shyam was, we would say, a bookworm. I think he introduced me to the world of books a lot

01:15:16.540 --> 01:15:23.780
[Guest]: and things like chess and intellectual matters a lot. And my other brother Ishwari, who went

01:15:23.780 --> 01:15:29.940
[Guest]: on to be a journalist, he introduced me to sports and competition and being in the world,

01:15:29.940 --> 01:15:35.500
[Guest]: you know, being outside of myself. And I mean, I play a lot of sports, or I did, but I'm

01:15:35.500 --> 01:15:41.180
[Guest]: not a sportsman per se. It wasn't that influence that Ishwari had on me. It was that being

01:15:41.180 --> 01:15:48.780
[Guest]: in the world, being active in the world. And he's a person of strong views and ideas, and

01:15:48.780 --> 01:15:54.580
[Guest]: he can be much more argumentative in a good way. And I think I got that from him, from

01:15:54.580 --> 01:16:02.020
[Guest]: my brother. And I think from my younger sister, I got a sense of a certain kind of loyalty

01:16:02.020 --> 01:16:09.020
[Guest]: or commitment to a sort of family and all of that. And the metaphor for me there is,

01:16:09.020 --> 01:16:14.820
[Guest]: I think, you know, not being very public or demonstrative, but doing something quietly

01:16:14.820 --> 01:16:19.940
[Guest]: towards the well-being of others. I think my sister is a very outward person giving

01:16:19.940 --> 01:16:25.140
[Guest]: to family and all of that. And what that means, I think, for me in my arena was, I mean, trying

01:16:25.140 --> 01:16:29.660
[Guest]: to give something back to the public. I mean, I don't want to state it too grandly. I think

01:16:29.660 --> 01:16:35.740
[Guest]: my siblings had quite an impact on me. But why this area then? I mean, I think it developed

01:16:35.740 --> 01:16:40.940
[Guest]: gradually. My father forced me to do economics, because my brothers, especially my eldest

01:16:40.940 --> 01:16:45.340
[Guest]: brother said, oh, no, the way the world is going, you know, they were all history students.

01:16:45.340 --> 01:16:50.420
[Guest]: My dad had done history at St. Stephen's. Both my brothers did history at St. Stephen's.

01:16:50.420 --> 01:16:54.500
[Guest]: And they got together when I was finishing at Dune School and said, Dad, you know, Kanti

01:16:54.500 --> 01:16:59.300
[Guest]: cannot do history, and better for him not to go to St. Stephen's. Too many bachelors

01:16:59.300 --> 01:17:04.700
[Guest]: went there and kind of wasted their time. So get out of it. And my dad was an ambassador,

01:17:04.700 --> 01:17:09.060
[Guest]: High Commissioner in Canada. And I went off to do an economics degree. But my heart was

01:17:09.060 --> 01:17:16.340
[Guest]: not in economics, really. Although I kept, and I thank economics for, you know, instilling

01:17:16.340 --> 01:17:20.900
[Guest]: me the idea of thinking about things a bit systematically, trying to have a bit of a

01:17:20.900 --> 01:17:25.460
[Guest]: framework, introduced me to issues like the philosophy of science and things like that,

01:17:25.460 --> 01:17:30.820
[Guest]: that I think held me in good stead. And I loved mathematics. So the only attraction

01:17:30.820 --> 01:17:38.180
[Guest]: I had in economics was math, to be honest. But what developed in me through my undergrad

01:17:38.180 --> 01:17:46.060
[Guest]: days in economics was that I started to do some political science courses. And something

01:17:46.060 --> 01:17:53.140
[Guest]: along the way in my school life, I began to develop this feeling that Indian democracy,

01:17:53.140 --> 01:17:58.780
[Guest]: I mean, that it seemed very firm. This is, I mean, I went to Canada in 1973. I began

01:17:58.780 --> 01:18:04.340
[Guest]: my economics degree in 1973. And of course, it was kind of a high tide still of democracy.

01:18:04.340 --> 01:18:09.500
[Guest]: It was before the emergency. We were still in a kind of post-Neruvian glow, a Neruvian

01:18:09.500 --> 01:18:15.220
[Guest]: glow. But I think I had a little bit of a sense that Indian democracy was still quite

01:18:15.220 --> 01:18:21.580
[Guest]: tenuous. And in one of my courses in my second or third year under a professor called John

01:18:21.580 --> 01:18:27.980
[Guest]: Wood, who was an Indianist, I read a lot of stuff about civil-military relations. And

01:18:27.980 --> 01:18:33.300
[Guest]: what came out of that was how many countries in the third world had had military coups,

01:18:33.300 --> 01:18:40.500
[Guest]: including Pakistan, our neighbor. Here was a military that was born of the same original

01:18:40.500 --> 01:18:45.780
[Guest]: military, the same genus, the Indian army, but it had intervened in politics in 1958.

01:18:45.780 --> 01:18:51.420
[Guest]: And by the way, I'd lived in Pakistan in the 60s because my dad was the deputy high

01:18:51.420 --> 01:18:59.820
[Guest]: commissioner there. And so I had a sense that it may be that Indian democracy was perhaps

01:18:59.820 --> 01:19:06.340
[Guest]: more tenuous. And I thought initially that India also might succumb to, in a moment of

01:19:06.340 --> 01:19:13.420
[Guest]: crisis or instability, to a kind of right-wing military coup at some point. And later, I

01:19:13.420 --> 01:19:20.380
[Guest]: began to worry about the left wing. I thought, I don't know at what point, but gradually

01:19:20.380 --> 01:19:25.900
[Guest]: perhaps it was the Naxalites of the late 1960s. My brother, Shyam, had been at St. Stephen's

01:19:25.900 --> 01:19:29.420
[Guest]: College and some of his friends had become Naxalites and so on. And so maybe I knew a

01:19:29.420 --> 01:19:37.300
[Guest]: little bit about that and I was studying political philosophy alongside economics. And I had

01:19:37.300 --> 01:19:41.500
[Guest]: a sense that there could be a moment when the right wing and the left wing in India

01:19:41.500 --> 01:19:47.580
[Guest]: would be thrown into this kind of antagonistic dialectic and the liberal space in India would

01:19:47.580 --> 01:19:54.980
[Guest]: collapse. And my interest in social science became more political science than economics.

01:19:54.980 --> 01:20:00.540
[Guest]: And even in economics, the course I loved the most was economic development theory.

01:20:00.540 --> 01:20:06.340
[Guest]: And quite a lot of my interest there was, what are the political underpinnings of economic

01:20:06.340 --> 01:20:11.780
[Guest]: growth and development? And I thought, perhaps naively, that democracy and liberalism were

01:20:11.780 --> 01:20:19.220
[Guest]: made for long-term economic growth. And I was a bit worried that India... I was puzzled

01:20:19.220 --> 01:20:24.100
[Guest]: why India, as a relatively liberal democratic country, was still, in those days, the so-called

01:20:24.100 --> 01:20:29.220
[Guest]: Hindu rate of growth. We weren't growing very fast. So I think that led me to grad school

01:20:29.220 --> 01:20:34.460
[Guest]: in America, where I wanted to do civil military relations. That's why I ended up with Steve

01:20:34.460 --> 01:20:41.340
[Guest]: Cohen at the University of Illinois, because he was the expert on the Indian Army, on civil

01:20:41.340 --> 01:20:46.980
[Guest]: military relations in India. And I didn't know it at the time, but he was already more

01:20:46.980 --> 01:20:52.860
[Guest]: or less finishing a book on the Pakistani military. And I hoped to write a book on comparative

01:20:52.860 --> 01:20:57.900
[Guest]: civil military relations in South Asia. I thought India, Pakistan, and Bangladesh. When

01:20:57.900 --> 01:21:03.820
[Guest]: I arrived there, he'd already written the book on Pakistan. But what stayed with me

01:21:03.820 --> 01:21:08.020
[Guest]: there was that, I mean, I was introduced to international relations there. I had come

01:21:08.020 --> 01:21:14.140
[Guest]: thinking doing comparative politics, civil military relations, doing political theory,

01:21:14.140 --> 01:21:19.060
[Guest]: because I enjoyed that. And I thought American government and politics, because at that time,

01:21:19.060 --> 01:21:24.220
[Guest]: it was the city on the hill. It was the world's greatest democracy. And if you were concerned

01:21:24.220 --> 01:21:29.620
[Guest]: about democracy, then maybe there was something to learn from America. But I started to take

01:21:29.620 --> 01:21:34.940
[Guest]: some courses in international relations, and I had inspiring professors. And my fellowship

01:21:34.940 --> 01:21:43.340
[Guest]: was in arms control and security issues, international security. And I saw a kind of nexus, and I'll

01:21:43.340 --> 01:21:50.100
[Guest]: end with that thought, which is that, would democracy survive in times of intense kind

01:21:50.100 --> 01:21:57.220
[Guest]: of security turmoil? Whether internal security turmoil, as I suppose happened in Pakistan,

01:21:57.220 --> 01:22:04.140
[Guest]: leading to the end of democracy there, or other forms of internal turmoil, or in terms

01:22:04.140 --> 01:22:12.260
[Guest]: of an enormous challenge externally, under which democracy might crumble. So I thought

01:22:12.260 --> 01:22:17.300
[Guest]: my worry was that, and a connecting thread to my earlier interest in democracy was whether

01:22:17.300 --> 01:22:24.380
[Guest]: in India, the discourse around security might lead to a point where democracy might be called

01:22:24.380 --> 01:22:30.660
[Guest]: into question. And I thought the antagonism with Pakistan, particularly in the early 80s

01:22:30.660 --> 01:22:36.340
[Guest]: when I was there, and overlooking the possibilities of cooperation with Pakistan might someday

01:22:36.340 --> 01:22:41.860
[Guest]: lead to a situation where democracy might come under stress in India. And so my PhD

01:22:41.860 --> 01:22:48.140
[Guest]: was on SARC, an unlikely subject, the South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation,

01:22:48.140 --> 01:22:52.540
[Guest]: because I wanted to look at the prospects of cooperation in the region, and how that

01:22:52.540 --> 01:22:59.980
[Guest]: might make in all the countries, it might be a part of a kind of democratic spirit that

01:22:59.980 --> 01:23:05.860
[Guest]: would flower in the region, and undergird and strengthen democracy for the long term.

01:23:05.860 --> 01:23:10.180
[Guest]: I probably now reading back into it a bit too much, and trying to make myself too clever

01:23:10.180 --> 01:23:15.140
[Guest]: about it, and maybe too philosophical about it. But there was something like that was

01:23:15.140 --> 01:23:22.100
[Guest]: brewing in me. And that's how my academic career sort of flowered from there.

01:23:22.100 --> 01:23:25.980
[Amit Varma]: So you know, when we are young, we are filled with this intellectual excitement whenever

01:23:25.980 --> 01:23:30.420
[Amit Varma]: we discover a new subject, especially when it comes to answering big questions about

01:23:30.420 --> 01:23:34.660
[Amit Varma]: the world. So there is this allure of grand theories, right, whether it's in economics

01:23:34.660 --> 01:23:38.420
[Amit Varma]: or political science or whatever, you know, the first grand theory that you come across

01:23:38.420 --> 01:23:42.660
[Amit Varma]: that is attractive, and that explains everything in a coherent way. Doesn't matter if the explanations

01:23:42.660 --> 01:23:47.660
[Amit Varma]: are true or false, because who knows at that time, but that seems to offer a coherent frame

01:23:47.660 --> 01:23:51.660
[Amit Varma]: of looking at the world, one is tempted to adopt it. And then what happens is that over

01:23:51.660 --> 01:23:56.220
[Amit Varma]: a period of time, you know, you kind of get mugged by reality, you begin to realize that

01:23:56.220 --> 01:24:01.180
[Amit Varma]: none of the grand theories are necessarily, you know, the whole answer to anything as

01:24:01.180 --> 01:24:05.460
[Amit Varma]: a friend of mine likes to say, the quote goes, all models are false, but some models are

01:24:05.460 --> 01:24:10.180
[Amit Varma]: useful. So what was that intellectual journey on your part, like, in terms of what were

01:24:10.180 --> 01:24:14.020
[Amit Varma]: the theories that you were drawn towards? What frames did you feel had the greatest

01:24:14.020 --> 01:24:19.740
[Amit Varma]: explanatory power? And earlier in this conversation, you spoke about how you had certainty about

01:24:19.740 --> 01:24:24.220
[Amit Varma]: a lot of things in the 80s, where you weren't afraid to express your opinion firmly, but

01:24:24.220 --> 01:24:29.900
[Amit Varma]: now your view is much more kind of nuanced. So take me a little bit through your personal

01:24:29.900 --> 01:24:34.620
[Amit Varma]: intellectual development also of looking back at that time and saying that, okay, these

01:24:34.620 --> 01:24:38.740
[Amit Varma]: are the things that attracted me then that I felt explained the world. And this is how

01:24:38.740 --> 01:24:41.660
[Amit Varma]: my frame has evolved over time, and so on.

01:24:41.660 --> 01:24:48.580
[Guest]: You know, I was a bit stupid. I don't think I had a huge, coherent intellectual framework.

01:24:48.580 --> 01:24:55.860
[Guest]: Partly, I think the way my political science training was, was that it wasn't a high theory

01:24:55.860 --> 01:25:01.100
[Guest]: school. I think some of the other departments were like that, in you know, the great schools

01:25:01.100 --> 01:25:06.780
[Guest]: of the East Coast or the West Coast of America. But at Illinois, it wasn't such a high theory

01:25:06.780 --> 01:25:14.260
[Guest]: school. And I think we dealt more with kind of more meso or micro theories. And a lot

01:25:14.260 --> 01:25:21.900
[Guest]: of my kind of theoretical predilections were towards issues related to deterrence theory,

01:25:21.900 --> 01:25:27.300
[Guest]: for instance, which is the idea of how you with nuclear weapons or with conventional

01:25:27.300 --> 01:25:32.340
[Guest]: military weapons, how can you prevent another country from attacking you? That's a kind

01:25:32.340 --> 01:25:37.740
[Guest]: of a micro theory. And I delved a lot into the logic of deterrence theory. I knew a lot

01:25:37.740 --> 01:25:43.660
[Guest]: about civil military relations theory. Why coups happen? Why do military step into power

01:25:43.660 --> 01:25:51.140
[Guest]: and then fail to relinquish power at some point? For my thesis, I read a lot about regionalism.

01:25:51.140 --> 01:25:56.260
[Guest]: Why do countries come together, particularly to cooperate at the regional level? I had

01:25:56.260 --> 01:26:03.100
[Guest]: a whole argument about how we think about regions. I mean, regions are a bit seamless.

01:26:03.100 --> 01:26:08.700
[Guest]: How is it that we draw a boundary around a region at a particular place, more or less?

01:26:08.700 --> 01:26:14.460
[Guest]: You know, again, a kind of middle range theory I had, I didn't have a big picture IR view

01:26:14.460 --> 01:26:19.580
[Guest]: of the world. I mean, your listeners may not be in this area, but there are basically three

01:26:19.580 --> 01:26:25.260
[Guest]: big paradigms in international relations. Realism, which is a power based understanding

01:26:25.260 --> 01:26:31.220
[Guest]: of the world. Liberalism, which is that certain institutions and rules and norms out there

01:26:31.220 --> 01:26:39.900
[Guest]: like international law or diplomatic understandings and negotiations is what makes the world between

01:26:39.900 --> 01:26:44.940
[Guest]: nation states. And the third is constructivism, which is that we make our world. There's certain

01:26:44.940 --> 01:26:50.860
[Guest]: kinds of deep values and identities we hold to that we construct periodically, which have

01:26:50.860 --> 01:26:56.060
[Guest]: great power. And, you know, it's those that affect how we think about other societies

01:26:56.060 --> 01:27:01.940
[Guest]: and our relationship with them. But, you know, at that time, I wasn't in that game. I was

01:27:01.940 --> 01:27:08.460
[Guest]: in these middle range theories. In that sense, I was a bit stupid. But in a sense, I was

01:27:08.460 --> 01:27:14.700
[Guest]: a problem solver. I was attracted to big theory. I read a lot of sociology, literary criticism.

01:27:14.700 --> 01:27:19.500
[Guest]: I read the French theorists, the Derrida's and the Foucault's and the Roland Barthes

01:27:19.500 --> 01:27:24.140
[Guest]: and all of that, mostly so that I didn't look stupid. It took quite a long time for

01:27:24.140 --> 01:27:30.780
[Guest]: that to settle in me to help me make sense of the world better. But I had a kind of problem

01:27:30.780 --> 01:27:37.180
[Guest]: solving view of theory. It would help me solve certain kinds of intellectual puzzles or concerns

01:27:37.180 --> 01:27:42.300
[Guest]: and not much more, I think. And so that's where I was. I mean, I looked at problems

01:27:42.300 --> 01:27:48.180
[Guest]: that interested me, and then I tried to turn to theories that I thought would explain that.

01:27:48.180 --> 01:27:53.780
[Guest]: Not very big theories, but kind of intermediate theory. So I didn't have a, you know, a very

01:27:53.780 --> 01:28:00.340
[Guest]: coherent picture. Although deep down, I suppose, and I suppose that's true even now, I was

01:28:00.340 --> 01:28:06.180
[Guest]: kind of a liberal. I'm a liberal in domestic politics, probably, and I'm a liberal internationally

01:28:06.180 --> 01:28:10.820
[Guest]: as well. And I suppose there was always a substratum of that. I just didn't quite know

01:28:10.820 --> 01:28:17.580
[Guest]: it. I didn't quite have the language and the profundity to figure that out, or even

01:28:17.580 --> 01:28:23.780
[Guest]: the self-reflection. But I think gradually, that's where I ended up. And I think something

01:28:23.780 --> 01:28:29.740
[Guest]: of what I learned very perfectly through these French theorists, you know, the postmodernists

01:28:29.740 --> 01:28:35.460
[Guest]: and poststructuralists and deconstructionists and so on, came back to this kind of bifocal

01:28:35.460 --> 01:28:41.660
[Guest]: worldview, which is, don't make too many big assumptions about there being certainties

01:28:41.660 --> 01:28:49.940
[Guest]: undergirding your worldviews. There's no language game that produces a stable set of assumptions

01:28:49.940 --> 01:28:55.300
[Guest]: and arguments for all time. You can't derive an understanding of the world about everything

01:28:55.300 --> 01:29:03.060
[Guest]: once and for all from some Olympian standpoint, which you hold forever. And so I guess I have

01:29:03.060 --> 01:29:10.660
[Guest]: a kind of shifting good-humored liberalism, again, a reflex against holding to certainties

01:29:10.660 --> 01:29:17.380
[Guest]: in a very orthodox position. So I guess my meta-theory is, don't have a firm theoretical

01:29:17.380 --> 01:29:23.020
[Guest]: base and be wedded to it for all time. So that's my governing theory.

01:29:23.020 --> 01:29:27.660
[Amit Varma]: So I'll just think aloud here. And because I'm thinking aloud, what I say might be somewhat

01:29:27.660 --> 01:29:32.300
[Amit Varma]: naive, but then it seems to me that one could say that at the extremes, there are two kind

01:29:32.300 --> 01:29:36.020
[Amit Varma]: of broad ways of figuring the world out. And one is that you have a grand theory and you

01:29:36.020 --> 01:29:40.980
[Amit Varma]: make everything fit. And the other one is that you have no grand theories, but you get

01:29:40.980 --> 01:29:44.740
[Amit Varma]: in the nitty gritties of every problem. You solve one problem at a time and eventually

01:29:44.740 --> 01:29:49.860
[Amit Varma]: whatever intermediate theories, as it were, emerge and whatever grand theories are useful

01:29:49.860 --> 01:29:53.900
[Amit Varma]: at a particular moment in time to explain something are fine. And it seems to me that

01:29:53.900 --> 01:29:58.580
[Amit Varma]: you would then have taken the second of these approaches where you are not sort of guided

01:29:58.580 --> 01:30:03.100
[Amit Varma]: by a particular way of explaining the world, but you're just trying to figure small things

01:30:03.100 --> 01:30:08.900
[Amit Varma]: out and seeing where they kind of lead you. So, you know, would this kind of be, therefore,

01:30:08.900 --> 01:30:13.200
[Amit Varma]: an accurate way of summing up the different approaches? And are these different approaches

01:30:13.200 --> 01:30:18.140
[Amit Varma]: something that exists out of a thought experiment? Are there people you can actually look at?

01:30:18.140 --> 01:30:22.340
[Amit Varma]: Maybe this ties into the fox and hedgehog sort of description of Isaiah Berlin.

01:30:22.340 --> 01:30:24.380
[Amit Varma]: Exactly. I was going to say, yeah.

01:30:24.380 --> 01:30:27.580
[Amit Varma]: Yeah. So, so is it there within academics as well, for example?

01:30:27.580 --> 01:30:31.340
[Guest]: Yeah, absolutely. I mean, I think, you know, as you were speaking and before you uttered

01:30:31.340 --> 01:30:36.580
[Guest]: those words, I was going to say, yeah, Isaiah Berlin, hedgehog and the fox, where the hedgehog

01:30:36.580 --> 01:30:41.980
[Guest]: knows only one thing, if I get it right. And the fox is slower, but it knows many things

01:30:41.980 --> 01:30:47.060
[Guest]: and it, or it tries to do many things. And I guess I'm more a fox and I would wear that

01:30:47.060 --> 01:30:52.460
[Guest]: as a bit of a badge of honor. But again, the world needs both kinds of people. And I just

01:30:52.460 --> 01:30:59.580
[Guest]: hate monocultures. And so we need hedgehogs and we need foxes. And sometimes we need to

01:30:59.580 --> 01:31:05.740
[Guest]: be hedgehogs and sometimes we need to be foxes. So even I wouldn't typify myself totally and

01:31:05.740 --> 01:31:10.540
[Guest]: forever as a fox. There are times when I've been a hedgehog. I mean, for, for some time

01:31:10.540 --> 01:31:15.940
[Guest]: in the 1980s, 1990s, particularly, I became a hedgehog. I was obsessed with the issue

01:31:15.940 --> 01:31:20.620
[Guest]: of India's nuclear weapons and deterrence, and that's all I cared about. And I got very

01:31:20.620 --> 01:31:27.300
[Guest]: argumentative and bolshie over it. I think I became a bit of a bore and, you know, I

01:31:27.300 --> 01:31:32.540
[Guest]: bored myself at some point and I think things moved on and quite rightly. And I had to go

01:31:32.540 --> 01:31:39.340
[Guest]: back to being more of a fox and I'm glad I did. And so, yeah, we need both kinds of people.

01:31:39.340 --> 01:31:44.520
[Guest]: And broadly, I think Berlin was right. You can, you can divide the world up into hedgehogs

01:31:44.520 --> 01:31:49.780
[Guest]: and foxes and your own persona. At times you're a hedgehog and times at other times you're

01:31:49.780 --> 01:31:54.980
[Guest]: a fox. And I think that's fine. I think that's, that's good for the world.

01:31:54.980 --> 01:31:58.260
[Amit Varma]: And again, thinking aloud, I wonder if the imperatives of the role that you give yourself

01:31:58.260 --> 01:32:02.340
[Amit Varma]: actually shape you in one direction or the other. For example, if you're a TV expert,

01:32:02.340 --> 01:32:06.620
[Amit Varma]: TV experts are supposed to have certainty about the world. So you would imagine a TV

01:32:06.620 --> 01:32:10.940
[Amit Varma]: expert would be a hedgehog like Harry Truman when he when he was president once said, give

01:32:10.940 --> 01:32:14.680
[Amit Varma]: me a one handed economist. And obviously, the reason he said that was all his advisors

01:32:14.680 --> 01:32:18.100
[Amit Varma]: were saying on the one hand this on the other hand that and he wanted a hedgehog that just

01:32:18.100 --> 01:32:23.340
[Amit Varma]: tell me what to do tell me that this is the way to go. It strikes me that then there is

01:32:23.340 --> 01:32:28.680
[Amit Varma]: this sort of dual imperative that on the one hand, as an academic, you do want to have

01:32:28.680 --> 01:32:32.940
[Amit Varma]: intellectual humility, not be tied down to any one idea and be a bit of a fox. But at

01:32:32.940 --> 01:32:38.540
[Amit Varma]: the same time as an academic, if you want your ideas to be part of the mainstream discourse,

01:32:38.540 --> 01:32:43.140
[Amit Varma]: then you do want to be a bit of a public intellectual. But being a public intellectual, you'll gain

01:32:43.140 --> 01:32:48.140
[Amit Varma]: as much visibility as as much as you can be a hedgehog because people crave certainty

01:32:48.140 --> 01:32:53.340
[Amit Varma]: people don't, you know, crave nuance. So is that something that you've thought about? Or

01:32:53.340 --> 01:32:57.060
[Amit Varma]: is that something that when you look around you and you see public intellectuals or you

01:32:57.060 --> 01:33:01.500
[Amit Varma]: followed their journeys as academics to a particular place? Do you see that kind of

01:33:01.500 --> 01:33:03.460
[Amit Varma]: sort of tussle happening within them?

01:33:03.460 --> 01:33:09.940
[Guest]: I do. I mean, and as I said, I mean, society needs both kinds of people. And so it's right

01:33:09.940 --> 01:33:14.780
[Guest]: and proper that there are those who are the hedgehogs and they have a very certain worldview,

01:33:14.780 --> 01:33:19.940
[Guest]: they express themselves very unambiguously. They tell us how we should proceed. And we

01:33:19.940 --> 01:33:27.260
[Guest]: need that in times of crises, and so on. And they often lead us in whichever field, including

01:33:27.260 --> 01:33:32.860
[Guest]: the political field. But as a check and balance, we need foxes. And I think that's important

01:33:32.860 --> 01:33:37.420
[Guest]: as well. And there are times when I've been a hedgehog, my children would probably say

01:33:37.420 --> 01:33:44.580
[Guest]: that I was too often at home, but and sometimes I'm impatient with myself. And I think, well,

01:33:44.580 --> 01:33:50.140
[Guest]: both in academic life, and in public intellectual life, I should have been more of a fox or

01:33:50.140 --> 01:33:56.340
[Guest]: certainly my television experience forced me towards being a hedgehog. And sometimes

01:33:56.340 --> 01:34:01.700
[Guest]: my brother who was in television used to say, don't do this. On the one hand, on the other

01:34:01.700 --> 01:34:07.820
[Guest]: hand, I mean, and I stick to a view, you've got 30 seconds before the anchor interrupts

01:34:07.820 --> 01:34:12.540
[Guest]: you. And there's no time for that. If you want to make an impact, be blunt. And I think

01:34:12.540 --> 01:34:16.940
[Guest]: there's place for that. And I tried to do it. But it was never quite me, I think. And

01:34:16.940 --> 01:34:21.260
[Guest]: I think there are people who read me that way. I did a, you know, an interview with

01:34:21.260 --> 01:34:25.780
[Guest]: a student of mine, who's now in Australia yesterday. And he said that, you know, a lot

01:34:25.780 --> 01:34:30.420
[Guest]: of former students of mine, who were never very happy with my political stance in India,

01:34:30.420 --> 01:34:36.900
[Guest]: thought that I was a dyed in the wool, peacenik, liberal, secularist, and I couldn't listen

01:34:36.900 --> 01:34:42.220
[Guest]: to anyone else. I don't know. I mean, I must have come across like that. And some part

01:34:42.220 --> 01:34:49.660
[Guest]: of me is that, that I do hold those values dear. And sometimes I do get on my horse and

01:34:49.660 --> 01:34:55.500
[Guest]: insist on that. But I think deep down, I'm willing to listen and adjust and think things

01:34:55.500 --> 01:35:02.020
[Guest]: through and, of course, be persuaded and so on, that I'm not the last word by any means,

01:35:02.020 --> 01:35:08.540
[Guest]: and I don't know all the answers. So I think that's important. And, you know, I mean, cometh

01:35:08.540 --> 01:35:13.420
[Guest]: the hour, cometh the man, cometh the hour, cometh the stance. There are some times when

01:35:13.420 --> 01:35:20.980
[Guest]: you might just have to take a stand and take the risk of holding to, hewing to a point

01:35:20.980 --> 01:35:27.180
[Guest]: of view and sticking to it. And you probably know that moment when it comes. And I think

01:35:27.180 --> 01:35:33.300
[Guest]: you have to rely on your instinct and your ratucination at that point to tell you, here,

01:35:33.300 --> 01:35:39.220
[Guest]: I have to take a stand. There's nothing else. And I can't listen to too much nuance and

01:35:39.220 --> 01:35:44.140
[Guest]: all of that. I've just got to stand for something. But that can't be a permanent position, it

01:35:44.140 --> 01:35:49.220
[Guest]: seems to me. So I think I'll just let it wash over me. When I feel I absolutely have to

01:35:49.220 --> 01:35:55.060
[Guest]: take that stand, I will. Does that mean that I'm the person that you would always call

01:35:55.060 --> 01:36:01.020
[Guest]: up in a crisis or to sign a petition or to stand shoulder to shoulder on an issue and

01:36:01.020 --> 01:36:06.540
[Guest]: all of that? Yes, no, maybe, I don't know. That's someone else's judgment. But I think

01:36:06.540 --> 01:36:11.740
[Guest]: more and more to myself, I'll have to take the risk of making those judgments as and

01:36:11.740 --> 01:36:15.060
[Guest]: when you know, the moment comes.

01:36:15.060 --> 01:36:18.260
[Amit Varma]: You know, and just again, thinking aloud, I'd say that, you know, the way I sort of

01:36:18.260 --> 01:36:22.060
[Amit Varma]: determined this for myself is that when it comes to values, I'm a hedgehog, you know,

01:36:22.060 --> 01:36:25.900
[Amit Varma]: there are certain things I believe in, and I'm unequivocal, and I have certainty of those

01:36:25.900 --> 01:36:29.980
[Amit Varma]: and, you know, individual rights and personal autonomy and all of those things, whatever

01:36:29.980 --> 01:36:34.860
[Amit Varma]: they are. But when it comes to facts, then I'm a fox, I'm willing to, you know, consider

01:36:34.860 --> 01:36:39.140
[Amit Varma]: different interpretations and different versions of events. And I'm always open. So I don't

01:36:39.140 --> 01:36:42.900
[Amit Varma]: have one big theory that kind of explains the world. But when it comes to values, I

01:36:42.900 --> 01:36:48.020
[Amit Varma]: do have a very clear idea of what I stand for. We'll go in for a quick commercial break

