[Amit Varma]: beginning with, you know, looking at civil military relations and all of that. And I

01:38:34.140 --> 01:38:38.440
[Amit Varma]: presume during this phase, you would have studied the 62 war and all of that. When did

01:38:38.440 --> 01:38:43.540
[Amit Varma]: you really start looking at China closely and start sort of refining your prisms and

01:38:43.540 --> 01:38:48.900
[Amit Varma]: also this entire period when you've been an academic is a period of almost tectonic change

01:38:48.900 --> 01:38:53.620
[Amit Varma]: in both China and India in different ways, where just so much has changed. And at the

01:38:53.620 --> 01:38:58.380
[Amit Varma]: same time, how has a scholarship been changing? How has you know, within the academic world,

01:38:58.380 --> 01:39:02.540
[Amit Varma]: for example, is it a danger that there are fashions in terms of ways of looking at a

01:39:02.540 --> 01:39:06.860
[Amit Varma]: particular subject or a subject area? How has that been evolving? When did you start

01:39:06.860 --> 01:39:10.820
[Amit Varma]: getting into it? How did your thinking on it evolve as the years went by?

01:39:10.820 --> 01:39:16.420
[Guest]: Yeah, so you know, you pointed out that in the book in 1962, my dad was a diplomat in

01:39:16.420 --> 01:39:21.380
[Guest]: in London in the High Commission. And at the time of the war, it was sepulchral at home.

01:39:21.380 --> 01:39:26.020
[Guest]: It was not that we talked about the war a lot. In fact, it was the opposite. There was

01:39:26.020 --> 01:39:32.820
[Guest]: just a kind of gloomy silence in cold London during those weeks. And, and so I think, you

01:39:32.820 --> 01:39:39.620
[Guest]: know, something like all Indians, the war has left a bit of a scar and a vestige in

01:39:39.620 --> 01:39:46.660
[Guest]: our, in our, you know, memories and hearts. And I think the Chinese don't quite get it.

01:39:46.660 --> 01:39:51.780
[Guest]: But it's there in most Indians, at least to the elite, middle class type of people. So

01:39:51.780 --> 01:39:56.820
[Guest]: I suppose it was there in me. And, but my focus, as I was explaining earlier, was really

01:39:56.820 --> 01:40:03.420
[Guest]: much more India, Pakistan, and South Asia, and the prospects of cooperation and the possibilities

01:40:03.420 --> 01:40:09.380
[Guest]: of conflict there. So China was not a big thing. Although, in the early 90s, I wrote

01:40:09.380 --> 01:40:13.740
[Guest]: some stuff on, well, two or three things happened. The first was, somebody asked me to write

01:40:13.740 --> 01:40:19.140
[Guest]: on confidence building measures, this idea that countries that were locked into conflict

01:40:19.140 --> 01:40:24.020
[Guest]: could through some forms of communication and transparency, ensure that they didn't

01:40:24.020 --> 01:40:30.940
[Guest]: get into a scrap militarily, unwittingly, that out of uncertainty and miscommunication,

01:40:30.940 --> 01:40:37.580
[Guest]: at least you wouldn't fight. And so military talks, better diplomatic contacts, arrangements

01:40:37.580 --> 01:40:44.060
[Guest]: like that would ensure that it didn't happen unwittingly. So I wrote a piece on that. But

01:40:44.060 --> 01:40:50.180
[Guest]: again, drifted back to South Asian issues, particularly the nuclear issue. But Abid Hussain,

01:40:50.180 --> 01:40:57.260
[Guest]: actually, you know, coming back to him, put it in my brain, I think a little bit, that

01:40:57.260 --> 01:41:04.940
[Guest]: China had to be watched. He was very liberal, but he began to focus on this issue of India's

01:41:04.940 --> 01:41:11.060
[Guest]: economic reforms, and how India had to get out of Hindu rate of growth and so on. And,

01:41:11.060 --> 01:41:16.500
[Guest]: you know, this is the period of 1992, 93. The economic reforms had just begun after

01:41:16.500 --> 01:41:22.500
[Guest]: the crisis. And he was looking at China, and asking the question, how come they've done

01:41:22.500 --> 01:41:28.620
[Guest]: so well, and India lagged behind. So talking to him and helping him write some speeches

01:41:28.620 --> 01:41:34.580
[Guest]: and so on. My friend and colleague Varun Saini, who is now Vice Chancellor of Goa University,

01:41:34.580 --> 01:41:38.980
[Guest]: we were part of his little kitchen cabinet, where we would toss issues around. And he

01:41:38.980 --> 01:41:43.660
[Guest]: was constantly talking about India's prospects. And we would look sideways at China. And one

01:41:43.660 --> 01:41:48.980
[Guest]: time we were visited by quite a high level delegation of think tankers and academics

01:41:48.980 --> 01:41:55.580
[Guest]: from China. And what struck us there was how much more work on India there was in China

01:41:55.580 --> 01:42:02.620
[Guest]: than there was in India about China. And I remember in the meeting there, in Hindi, Abid

01:42:02.620 --> 01:42:07.780
[Guest]: just said to me, and he said, they've got so many people who have learned Hindi and

01:42:07.780 --> 01:42:14.820
[Guest]: Indian languages. You know who can speak Mandarin? And I didn't know the answer quite, but I

01:42:14.820 --> 01:42:19.620
[Guest]: said, I don't know. I mean, through the various programs, maybe we could get 20-25 people

01:42:19.620 --> 01:42:28.740
[Guest]: outside of the diplomats who had learned Mandarin in China. And he said, I'll have to fake the

01:42:28.740 --> 01:42:33.540
[Guest]: figure a bit. Otherwise, it looked very embarrassing. So China was beginning to seep in. And he

01:42:33.540 --> 01:42:39.580
[Guest]: was always talking about globalization and how China had taken advantage of it, and India

01:42:39.580 --> 01:42:44.460
[Guest]: had got left behind. And from that, Varun and I both began to think and write a little

01:42:44.460 --> 01:42:49.520
[Guest]: bit about how India would begin to try and maybe catch up with China. What kind of growth

01:42:49.520 --> 01:42:54.380
[Guest]: rates would we need? We didn't write a lot about it, but here and there. And I think

01:42:54.380 --> 01:43:00.020
[Guest]: that thought stayed with me. And I think I wrote some pieces at that time, late 90s,

01:43:00.020 --> 01:43:06.500
[Guest]: middle 90s, about the gap already with China was beginning to be very significant. And

01:43:06.500 --> 01:43:10.540
[Guest]: what would be the implications of that? And then I think that went into cold storage.

01:43:10.540 --> 01:43:15.540
[Guest]: I went back to the nuclear tests and Pakistan and so on and so forth. And then when I finished

01:43:15.540 --> 01:43:20.500
[Guest]: Doon School, I went to Oxford. Instead of going back to JNU, I had an invitation to

01:43:20.500 --> 01:43:27.540
[Guest]: come to Singapore, but I chose to go to Oxford at that time. And there, I found that a lot

01:43:27.540 --> 01:43:33.980
[Guest]: of the kind of excitement was over China and its rise in a way that I hadn't appreciated

01:43:33.980 --> 01:43:39.580
[Guest]: being at Doon School and dealing with South Asian issues so much. China was in everyone's

01:43:39.580 --> 01:43:45.860
[Guest]: lips all the time in a way that India certainly was not. And it just struck me then more and

01:43:45.860 --> 01:43:50.500
[Guest]: more. And then another one of those phone calls came along. I got a call from my old

01:43:50.500 --> 01:43:54.860
[Guest]: friend Kishore Mebubani, who I had met at Harvard many years earlier at a conference

01:43:54.860 --> 01:44:01.100
[Guest]: on civilizational conflict, which Sam Huntington had organized. And he wrote the paper on Southeast

01:44:01.100 --> 01:44:06.700
[Guest]: Asia and civilization issues, and I wrote the paper on India. Anyway, he had asked me

01:44:06.700 --> 01:44:11.640
[Guest]: earlier whether I had wanted to come and teach at Singapore, at least for a couple of years,

01:44:11.640 --> 01:44:17.060
[Guest]: when I had chosen Oxford at that time. But he persisted. He said, you know, China is

01:44:17.060 --> 01:44:21.100
[Guest]: the big issue. Sitting here in Southeast Asia, we can see it even more clearly than you can

01:44:21.100 --> 01:44:25.060
[Guest]: see it sitting in Oxford. And by the way, this is the place to think about and study

01:44:25.060 --> 01:44:31.900
[Guest]: China and India-China. And why don't you come here instead? And various things happened,

01:44:31.900 --> 01:44:36.700
[Guest]: and there's a story there. But at some point, that was part of the reason that I made the

01:44:36.700 --> 01:44:41.700
[Guest]: move to Singapore. And of course, once I made the move to Singapore, it was China, China,

01:44:41.700 --> 01:44:45.900
[Guest]: China, but also, very importantly, quite a lot of interest in India in a way that was

01:44:45.900 --> 01:44:52.220
[Guest]: not true, oddly enough, in Oxford. Those two things came together, and Kishore played a

01:44:52.220 --> 01:44:58.580
[Guest]: big part in sort of pushing me more in that direction of develop this idea of India-China

01:44:58.580 --> 01:45:05.820
[Guest]: relations, cooperation, and in the shadow of conflict. And I suppose that's what really

01:45:05.820 --> 01:45:10.540
[Guest]: then brewed and brewed. And I did various things here to take forward an India-China

01:45:10.540 --> 01:45:16.060
[Guest]: agenda, which I could talk about if you're interested. But in a way, that led up to the

01:45:16.060 --> 01:45:20.980
[Guest]: moment when I got that other phone call, which is from Nandini Mehta on behalf of Chicky

01:45:20.980 --> 01:45:25.660
[Guest]: Sarkar to write this book on India-China relations.

01:45:25.660 --> 01:45:29.740
[Amit Varma]: That's fascinating. I've just read one book by Kishore, which has a provocative title

01:45:29.740 --> 01:45:34.700
[Amit Varma]: of Can Asians Think? I read it a couple of decades ago. And I noticed just now, you know,

01:45:34.700 --> 01:45:37.500
[Amit Varma]: I couldn't remember the name of the book that I've read. So I googled that and I noticed

01:45:37.500 --> 01:45:43.100
[Amit Varma]: his latest book is called, Has China Won? Which is also a provocative title, good titles

01:45:43.100 --> 01:45:47.780
[Amit Varma]: for books. Do tell me more about the India-China agenda. I'm very curious, like, first of all,

01:45:47.780 --> 01:45:53.660
[Amit Varma]: to begin with, in Singapore, how different would the gaze on China be? Because it's physically

01:45:53.660 --> 01:45:58.420
[Amit Varma]: much closer, because I guess there is much greater access to insiders and to Chinese

01:45:58.420 --> 01:46:03.540
[Amit Varma]: scholars and all of that. And how did your interest develop here? What are the areas

01:46:03.540 --> 01:46:07.020
[Amit Varma]: you were looking at? This is quite fascinating. So do tell me more.

01:46:07.020 --> 01:46:11.980
[Guest]: Yeah, sorry. So one part of your earlier question I didn't answer, which was kind of the thought

01:46:11.980 --> 01:46:16.780
[Guest]: process about how to think about China academically and so on. So I think in certainly when I

01:46:16.780 --> 01:46:23.500
[Guest]: was at Oxford and earlier, the burden of scholarship was China's peaceful rise, and seemed to be

01:46:23.500 --> 01:46:30.380
[Guest]: going well. And the idea was how to continue to bring China into kind of a liberal international

01:46:30.380 --> 01:46:35.740
[Guest]: order. And the prospects seemed quite good through trade, China was joining all these

01:46:35.740 --> 01:46:41.060
[Guest]: international institutions. And so the narrative was all good. I mean, there was uneasiness

01:46:41.060 --> 01:46:46.020
[Guest]: here and there and particular episodes where China was a bit more aggressive. But on the

01:46:46.020 --> 01:46:50.460
[Guest]: whole, there was a sense that, you know, China was rising peacefully and would play a more

01:46:50.460 --> 01:46:57.620
[Guest]: or less responsible role. But I think that Singapore did partake of that. But Singapore

01:46:57.620 --> 01:47:04.900
[Guest]: has always had its weather vanes or antenna up and sensitive to other perspectives and

01:47:04.900 --> 01:47:11.580
[Guest]: possibilities. And I think Singapore certainly wants to ensure that exactly that happens,

01:47:11.580 --> 01:47:17.460
[Guest]: that China rises peacefully, it's accommodated appropriately, and that it is socialized into

01:47:17.460 --> 01:47:23.780
[Guest]: this more or less rules-based liberal order. But it's always had a worry that that might

01:47:23.780 --> 01:47:29.780
[Guest]: not happen, that other countries might provoke China beyond a point, or that things might

01:47:29.780 --> 01:47:35.580
[Guest]: develop within China that would deflect us from that. So I think that I kind of followed

01:47:35.580 --> 01:47:41.780
[Guest]: that trajectory, which is, I went from quite a complacent attitude towards where China

01:47:41.780 --> 01:47:48.520
[Guest]: was in the world. I mean, when I was charting this idea of China's growth and what it implied,

01:47:48.520 --> 01:47:54.140
[Guest]: it was more, how could India reach those kinds of growth rates and catch up, but not from

01:47:54.140 --> 01:47:58.900
[Guest]: a very alarmist point of view, you know. And I think that fitted in with this kind of China

01:47:58.900 --> 01:48:02.980
[Guest]: rise thesis that was prevalent everywhere as well. There were lessons to be learned

01:48:02.980 --> 01:48:08.660
[Guest]: from China, and then China was to be accommodated in a correct way, not to be appeased, but

01:48:08.660 --> 01:48:14.220
[Guest]: to be accommodated where appropriate. I think in Singapore, there was already a sense that

01:48:14.220 --> 01:48:20.140
[Guest]: that might not quite work out, and so one had to give thought to something else. But

01:48:20.140 --> 01:48:26.900
[Guest]: of course, Singapore itself very much needs and wants and hopes that China will be peaceful

01:48:26.900 --> 01:48:33.060
[Guest]: and it'll be accommodated in the right way. And it has friendships with the West and friendships

01:48:33.060 --> 01:48:39.740
[Guest]: with China, and it tries to, you know, reconcile that. So when I came here, I think I began

01:48:39.740 --> 01:48:46.340
[Guest]: to look a bit more at the arguments for why the rise may not be altogether peaceful. And

01:48:46.340 --> 01:48:51.420
[Guest]: in the context of India-China, where I'd been a bit more complacent, I began to think that

01:48:51.420 --> 01:48:57.660
[Guest]: everything may not be necessarily quite so smooth. I mean, I came here in 2010, 2011,

01:48:57.660 --> 01:49:01.240
[Guest]: and already there were signs that things were sharpening, although the relationship was

01:49:01.240 --> 01:49:05.900
[Guest]: not where it is today, of course. I think, and a lot of my colleagues look at China issues

01:49:05.900 --> 01:49:12.340
[Guest]: and there's a lively debate here on relations with China. And one of the things that Singapore

01:49:12.340 --> 01:49:17.460
[Guest]: deals with is that, of course, geographically, it's much more proximate to China. It's got

01:49:17.460 --> 01:49:23.920
[Guest]: a population that is 70% of Chinese ethnic origins, 70 plus. So there's another kind

01:49:23.920 --> 01:49:29.660
[Guest]: of relationship to China that goes beyond just geopolitics. There's an economic relationship

01:49:29.660 --> 01:49:34.980
[Guest]: to China, which is very vital, as it is for everyone in Southeast Asia. So, you know,

01:49:34.980 --> 01:49:41.980
[Guest]: I mean, thinking about China here is a very different ballgame. There are many other factors

01:49:41.980 --> 01:49:48.260
[Guest]: at play here. And what that suggests is that it's not just the China rise story. When you're

01:49:48.260 --> 01:49:56.380
[Guest]: in a region like Southeast Asia, the connective tissues are ethnic, diasporic, cultural, historical,

01:49:56.380 --> 01:50:02.700
[Guest]: very profoundly. They are questions of geography and the intimacies that come from that, which

01:50:02.700 --> 01:50:08.380
[Guest]: even a country, you know, such as India may not quite have because it's got the Himalayas

01:50:08.380 --> 01:50:13.620
[Guest]: in between. And certainly the Western countries don't have that kind of intimacy. So they

01:50:13.620 --> 01:50:19.340
[Guest]: look at China in a different kind of way. But this region must factor that in constantly

01:50:19.340 --> 01:50:25.940
[Guest]: when thinking about China. And they have many deep institutional links over the last 20,

01:50:25.940 --> 01:50:32.900
[Guest]: 30 years with China through many international institutions, ASEAN, East Asia Summit, APEC,

01:50:32.900 --> 01:50:39.020
[Guest]: bilateral dialogues, etc., etc., which India, at least until the last 10, 12 years, did

01:50:39.020 --> 01:50:43.700
[Guest]: not really have and which some Western countries, most of them don't have except for the United

01:50:43.700 --> 01:50:50.660
[Guest]: States. So I think that, you know, there are many more lenses through which you look at

01:50:50.660 --> 01:50:57.380
[Guest]: China here in Southeast Asia. And perhaps that's why, you know, my book also has these

01:50:57.380 --> 01:51:04.420
[Guest]: four different peas or lenses through which I look at India, China, the general ontology,

01:51:04.420 --> 01:51:10.820
[Guest]: you know, the broad way we think about a subject and its constituent parts. In this part of

01:51:10.820 --> 01:51:18.100
[Guest]: the world, it's a more pluralistic ontology of looking at China. And I think maybe some

01:51:18.100 --> 01:51:22.940
[Guest]: of that filtered into my book.

01:51:22.940 --> 01:51:26.780
[Amit Varma]: So we'll come to your book in a moment. But a final question about this sort of field

01:51:26.780 --> 01:51:30.940
[Amit Varma]: of India, China studies like it strikes me and I'm thinking aloud and you can tell me

01:51:30.940 --> 01:51:37.260
[Amit Varma]: to what extent this would be true. One, a lot of policy of countries is shaped by elites

01:51:37.260 --> 01:51:41.620
[Amit Varma]: in some way or the other. I mean, obviously, you know, politicians have incentives where

01:51:41.620 --> 01:51:45.200
[Amit Varma]: they've, you know, where more and more they have to be populist and they have to think

01:51:45.200 --> 01:51:49.620
[Amit Varma]: about what the people feel and popular sentiment and all of that. But a significant amount

01:51:49.620 --> 01:51:53.900
[Amit Varma]: of it is shaped by elites in most countries. That's number one. Number two, my premise

01:51:53.900 --> 01:51:59.540
[Amit Varma]: would be that, therefore, academics like yourself and academics in all the places where you've

01:51:59.540 --> 01:52:04.780
[Amit Varma]: taught and worked have some kind of influence. It's limited, but they have some kind of influence

01:52:04.780 --> 01:52:08.900
[Amit Varma]: that they will often consult for governments, they'll have, you know, entry points to talk

01:52:08.900 --> 01:52:13.580
[Amit Varma]: to babus and sometimes some politicians and all of that is there. And the third thing

01:52:13.580 --> 01:52:18.620
[Amit Varma]: that I'm then struck by is that whatever the extent of this elite shaping of public policy

01:52:18.620 --> 01:52:24.180
[Amit Varma]: might be in say countries like the USA, which has a rich tradition of think tanks and parties

01:52:24.180 --> 01:52:30.660
[Amit Varma]: feeding into the think tanks, and to a smaller extent in India, what is that extent in China?

01:52:30.660 --> 01:52:36.180
[Amit Varma]: Because China from the outside at least seems to be an incredibly opaque system, where you

01:52:36.180 --> 01:52:41.780
[Amit Varma]: know, the people in charge are not as accountable to the people as in these democracies. Though

01:52:41.780 --> 01:52:46.780
[Amit Varma]: as Manoj Kevalramani enlightened me in a previous episode that they do really care about what

01:52:46.780 --> 01:52:50.060
[Amit Varma]: the people think, and they're always trying to shape those narratives, but not in the

01:52:50.060 --> 01:52:55.300
[Amit Varma]: same way as in India, where there are elections all the time and so on. So how much of an

01:52:55.300 --> 01:53:01.980
[Amit Varma]: influence are thinkers and academics like yourself in even more of an ivory tower when

01:53:01.980 --> 01:53:07.460
[Amit Varma]: it comes to the context of policy within China, than they would be in the US and India. And

01:53:07.460 --> 01:53:11.060
[Amit Varma]: this seems kind of rambley again, I'm kind of thinking aloud. So excuse me if any of

01:53:11.060 --> 01:53:13.380
[Amit Varma]: these are just, you know, wrong assumptions.

01:53:13.380 --> 01:53:20.580
[Guest]: No, I think you've got a lot that's spot on there. I mean, I mean, first of all, academics,

01:53:20.580 --> 01:53:24.900
[Guest]: you know, I think we ourselves undermine our influence. But after all, we're the people

01:53:24.900 --> 01:53:30.540
[Guest]: who educated the people who run the country. We're the people who educate most of the elite,

01:53:30.540 --> 01:53:35.460
[Guest]: because they all go to colleges and universities. All the journalists who shape opinion, and

01:53:35.460 --> 01:53:41.300
[Guest]: the broadcasters all went through our hands, all the businessmen went through our hands.

01:53:41.300 --> 01:53:48.020
[Guest]: So I sometimes I'm very puzzled by this notion that academics are Lotus eaters, thumbsuckers

01:53:48.020 --> 01:53:54.140
[Guest]: out there somewhere in some ivory tower, you know, and that's all, they're kind of useless

01:53:54.140 --> 01:53:58.380
[Guest]: people who that we sort of tolerate them, they have a profound impact on how we think

01:53:58.380 --> 01:54:03.860
[Guest]: about issues, because they train people, and then those people go out and shape the world

01:54:03.860 --> 01:54:11.700
[Guest]: every day, and shape wider opinion. So it seems to me, on that point, academics everywhere,

01:54:11.700 --> 01:54:17.220
[Guest]: including in China, I mean, who in China has not been educated by an academic and the university

01:54:17.220 --> 01:54:24.020
[Guest]: structure there. So they're all products of that. And to that extent, I mean, their influence,

01:54:24.020 --> 01:54:30.660
[Guest]: the influence of academics is profound, lasting, and subtle. So I don't think we should ever

01:54:30.660 --> 01:54:37.100
[Guest]: undermine that kind of thought that they're important. I think in China, it would be a

01:54:37.100 --> 01:54:45.340
[Guest]: mistake to think that academics, public intellectuals, even journalists, and so on, social media,

01:54:45.340 --> 01:54:50.180
[Guest]: you know, that it doesn't have an impact. It very much does. I mean, this is my instinct.

01:54:50.180 --> 01:54:56.900
[Guest]: I am not a China specialist, per se. I haven't lived there. I visited several times, of course,

01:54:56.900 --> 01:55:02.620
[Guest]: I talked to Chinese colleagues, and you just get a sort of a sense of it, you know, reading

01:55:02.620 --> 01:55:07.660
[Guest]: their press and opinions and things like that. And then I teach Chinese students, we have

01:55:07.660 --> 01:55:13.100
[Guest]: a good number of Chinese students in my classes, and so on. I mean, it would be astonishing

01:55:13.100 --> 01:55:19.020
[Guest]: if Chinese people were not influenced by their academics, their media, their social media.

01:55:19.020 --> 01:55:24.180
[Guest]: I mean, they would be the most amazing people on earth if they were more or less impervious

01:55:24.180 --> 01:55:28.940
[Guest]: to it, no matter how much the government tries to control it. Indeed, their elites, the Communist

01:55:28.940 --> 01:55:34.900
[Guest]: Party, their rulers would be amazing people, like gods. And we know that even gods are

01:55:34.900 --> 01:55:40.300
[Guest]: influenced by human beings. So, you know, I mean, I'll just begin with the presumption

01:55:40.300 --> 01:55:46.100
[Guest]: that they lend an ear, they're influenced by, they can't separate themselves from the

01:55:46.100 --> 01:55:51.220
[Guest]: people and their thoughts. And I think they made it very clear over time that they are

01:55:51.220 --> 01:55:56.380
[Guest]: affected by those pressures and imperatives and, you know, what ordinary Chinese people

01:55:56.380 --> 01:56:02.900
[Guest]: may be saying. And we know that at the micro level in government in China, local protests,

01:56:02.900 --> 01:56:09.060
[Guest]: the interaction with local people, with the Communist Party and administration, I mean,

01:56:09.060 --> 01:56:18.020
[Guest]: they have an impact. And the Chinese Communist Party is extremely sensitive to what people

01:56:18.020 --> 01:56:22.740
[Guest]: out there think. I mean, they may not show it, they're not going to declare it, but they

01:56:22.740 --> 01:56:31.580
[Guest]: are extremely sensitive. And my instinct is that, particularly in India, this government

01:56:31.580 --> 01:56:41.420
[Guest]: is very, very attentive to how the Chinese Communist Party, as a party, has sent its

01:56:41.420 --> 01:56:50.340
[Guest]: influence and its kind of administrative tentacles to the smallest, most remote part of China.

01:56:50.340 --> 01:56:55.460
[Guest]: And those tentacles, tentacles may not be quite the right word, those arteries, I mean,

01:56:55.460 --> 01:57:02.980
[Guest]: they take ideas arterially out there, and a certain number of ideas and perceptions

01:57:02.980 --> 01:57:08.220
[Guest]: come back up through the arteries. And I think this government in India, particularly the

01:57:08.220 --> 01:57:16.300
[Guest]: BJP and its various affiliates, are quite intrigued by how well, in fact, there is this

01:57:16.300 --> 01:57:24.340
[Guest]: movement of ideas and thoughts from the party down to the micro level and back from the

01:57:24.340 --> 01:57:31.020
[Guest]: micro level in a constructive way to the to the party. And I think there's something there.

01:57:31.020 --> 01:57:35.500
[Guest]: It would be amazing again, if the Chinese Communist Party could, you know, just sit

01:57:35.500 --> 01:57:42.860
[Guest]: up there on these Olympian Heights, sending out famans and diktats and so on, and not

01:57:42.860 --> 01:57:48.140
[Guest]: bother to listen to anything that's out there. And that's not the history of Chinese political

01:57:48.140 --> 01:57:54.060
[Guest]: thought either. I think that there's much more going on at those levels, and the Chinese

01:57:54.060 --> 01:57:59.180
[Guest]: Communist Party is very attentive to it. And one of the difficulties, probably in respect

01:57:59.180 --> 01:58:04.180
[Guest]: of India-China relations and dealing with, let's say, the border issue, is that today

01:58:04.180 --> 01:58:11.780
[Guest]: you don't have a magisterial personality like Mao, or a super magisterial personality like

01:58:11.780 --> 01:58:17.660
[Guest]: Mao, or even Deng Xiaoping, who could swing a deal where China makes some significant

01:58:17.660 --> 01:58:23.140
[Guest]: concessions on the border with India in the way that they could have. I mean, Xi Jinping,

01:58:23.140 --> 01:58:27.380
[Guest]: he is magisterial in some ways. And, you know, we hear every day about how he's taken control

01:58:27.380 --> 01:58:33.220
[Guest]: and he's president or general secretary for life and all that kind of stuff. But I wonder,

01:58:33.220 --> 01:58:40.940
[Guest]: he's not Deng Xiaoping and he's not Mao. And he would, in a moment, if you could get him

01:58:40.940 --> 01:58:45.900
[Guest]: to really talk to you personally on the Amit Verma show like this, I think he would confess

01:58:45.900 --> 01:58:52.020
[Guest]: that he could not swing a deal necessarily as his predecessors, two or three of his predecessors

01:58:52.020 --> 01:58:59.020
[Guest]: could have. So I think there is an elite there. They can have an impact. And, you know, the

01:58:59.020 --> 01:59:05.220
[Guest]: thing about the elite is they're like the middle class. They connect upwards, sending

01:59:05.220 --> 01:59:12.620
[Guest]: ideas and feelings and perceptions up to the rulership. And they communicate downwards

01:59:12.620 --> 01:59:20.140
[Guest]: from the rulership to people below the elite, the masses, so-called ordinary folks. They're

01:59:20.140 --> 01:59:25.740
[Guest]: a vital element of a society just like the middle classes. So they both shape and are

01:59:25.740 --> 01:59:33.300
[Guest]: shaped by ideas. And I have no doubt that the elite there is a very powerful force.

01:59:33.300 --> 01:59:37.220
[Amit Varma]: That's a very interesting point about Xi and, you know, Modi not being able to sell concessions

01:59:37.220 --> 01:59:41.580
[Amit Varma]: to their people because, you know, in your book, you've mentioned Nehru and Mao and what

01:59:41.580 --> 01:59:47.500
[Amit Varma]: magisterial personalities they are. But even there you point out that in circa 57, 58 or

01:59:47.500 --> 01:59:51.420
[Amit Varma]: something like that, Nehru tried to push through his cabinet the proposal that the Chinese

01:59:51.420 --> 01:59:56.860
[Amit Varma]: be allowed open access to Aksai Chin so that they could get in and out of Tibet easily.

01:59:56.860 --> 01:59:59.900
[Amit Varma]: And this cabinet didn't let it go through. So eventually they allowed that access only

01:59:59.900 --> 02:00:05.100
[Amit Varma]: for civilian purposes. And that kind of remains a problem even now. So even back then when

02:00:05.100 --> 02:00:09.140
[Amit Varma]: these leaders were so strong and had the aura that they had, that there was a limit to how

02:00:09.140 --> 02:00:15.260
[Amit Varma]: much they could get through. And this seems a good time to kind of ask that meta question

02:00:15.260 --> 02:00:21.540
[Amit Varma]: about, you know, the constraint that politics holds upon actually having meaningful action

02:00:21.540 --> 02:00:25.740
[Amit Varma]: forward like you talk about elite influence. Now, China, obviously, everything you said

02:00:25.740 --> 02:00:29.420
[Amit Varma]: is very illuminating for me, because I don't know anything about China. But looking at

02:00:29.420 --> 02:00:33.180
[Amit Varma]: India, I'm not sure it's true, because none of the political class have actually been

02:00:33.180 --> 02:00:38.540
[Amit Varma]: educated by academics, despite, you know, Supreme Leader having a degree in entire political

02:00:38.540 --> 02:00:42.700
[Amit Varma]: science. And if there's any university whose ideas they have imbibed, it's really WhatsApp

02:00:42.700 --> 02:00:47.620
[Amit Varma]: University. And I'm kind of being flippant here. But it is also kind of true that when

02:00:47.620 --> 02:00:52.540
[Amit Varma]: you look at the underpinnings of the things that drive these guys, I don't see any of

02:00:52.540 --> 02:00:57.300
[Amit Varma]: that influence. For example, just today, and we are recording this on, let me check the

02:00:57.300 --> 02:01:03.500
[Amit Varma]: date on my computer, I'm so bad. It's July 9. And just today, Meenakshi Lekhi, who's

02:01:03.500 --> 02:01:10.220
[Amit Varma]: the new Minister of State for External Affairs, has said, quote, some have expertise in making

02:01:10.220 --> 02:01:16.340
[Amit Varma]: the virus, some in making vaccines. Now, this is a very jingoistic and incendiary thing

02:01:16.340 --> 02:01:20.900
[Amit Varma]: to say and totally not on for an external affairs minister, for God's sake, this is

02:01:20.900 --> 02:01:25.620
[Amit Varma]: not how we want to talk. And as you pointed out in the book, a lot of the Chinese attitudes

02:01:25.620 --> 02:01:30.380
[Amit Varma]: towards us are shaped by what they see in our media and how they interpret it. And when

02:01:30.380 --> 02:01:35.100
[Amit Varma]: they see a minister talking like this, that some make the virus, some make the vaccine,

02:01:35.100 --> 02:01:39.820
[Amit Varma]: it's just completely out of line. But this seems to me to be shaped by a certain kind

02:01:39.820 --> 02:01:44.860
[Amit Varma]: of jingoistic nationalistic rhetoric, which is popular on WhatsApp, devoid of reality,

02:01:44.860 --> 02:01:49.060
[Amit Varma]: something that no academic would support. And more and more, you get the sense that

02:01:49.060 --> 02:01:53.500
[Amit Varma]: our politicians can kind of drive themselves into a corner. Now, it is okay that we have

02:01:53.500 --> 02:01:58.340
[Amit Varma]: a skirmish with Pakistan. And you know, our leaders can sell the narrative that we did

02:01:58.340 --> 02:02:02.500
[Amit Varma]: a surgical strike where they basically bomb a few rocks. But when it comes to China, it's

02:02:02.500 --> 02:02:08.300
[Amit Varma]: a whole different ballgame. This kind of posturing can be extremely counterproductive, and just

02:02:08.300 --> 02:02:13.140
[Amit Varma]: takes us into the wrong direction. And then it becomes like a vicious circle. So one,

02:02:13.140 --> 02:02:17.900
[Amit Varma]: what would be your response to my counterpoint that, you know, even if there is some academic

02:02:17.900 --> 02:02:23.260
[Amit Varma]: influence on the way say bureaucrats may think, it's not there in politics. And this force

02:02:23.260 --> 02:02:29.220
[Amit Varma]: of domestic politics, this force of populism, and this particular kind of nationalism makes

02:02:29.220 --> 02:02:32.260
[Amit Varma]: a lot of other things that we might talk about, Moot.

02:02:32.260 --> 02:02:37.820
[Guest]: Yeah, I mean, I don't want to suggest that, you know, everyone has read that political

02:02:37.820 --> 02:02:43.980
[Guest]: science textbook or their economics textbook, and then, you know, really makes policy and

02:02:43.980 --> 02:02:49.740
[Guest]: even constructs a worldview out of that necessarily, and very easily. But just does seem to me that,

02:02:49.740 --> 02:02:54.340
[Guest]: you know, whether they acknowledge it or not, and sometimes they traduce what they learn,

02:02:54.340 --> 02:03:01.220
[Guest]: I mean, saying stupid things, despite your training is something that we've all done,

02:03:01.220 --> 02:03:07.300
[Guest]: including myself, I may know something intellectually, and then I've made all kinds of foolish remarks.

02:03:07.300 --> 02:03:12.100
[Guest]: And I think politicians are exactly like that as well. And of course, they may be more prone

02:03:12.100 --> 02:03:19.700
[Guest]: to display that because it might win them elections and so forth. But just still seems

02:03:19.700 --> 02:03:25.460
[Guest]: to me that at least a good part of what they mouth and so on has come from some branch

02:03:25.460 --> 02:03:32.500
[Guest]: of their training and thinking. And even what's mouthed on WhatsApp has come from people who

02:03:32.500 --> 02:03:37.620
[Guest]: were educated at universities and high schools and so forth. So, I mean, I guess I'm giving

02:03:37.620 --> 02:03:42.460
[Guest]: you a fairly prosaic answer, which is a literalist answer that, you know, you went through school

02:03:42.460 --> 02:03:47.460
[Guest]: and college, and so you picked up a vocabulary, which then allows you to make certain kinds

02:03:47.460 --> 02:03:52.340
[Guest]: of assertions and arguments, even on WhatsApp and in political life, which otherwise you

02:03:52.340 --> 02:03:59.820
[Guest]: couldn't possibly make. But yeah, I mean, I suppose my sense is that it's true that

02:03:59.820 --> 02:04:05.780
[Guest]: a little learning is worse than none. But on the whole, I would bet on education, university

02:04:05.780 --> 02:04:11.940
[Guest]: education in particular, still bringing us to a place of some moderation and thoughtfulness

02:04:11.940 --> 02:04:18.540
[Guest]: and progressiveness. And I wouldn't want a world where that possibility didn't exist.

02:04:18.540 --> 02:04:24.780
[Guest]: So it may be that leaders and elites, or particularly political leaders, are not as well schooled

02:04:24.780 --> 02:04:31.140
[Guest]: or as well educated as we academics would like, and they ignore their own training or

02:04:31.140 --> 02:04:36.500
[Guest]: the best thoughts that we try to communicate to them and instill in them. But that's the

02:04:36.500 --> 02:04:42.600
[Guest]: world, you know, and we as academics ourselves in our personal or micro social existences

02:04:42.600 --> 02:04:48.500
[Guest]: don't always live by the thoughts that we espouse. So I'm a bit more forgiving of politicians

02:04:48.500 --> 02:04:54.400
[Guest]: that way. Take nationalism, I mean, what else is nationalism, but, you know, a set of ideas

02:04:54.400 --> 02:04:59.780
[Guest]: that probably almost certainly were put together by sort of academics themselves, first of

02:04:59.780 --> 02:05:06.580
[Guest]: all, given the kind of modern shape that we today recognize as nationalism. If you trace

02:05:06.580 --> 02:05:12.620
[Guest]: the origins of nationalism to things like the development of national languages, I mean,

02:05:12.620 --> 02:05:18.780
[Guest]: Benedict Anderson, the famous historian, late historian, in his book, Imagined Communities,

02:05:18.780 --> 02:05:23.620
[Guest]: talks about, you know, the role of the kind of nationalization of a language, which is

02:05:23.620 --> 02:05:31.780
[Guest]: the dialects and so on were reduced and squeezed out. And mass education began to teach a standardized

02:05:31.780 --> 02:05:37.220
[Guest]: script and grammar and language. And that's such a powerful kind of vehicle for nationalism.

02:05:37.220 --> 02:05:41.820
[Guest]: It wasn't the only one. The book is much more interesting than that. But he does show that

02:05:41.820 --> 02:05:48.620
[Guest]: as other theorists and nationalists. And, you know, that was philologists and grammarians,

02:05:48.620 --> 02:05:55.380
[Guest]: who we would call academics, who did that. So, Ernest Renard, the historian, said that,

02:05:55.380 --> 02:06:00.620
[Guest]: you know, nationalism becomes possible through forgetting. And historians are also part of

02:06:00.620 --> 02:06:06.940
[Guest]: this forgetting. We band together as a people by forgetting some of the terrible things

02:06:06.940 --> 02:06:11.900
[Guest]: our co-nationalists once did to us back in the day. And I think historians play a role

02:06:11.900 --> 02:06:17.180
[Guest]: in that. They help us contextualize something that happened back in the day. We forget some

02:06:17.180 --> 02:06:23.100
[Guest]: of the hurt and anger that our forebears may have had, because we see what happened in

02:06:23.100 --> 02:06:29.340
[Guest]: some context, which is kind of a forgetting. We forget some part of the anger and the resentment

02:06:29.340 --> 02:06:35.460
[Guest]: we feel because of this larger context within which certain decisions and episodes occurred.

02:06:35.460 --> 02:06:40.660
[Guest]: And sometimes historians tell us that certain episodes that we think were central forget

02:06:40.660 --> 02:06:46.140
[Guest]: about them, because actually that wasn't the biggest thing at that time. So, yeah, I think

02:06:46.140 --> 02:06:51.540
[Guest]: historians have had a very big role in fostering this nationalism as well. I know we have historians

02:06:51.540 --> 02:06:59.700
[Guest]: in India. I mean, I'm not part of Indian historiography and its study, but very national historians,

02:06:59.700 --> 02:07:06.860
[Guest]: both of the right-wing and of the more liberal left-wing kind, who very much how we see nationalism

02:07:06.860 --> 02:07:11.820
[Guest]: today came out of their writings. So, again, I would say, you know, whether politicians

02:07:11.820 --> 02:07:17.140
[Guest]: understand it or not, they are mouthing the lines that academics have taught. And, you

02:07:17.140 --> 02:07:21.100
[Guest]: know, I mean, I guess it brings me to the larger point, which is that academics have

02:07:21.100 --> 02:07:28.460
[Guest]: an enormous responsibility. We can't keep criticizing politicians and lampooning them

02:07:28.460 --> 02:07:34.580
[Guest]: and caricaturing them, because we have helped make those leaders. It's our ideas that are

02:07:34.580 --> 02:07:41.860
[Guest]: being used out there, misused by politicians and other influencers. And we do have to be

02:07:41.860 --> 02:07:48.420
[Guest]: careful, I think. And perhaps the best thing we can always do is insist that, you know,

02:07:48.420 --> 02:07:53.700
[Guest]: well, if not a hundred flowers bloom, but a multiplicity of flowers are considered.

02:07:53.700 --> 02:07:58.820
[Guest]: And in our pedagogy and in our classrooms, at least convey that spirit of, even if you

02:07:58.820 --> 02:08:03.580
[Guest]: don't agree with something altogether, try and live that spirit of weighing up things

02:08:03.580 --> 02:08:09.660
[Guest]: and telling the other story and all of that. So, I certainly wouldn't exculpate academics

02:08:09.660 --> 02:08:11.700
[Guest]: from the things that are going wrong.

02:08:11.700 --> 02:08:16.620
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I mean, I have a couple of thoughts here. And one is about, you spoke about, you

02:08:16.620 --> 02:08:20.500
[Amit Varma]: know, the importance of history and memory. And at an individual level, you know, one

02:08:20.500 --> 02:08:24.940
[Amit Varma]: of my big learnings about memory, which I remember discussing also with Anshul Malhotra

02:08:24.940 --> 02:08:29.180
[Amit Varma]: in an episode I did with her, she's written this lovely book on partition of people remembering

02:08:29.180 --> 02:08:33.580
[Amit Varma]: through objects they've carried. And it's a big TIL learning about a memory for me,

02:08:33.580 --> 02:08:37.940
[Amit Varma]: because how memory apparently works is that when we remember an event, the first time

02:08:37.940 --> 02:08:41.780
[Amit Varma]: we remember an event, we remember the event. But the next time we remember it, we remember

02:08:41.780 --> 02:08:46.260
[Amit Varma]: the remembering of the event, and so on in a case of Chinese whispers in our brain, which

02:08:46.260 --> 02:08:50.060
[Amit Varma]: is why, you know, two people who shared the same experience can 10 years later remember

02:08:50.060 --> 02:08:55.660
[Amit Varma]: it completely differently, because each remembering it has altered a bit because of so many other

02:08:55.660 --> 02:09:00.940
[Amit Varma]: factors. And that seems to me to be the case, in a sense with a collective memory, also

02:09:00.940 --> 02:09:05.460
[Amit Varma]: historical grievances that a lot of the grievances that we have that the Mughals did this, or

02:09:05.460 --> 02:09:09.060
[Amit Varma]: so and so did this, or so and so did that, you know, I don't even see why they should

02:09:09.060 --> 02:09:13.460
[Amit Varma]: be relevant to us in the modern day. But we have these simplistic history, which then

02:09:13.460 --> 02:09:20.100
[Amit Varma]: create these simplistic sort of grievances, which feed into the things that we do today.

02:09:20.100 --> 02:09:27.300
[Amit Varma]: And the other aspect of it is the aspect of where academics are important in sort of keeping

02:09:27.300 --> 02:09:32.220
[Amit Varma]: the those dialogues and you know, that nuance alive, like you mentioned nationalism. Now,

02:09:32.220 --> 02:09:36.060
[Amit Varma]: in the last episode I recorded with Pranay Kotasane, which is coming out after we are

02:09:36.060 --> 02:09:40.340
[Amit Varma]: recording this, so it's not out yet. He spoke about how one of his favorite books is the

02:09:40.340 --> 02:09:45.860
[Amit Varma]: Gandhi Tagore debates. And you have mentioned in your book, and I'll quote those lines where

02:09:45.860 --> 02:09:51.700
[Amit Varma]: you write about how Gandhi and Tagore and one matter on which they agreed, viewed nationalism,

02:09:51.700 --> 02:09:56.020
[Amit Varma]: where you have written, quote, especially for Tagore and Gandhi, nationalism is both

02:09:56.020 --> 02:10:01.140
[Amit Varma]: emancipatory from colonial rule and oppressive. It encourages individuals to sacrifice their

02:10:01.140 --> 02:10:06.180
[Amit Varma]: creativity and moral sense for the collective and to make excuses for social violence. States

02:10:06.180 --> 02:10:11.380
[Amit Varma]: built on nationalism are inevitable, but for both Tagore and Gandhi, individual self-restraint

02:10:11.380 --> 02:10:16.020
[Amit Varma]: and moral behavior are the key to peace and order. If you all respected certain norms

02:10:16.020 --> 02:10:20.340
[Amit Varma]: of behavior towards each other, irrespective of nationality, governments and states would

02:10:20.340 --> 02:10:25.860
[Amit Varma]: become largely irrelevant, stop quote. And it's a sort of a broad sort of view of nationalism,

02:10:25.860 --> 02:10:33.300
[Amit Varma]: which encompasses more than, you know, our current narrow divisive visions of it. Let's

02:10:33.300 --> 02:10:38.540
[Amit Varma]: come to the book, because otherwise, your publisher Chiki will get extremely upset if

02:10:38.540 --> 02:10:42.380
[Amit Varma]: you don't discuss a book at all. So let's actually talk about this framework, which

02:10:42.380 --> 02:10:48.700
[Amit Varma]: I found so fascinating, the four P's. So tell me a bit about the four P's. And how did you

02:10:48.700 --> 02:10:52.140
[Amit Varma]: arrive at the framework? Did it happen over a period of years? Or did you start thinking

02:10:52.140 --> 02:10:57.780
[Amit Varma]: about this book? And then, as you started making your notes, this came to you, how did

02:10:57.780 --> 02:11:01.420
[Amit Varma]: it happen? And then, you know, we can begin with the first of the P's maybe.

02:11:01.420 --> 02:11:07.420
[Guest]: Well, it happened with a fifth P, which is panic. I guess in conversation with Jagannath,

02:11:07.420 --> 02:11:12.500
[Guest]: set myself such a big list of things I was saying earlier, you know, river water issues

02:11:12.500 --> 02:11:18.980
[Guest]: with China, trade issues with China, our influence in third regions with China, Pakistan, another

02:11:18.980 --> 02:11:24.100
[Guest]: P. And the list was just getting bigger and bigger. And I was getting more and more panicky,

02:11:24.100 --> 02:11:28.540
[Guest]: because on some topics, I thought, oh, my gosh, if I have to cover all of these, first

02:11:28.540 --> 02:11:33.020
[Guest]: of all, the length of the book, how will I accommodate them? But secondly, I'll either

02:11:33.020 --> 02:11:38.380
[Guest]: write some pablum, another P, something so boring that, you know, everyone knows already,

02:11:38.380 --> 02:11:43.580
[Guest]: or, you know, I would have enough to say. And some chapters will be humongous, like

02:11:43.580 --> 02:11:47.780
[Guest]: the perimeters chapter, which is about the border into where, and in others, I'll be

02:11:47.780 --> 02:11:52.900
[Guest]: muttering something for about four or five pages, and then I'll be done. And it'll look

02:11:52.900 --> 02:11:58.220
[Guest]: very odd, the book will be imbalanced, you know. So out of that panic about, oh, my God,

02:11:58.220 --> 02:12:03.740
[Guest]: the time was ticking. So I think about three or four weeks into the book, I began with

02:12:03.740 --> 02:12:07.380
[Guest]: what I knew already, the perimeter, the border issue, that's where I started. So I thought

02:12:07.380 --> 02:12:11.060
[Guest]: that would be chapter one, turned out to be chapter two, eventually. And I thought the

02:12:11.060 --> 02:12:15.420
[Guest]: power chapter had to be done, obviously, weighing up the relative power of the two. So those

02:12:15.420 --> 02:12:21.060
[Guest]: two were very clear. So I started in the Steve Cohen mode, just start writing, don't think

02:12:21.060 --> 02:12:26.900
[Guest]: about it too much, start getting stuff on paper. So I started that way. And then I had

02:12:26.900 --> 02:12:32.220
[Guest]: fingers crossed that other things would fall by the wayside or fall into place as I went

02:12:32.220 --> 02:12:36.860
[Guest]: along. And I guess, in a way, that's what happened. Out of that panic and beginning

02:12:36.860 --> 02:12:42.280
[Guest]: with what I knew, slowly it dawned on me that the length of these chapters, I was already

02:12:42.280 --> 02:12:47.700
[Guest]: getting to the halfway point of the book, it didn't lend itself to too many more chapters.

02:12:47.700 --> 02:12:55.340
[Guest]: So I had to start to squeeze down. And then I began to sort of just play it backwards

02:12:55.340 --> 02:12:59.580
[Guest]: from what I knew to what I would declare to be a virtue, which is, you know, what did

02:12:59.580 --> 02:13:04.420
[Guest]: I know best? And what could I write about that would be most interesting to me and possibly

02:13:04.420 --> 02:13:10.740
[Guest]: to a reader, to what ought to be properly in the book, rather than some grand scheme.

02:13:10.740 --> 02:13:15.460
[Guest]: And I just thought, yeah, something about the perceptions of the two societies towards

02:13:15.460 --> 02:13:20.780
[Guest]: each other. And because Juggernaut had said, you're trying to infuse a bit of your own

02:13:20.780 --> 02:13:26.100
[Guest]: personal experiences into it, I thought that's where the perceptions would come in. My trips

02:13:26.100 --> 02:13:30.740
[Guest]: there, sometimes a conversation with some Chinese people or students or some visitors

02:13:30.740 --> 02:13:35.880
[Guest]: from China, I could resurrect some of those episodes. So I thought a perceptions chapter

02:13:35.880 --> 02:13:40.820
[Guest]: would get Juggernaut off my back there, where they would say, oh, my God, don't just narrate

02:13:40.820 --> 02:13:46.520
[Guest]: all this thirdhand, but give us your firsthand experience of some stuff. So that started

02:13:46.520 --> 02:13:50.900
[Guest]: to form itself as that chapter. And then, obviously, there's a geopolitical context

02:13:50.900 --> 02:13:58.340
[Guest]: in which India, China interact. And that was the partnerships chapter, the fourth P. And

02:13:58.340 --> 02:14:02.780
[Guest]: actually for myself, I think that's the least successful chapter of the book. I mean, that's

02:14:02.780 --> 02:14:09.180
[Guest]: the one that ought to be my bread and butter, India, China, Russia, Soviet Union, USA. But

02:14:09.180 --> 02:14:14.620
[Guest]: I don't know, I found it the most difficult to write. And I think it's the least successful.

02:14:14.620 --> 02:14:20.940
[Guest]: I don't know, I almost think if I had it over, I would chuck it out. But you know, I think

02:14:20.940 --> 02:14:24.020
[Amit Varma]: that's a curse of knowledge speaking that you know, the subject so well that you assume

02:14:24.020 --> 02:14:27.300
[Amit Varma]: that you're stating the obvious and you're like, what is that? I'm just stating the obvious.

02:14:27.300 --> 02:14:30.940
[Amit Varma]: But no, for a reader who doesn't know a lot of that, I would actually disagree. I'd say

02:14:30.940 --> 02:14:34.340
[Amit Varma]: that. No, it's a great chapter. All of it is good. Of course, the perimeter chapter

02:14:34.340 --> 02:14:38.580
[Amit Varma]: is the longest. But I guess one needs to go into that kind of detail, because they are

02:14:38.580 --> 02:14:42.820
[Amit Varma]: the kind of concrete details that animate the relationship that we've had. Yeah. So

02:14:42.820 --> 02:14:47.900
[Amit Varma]: for me, I, you know, you've almost framed your explanation of the book as if it is something

02:14:47.900 --> 02:14:51.460
[Amit Varma]: you know, you're responding to this from the publisher, that from the publisher, I will

02:14:51.460 --> 02:14:55.500
[Amit Varma]: just assure my listeners that it doesn't read like that at all. I would never have guessed

02:14:55.500 --> 02:15:02.260
[Amit Varma]: that it feels very self contained and just an excellent systematic building of a frame

02:15:02.260 --> 02:15:05.380
[Amit Varma]: to look at China. But I'm sorry, I interrupted you because I felt that I had to disagree

02:15:05.380 --> 02:15:09.460
[Amit Varma]: with your pejorative view of your own excellent chapter. Do continue.

02:15:09.460 --> 02:15:14.340
[Guest]: Yeah, so I think the one way of saving that account that I just gave you this rather disjointed

02:15:14.340 --> 02:15:20.060
[Guest]: as it actually happens, existential account is to maybe draw an analogy to personal life,

02:15:20.060 --> 02:15:25.140
[Guest]: you know, why these four. So if you do that, I mean, the first thing you can say is that

02:15:25.140 --> 02:15:33.720
[Guest]: how we relate to another person is refracted or, or affected by how we perceive each other.

02:15:33.720 --> 02:15:38.860
[Guest]: So we have some perceptions of each other that grow and chop and change and form themselves.

02:15:38.860 --> 02:15:43.740
[Guest]: And we can't even quite account for why we may think about people in certain ways. But

02:15:43.740 --> 02:15:50.700
[Guest]: that has a very powerful framing effect. So I think that's one justification for putting

02:15:50.700 --> 02:15:55.920
[Guest]: the perceptions chapter in there and putting it up front, a more kind of conceptual way

02:15:55.920 --> 02:16:01.780
[Guest]: of talking about these four P's. Although, I mean, drawing this analogy to individuals

02:16:01.780 --> 02:16:07.060
[Guest]: is not a very good way to think about social affairs. But it's one way of kind of just,

02:16:07.060 --> 02:16:12.300
[Guest]: you know, giving it some respectability, I think, and communicating to your listeners

02:16:12.300 --> 02:16:18.300
[Guest]: about why these four are important. The second piece is perimeters. So the analogy there

02:16:18.300 --> 02:16:24.420
[Guest]: in our personal lives is, of course, you know, to my neighbor, to others, you've got to respect

02:16:24.420 --> 02:16:30.620
[Guest]: my property, which is territory in geopolitics or international affairs, but my home and

02:16:30.620 --> 02:16:37.140
[Guest]: hearth, my belongings. I mean, if you try to steal them, if you try to break them, if

02:16:37.140 --> 02:16:42.660
[Guest]: you violate them, we've got a fight on our hands here. And I will defend them to the

02:16:42.660 --> 02:16:49.700
[Guest]: death, presumably. So, of course, perimeters matters because our property matters in personal

02:16:49.700 --> 02:16:56.300
[Guest]: life, and we will fight for those. The third P is partnership. So that's friendships. My

02:16:56.300 --> 02:17:01.380
[Guest]: friends' friends are my friends. My enemies' friends may be my enemies. My enemies' enemies

02:17:01.380 --> 02:17:05.860
[Guest]: may be my friends. That's true in personal life, I think. You know, at least it's the

02:17:05.860 --> 02:17:12.340
[Guest]: first clue or gesture. If my friend introduces me to their friend, the chances are I'm going

02:17:12.340 --> 02:17:17.460
[Guest]: to be congenial towards them. If my enemy introduces me to their friend, I might look

02:17:17.460 --> 02:17:23.400
[Guest]: sideways and suspiciously at that third person, et cetera. So I think, again, partnerships

02:17:23.400 --> 02:17:28.980
[Guest]: are important and undergird that, you know, they come from that sense that our larger

02:17:28.980 --> 02:17:34.740
[Guest]: network of sort of connections has a role in whether we are friends with someone else

02:17:34.740 --> 02:17:40.940
[Guest]: or not. And we learn from third parties. If we're friends with X, and they say Y is a

02:17:40.940 --> 02:17:46.620
[Guest]: bad person, and Y is my neighbor, then I might suddenly start to look at Y in a jaundiced

02:17:46.620 --> 02:17:52.620
[Guest]: way, because X who has had some other experience of Y that he or she narrates to me, and so

02:17:52.620 --> 02:17:58.140
[Guest]: on. And the fourth is power. So, of course, all our individual relationships are mediated

02:17:58.140 --> 02:18:04.740
[Guest]: by power at some level, some more than others. And again, the relationship between countries

02:18:04.740 --> 02:18:12.840
[Guest]: turns on relative power as well. So, I mean, I would say that that's four more formal arguments,

02:18:12.840 --> 02:18:17.460
[Guest]: if you'd accept the analogy to individuals and their relationships, that made me think

02:18:17.460 --> 02:18:24.180
[Guest]: that I was on a bit more solid ground. I wrote it not that way, a bit more conceptually.

02:18:24.180 --> 02:18:27.220
[Guest]: And then my publisher said, this will bore everyone to tears. Chuck it out. And I did.

02:18:27.220 --> 02:18:33.220
[Guest]: And I think they were right. And that's why I dismissed other P's and other aspects of

02:18:33.220 --> 02:18:39.220
[Guest]: the relationship, such as water, such as Pakistan, such as influence in third regions, and trade,

02:18:39.220 --> 02:18:45.980
[Guest]: and so on. And I said, those are more effect than cause. So they become problems between

02:18:45.980 --> 02:18:51.020
[Guest]: India and Pakistan because of some fundamental conflict. It's not that they are the cause

02:18:51.020 --> 02:18:56.780
[Guest]: of the conflict. I don't think Pakistan caused the India-Pakistan conflict. It's that the

02:18:56.780 --> 02:19:02.460
[Guest]: China-India conflict caused Beijing to reach out to Pakistan, and that drew Pakistan into

02:19:02.460 --> 02:19:08.940
[Guest]: the India-China conflict more and more. So I think sometimes we are mixing up cause and

02:19:08.940 --> 02:19:15.140
[Guest]: effect. And of course, at some point, effect becomes cause in a further loop. So I don't

02:19:15.140 --> 02:19:20.420
[Guest]: deny that sometimes what Pakistan does with China then affects India-China relations.

02:19:20.420 --> 02:19:25.020
[Guest]: But to give the book a succinctness and a direction, I decided to go with these four

02:19:25.020 --> 02:19:29.820
[Guest]: P's and just make it more readable for the ordinary reader.

02:19:29.820 --> 02:19:34.980
[Amit Varma]: No, the four P's, to my mind, do strike me as sort of a foundational frame to look at

02:19:34.980 --> 02:19:38.700
[Amit Varma]: the relationship, as you correctly pointed out, Pakistan, whatever is happening, there

02:19:38.700 --> 02:19:44.020
[Amit Varma]: is more effect than cause. And I love this quote from your book where you quote the former

02:19:44.020 --> 02:19:48.180
[Amit Varma]: Prime Minister Yusuf Jilani, talking about Pakistan's relationship with China. And he

02:19:48.180 --> 02:19:52.700
[Amit Varma]: describes it as quote, higher than mountains, deeper than the ocean, stronger than steel

02:19:52.700 --> 02:19:58.580
[Amit Varma]: and sweeter than honey, stop quote, which is incredibly romantic. Let's move on to the

02:19:58.580 --> 02:20:04.300
[Amit Varma]: first of the P's now. Your first chapter is called perceptions from regard to disdain.

02:20:04.300 --> 02:20:08.500
[Amit Varma]: And that does indeed seem to be the movement. It's a bit more nuanced and that of course,

02:20:08.500 --> 02:20:13.500
[Amit Varma]: it wasn't always regard and it isn't necessarily just disdain now. But you know, as you point

02:20:13.500 --> 02:20:18.020
[Amit Varma]: out, for about 15 years out of the 70, we had great relationships, especially in the

02:20:18.020 --> 02:20:24.580
[Amit Varma]: early 50s, mid 50s, Hindi Chini Bhai Bhai and Nehru overflowing with goodwill, almost

02:20:24.580 --> 02:20:31.300
[Amit Varma]: like Mr. Jilani towards China. And then it gradually began to go downhill. But you kind

02:20:31.300 --> 02:20:35.860
[Amit Varma]: of go a little deeper into history, into the past, into the kind of interactions we've

02:20:35.860 --> 02:20:40.100
[Amit Varma]: had through the centuries, which also I found very interesting because, you know, growing

02:20:40.100 --> 02:20:43.540
[Amit Varma]: up what I've been taught in school or what is there in the popular literature, we know

02:20:43.540 --> 02:20:49.520
[Amit Varma]: enough about India's troubled history with those who colonised us and our history with,

02:20:49.520 --> 02:20:53.740
[Amit Varma]: you know, those who invaded us or those who visited and so on. But China is just kind

02:20:53.740 --> 02:20:57.740
[Amit Varma]: of mentioned in footnotes, you know, even though they are our immediate neighbour, like

02:20:57.740 --> 02:21:01.820
[Amit Varma]: we'll, you know, know of Hunsang and Fahain and all that, which we read in our school

02:21:01.820 --> 02:21:07.100
[Amit Varma]: books with a different spelling than the ones you've used, which I assume are more authentic,

02:21:07.100 --> 02:21:10.860
[Amit Varma]: if we don't know much more about them. But actually, the truth is that India, China have

02:21:10.860 --> 02:21:17.180
[Amit Varma]: had in terms of people to people contacts, pretty deep relationships for centuries. So

02:21:17.180 --> 02:21:22.060
[Amit Varma]: can you, you know, briefly give me a sense of sort of this historical journey of the

02:21:22.060 --> 02:21:26.020
[Amit Varma]: contacts we have and how they shaped our perceptions of each other.

02:21:26.020 --> 02:21:29.660
[Guest]: So I think the story really begins with Buddhism. I mean, I'm sure there was contact before

02:21:29.660 --> 02:21:34.300
[Guest]: then, but I think most people begin the story there. And so did I, I mean, I'm not a historian

02:21:34.300 --> 02:21:39.940
[Guest]: of India, China, but just picking up the synthetic material that's out there and rendering it

02:21:39.940 --> 02:21:45.060
[Guest]: for readers. So you begin with Buddhism, which actually probably almost certainly went from

02:21:45.060 --> 02:21:51.320
[Guest]: Central Asia to China first, not from India, as I think we sometimes think. And so it was

02:21:51.320 --> 02:21:57.500
[Guest]: indirectly from India, but not directly. The Indian influence comes later, when particularly

02:21:57.500 --> 02:22:03.140
[Guest]: I think Chinese pilgrims and monks and so on came to India to receive wisdom and to

02:22:03.140 --> 02:22:07.500
[Guest]: pick up texts and practices and take them back to China. And then some Indian monks

02:22:07.500 --> 02:22:14.540
[Guest]: and Buddhists went there to help translate and communicate and so on. So, I mean, from

02:22:14.540 --> 02:22:22.820
[Guest]: that time forwards to roughly, I would say the 10th century, very broadly, crudely, you

02:22:22.820 --> 02:22:29.540
[Guest]: could say that China had regard for India. And even there, as I try to show, China did

02:22:29.540 --> 02:22:34.140
[Guest]: have a sense of its own kind of importance. And there were certainly segments in China,

02:22:34.140 --> 02:22:39.260
[Guest]: the elite people around the court, who at various times reacted quite negatively to

02:22:39.260 --> 02:22:45.740
[Guest]: Buddhism. And in effect, you know, they were able to accept Buddhism by synthesizing it.

02:22:45.740 --> 02:22:50.980
[Guest]: I mean, so they weren't negative towards India necessarily, but they wanted to synthesize

02:22:50.980 --> 02:22:56.300
[Guest]: it. And there were elements that claimed, you know, that Buddhism was actually a Chinese

02:22:56.300 --> 02:23:02.140
[Guest]: religion originally, the Buddha was Chinese, etc, etc, that it was actually, you know,

02:23:02.140 --> 02:23:08.060
[Guest]: synonymous with Daoism and things like that. I think, nonetheless, the broad story is that

02:23:08.060 --> 02:23:14.940
[Guest]: until about the 10th century or so, China had a regard for India through Buddhism. There

02:23:14.940 --> 02:23:19.100
[Guest]: was trade, there was other stuff going on, particularly in Buddhist relics and things

02:23:19.100 --> 02:23:25.300
[Guest]: like that, and in Chinese goods coming to India. But it was born out of Buddhism and

02:23:25.300 --> 02:23:31.780
[Guest]: the learning associated with it and practices. But at about that time, which is about 1000

02:23:31.780 --> 02:23:37.220
[Guest]: of the Christian era, Buddhism was more or less ending in India. And, you know, Brahmanism

02:23:37.220 --> 02:23:43.620
[Guest]: or whatever you want to call it, made a pushback. And in a sense, I mean, I think this is what

02:23:43.620 --> 02:23:48.380
[Guest]: came out of one of the seminars I was in after the book, Buddhism became naturalized as a

02:23:48.380 --> 02:23:52.660
[Guest]: kind of part of Hinduism. So it didn't die in the sense that it was completely vanquished

02:23:52.660 --> 02:23:58.340
[Guest]: and obliterated. It just became a part of the pantheon of Hinduism. You know, so you

02:23:58.340 --> 02:24:05.260
[Guest]: have Buddhism as another god in the Hindu pantheon. And so, but as a result of that,

02:24:05.260 --> 02:24:10.700
[Guest]: I think the Chinese pilgrimages to India, and the looking up to India kind of began

02:24:10.700 --> 02:24:16.860
[Guest]: to die. If China began to export Buddhism to parts of East Asia, and even parts of Southeast

02:24:16.860 --> 02:24:23.140
[Guest]: Asia, and perhaps look for Buddhist interactions and influences elsewhere, and develop their

02:24:23.140 --> 02:24:31.500
[Guest]: own Buddhist thought. And by the 15th century, I would say, and somewhat earlier, the tables

02:24:31.500 --> 02:24:37.100
[Guest]: were turned, as it were, and in the parts of India, began to look up to China, to the

02:24:37.100 --> 02:24:44.020
[Guest]: Chinese court, the Chinese imperial domains, and parts of Malabar, southern India, where

02:24:44.020 --> 02:24:50.660
[Guest]: there was a lot of trade, and where the great Chinese admiral, Cheng He, visited. And before

02:24:50.660 --> 02:24:56.420
[Guest]: that, you know, the great Khan, I mean, there were kingdoms in Bengal, that also were sending

02:24:56.420 --> 02:25:01.220
[Guest]: tribute to China. So, you know, I think the relationship was somewhat reversed. There

02:25:01.220 --> 02:25:05.980
[Guest]: are parts of India that began to look up to China, and perhaps even to some extent fear

02:25:05.980 --> 02:25:11.580
[Guest]: China. And there was some interference by the Cheng He's and so on in Indian affairs.

02:25:11.580 --> 02:25:16.180
[Guest]: And even going back to Harshvardhan's time in northern India, there was a kind of Chinese

02:25:16.180 --> 02:25:20.980
[Guest]: military expedition that was sent to India, to take some amount of revenge and sort out

02:25:20.980 --> 02:25:25.780
[Guest]: some of the affairs of some, you know, at the time of Harshvardhan and so on, when some

02:25:25.780 --> 02:25:31.300
[Guest]: Chinese envoys had been humiliated and killed. So, you know, there was a kind of fear and

02:25:31.300 --> 02:25:36.620
[Guest]: respect for China at that point. Then there's a hiatus in a way, I mean, there was trade

02:25:36.620 --> 02:25:41.100
[Guest]: increasingly, there was contacts between Indians and Chinese in third regions, Southeast Asia

02:25:41.100 --> 02:25:48.620
[Guest]: elsewhere. But colonialism, Western colonialism arrived. And I think increasingly, the relationship

02:25:48.620 --> 02:25:56.060
[Guest]: was mediated through the Portuguese, the Dutch, and increasingly by the British. The opium

02:25:56.060 --> 02:26:04.400
[Guest]: trade began with between India and China. And out of that, and increasing colonial influence

02:26:04.400 --> 02:26:09.900
[Guest]: in China, the century of humiliation and all of that, the Chinese looked at India with

02:26:09.900 --> 02:26:17.460
[Guest]: two kind of jaundiced eyes. The first was, you know, they looked at Indians in China,

02:26:17.460 --> 02:26:21.900
[Guest]: the policemen, the Indian troops that were being used by the British, some elements of

02:26:21.900 --> 02:26:29.020
[Guest]: Indian traders in China, of course, the opium trade, which clearly had a very bad effect

02:26:29.020 --> 02:26:33.780
[Guest]: amongst a segment of Chinese people. You know, so that led them to a kind of negative perception

02:26:33.780 --> 02:26:39.260
[Guest]: of India and Indian society. And associated with that was the question amongst a group

02:26:39.260 --> 02:26:45.940
[Guest]: of Chinese reformists, who were Republicans, mostly, and were trying to reform China. And

02:26:45.940 --> 02:26:52.580
[Guest]: the question they asked was, and this is what I recount, you know, how come this great civilization

02:26:52.580 --> 02:26:57.500
[Guest]: west of China, we think of China as a northern country, but they think of us as being in

02:26:57.500 --> 02:27:03.180
[Guest]: their west. How had this great civilization fallen on hard times? Why did it fall to the

02:27:03.180 --> 02:27:08.020
[Guest]: British? And this was asked at a time when China was going under. So, you know, they

02:27:08.020 --> 02:27:14.580
[Guest]: wanted to figure out how such a big landmass, huge population, vibrant civilization had

02:27:14.580 --> 02:27:24.540
[Guest]: fallen to a handful of imperialists and remained under their jackboot. So, the answer they

02:27:24.540 --> 02:27:29.700
[Guest]: came up with was, in a way, a pretty familiar one, one that we tell ourselves in India.

02:27:29.700 --> 02:27:34.460
[Guest]: They didn't fight hard enough, the Indians. They were disunited. They had been driven

02:27:34.460 --> 02:27:40.660
[Guest]: by and developed a psychology of being disunited by waves of invasion. They were not able to

02:27:40.660 --> 02:27:46.980
[Guest]: mount a, you know, a united kind of response to invaders. That different groups played

02:27:46.980 --> 02:27:51.940
[Guest]: out their animosities through these invaders, including the British, and they wanted to

02:27:51.940 --> 02:27:56.460
[Guest]: settle scores with other Indians rather than keep the foreigners out, et cetera, et cetera.

02:27:56.460 --> 02:28:03.580
[Guest]: And one abiding image was India was a country of many castes and religions and hopelessly

02:28:03.580 --> 02:28:10.180
[Guest]: pluralistic and divided, and they were a kind of Luan people. Luan means sort of chaotic.

02:28:10.180 --> 02:28:15.820
[Guest]: There was no center there, and this society was therefore hopeless and could not mount

02:28:15.820 --> 02:28:20.860
[Guest]: an effective response. And China, there were signs that China could become that, and it

02:28:20.860 --> 02:28:26.300
[Guest]: should never become India. So, they drew a negative lesson from India that China should

02:28:26.300 --> 02:28:30.060
[Guest]: not become that, and that's not a very pretty picture of India.

02:28:30.060 --> 02:28:37.380
[Guest]: So, by the late 19th century, their view of India was rather negative for all these reasons.

02:28:37.380 --> 02:28:42.740
[Guest]: And then fast forward, of course, you know, to the Nehruvian period and Mao and the Communist

02:28:42.740 --> 02:28:47.580
[Guest]: Party come to power. I think there were elements of that that still hung around. I mean, you're

02:28:47.580 --> 02:28:52.060
[Guest]: right that there was also an appreciation of India even now. Mao continued to famously

02:28:52.060 --> 02:28:56.380
[Guest]: say apparently that, you know, if a Chinese person was ever born again, they should be

02:28:56.380 --> 02:29:02.300
[Guest]: born Indian. It's some sort of quite well-known statement amongst the Chinese. So, there was

02:29:02.300 --> 02:29:07.460
[Guest]: a kind of regard, and of course, the admirers of Tagore and so on that I mentioned in the

02:29:07.460 --> 02:29:13.060
[Guest]: book had an admiration of India, and I don't want to deny all that.

02:29:13.060 --> 02:29:18.260
[Guest]: But I would say on the whole, you know, by the Nehruvian period and beyond, there began

02:29:18.260 --> 02:29:24.180
[Guest]: to be a kind of looking down the nose at India. And to tell the Indian side of the story,

02:29:24.180 --> 02:29:29.100
[Guest]: I mean, I guess it developed also, although I don't do enough of that in the book, I just

02:29:29.100 --> 02:29:34.380
[Guest]: didn't have time and I don't have enough access to it, but also perhaps both a regard for

02:29:34.380 --> 02:29:39.780
[Guest]: China that was there, but also in the modern period, a kind of negative view of China,

02:29:39.780 --> 02:29:44.940
[Guest]: partly racist that we learned through the British and the Westerners. They were yellow

02:29:44.940 --> 02:29:53.100
[Guest]: people with strange ways and, you know, consumed by drugs like opium and so on and so forth,

02:29:53.100 --> 02:29:58.540
[Guest]: more arrogant and warlike, again, learned from the West, you know, so I think mutual

02:29:58.540 --> 02:30:04.140
[Guest]: disdain was the story and elements of that remain the case.

02:30:04.140 --> 02:30:08.020
[Amit Varma]: So a few asides from this historical journey, like one part I found fascinating was where

02:30:08.020 --> 02:30:11.740
[Amit Varma]: you write about how when Buddhism first came to China, it wasn't entirely smooth, there

02:30:11.740 --> 02:30:16.260
[Amit Varma]: was a little bit of friction and its acceptance and many people fought back because they said,

02:30:16.260 --> 02:30:20.580
[Amit Varma]: you know, Taoism and Confucianism, they are our natural distinct, but then as Buddhism

02:30:20.580 --> 02:30:26.700
[Amit Varma]: declined in India itself, they kind of appropriated it and it just became like a third prong.

02:30:26.700 --> 02:30:29.740
[Amit Varma]: And it's interesting that, you know, what you just mentioned here, I don't remember

02:30:29.740 --> 02:30:34.220
[Amit Varma]: reading it in the book that they tried to paint Buddhism as a religion that originated

02:30:34.220 --> 02:30:39.580
[Amit Varma]: in China. We've kind of seen a similar thing in India where, for example, the wacky quote

02:30:39.580 --> 02:30:44.620
[Amit Varma]: unquote historian P.N. Oak, he would write about how Christianity originated in India

02:30:44.620 --> 02:30:49.300
[Amit Varma]: and Jesus Christ was Indian and Christianity was originally called Krishna Niti. And this

02:30:49.300 --> 02:30:53.860
[Amit Varma]: is the same guy who, by the way, said the Taj Mahal was originally Tejo Mahalaya. So

02:30:53.860 --> 02:30:58.660
[Amit Varma]: I don't know, you know, whether this is whether these ancient civilizations have this kind

02:30:58.660 --> 02:31:05.300
[Amit Varma]: of inferiority complex that they need to make up these kind of stories to sort of make themselves

02:31:05.300 --> 02:31:10.340
[Amit Varma]: feel better about the influences coming in. And speaking of influences coming in, there's

02:31:10.340 --> 02:31:15.300
[Amit Varma]: also a nice section on trade where you talk about the opium trade and you point out that

02:31:15.300 --> 02:31:19.340
[Amit Varma]: we would give them opium and in return, one of the products that we would take is white

02:31:19.340 --> 02:31:24.260
[Amit Varma]: sugar, which we therefore call Chini, you know, Chini because Chini is fairly obvious.

02:31:24.260 --> 02:31:29.100
[Amit Varma]: So all you Indian nationalists listening to this who feel glad that TikTok has been banned

02:31:29.100 --> 02:31:33.380
[Amit Varma]: kindly stop eating Chini also, which is actually good for the health. I mean, if you stop eating

02:31:33.380 --> 02:31:38.420
[Amit Varma]: it, that'll be good for the health. So that's one way that xenophobia may actually work

02:31:38.420 --> 02:31:42.820
[Amit Varma]: for you. Now, the other interesting thing that strikes me with this disdain is and that,

02:31:42.820 --> 02:31:47.060
[Amit Varma]: you know, you point out about how in the late 19th century, they lose the war to Japan.

02:31:47.060 --> 02:31:51.860
[Amit Varma]: And you write about how young reformers in China are now saying that, listen, we need

02:31:51.860 --> 02:31:56.900
[Amit Varma]: to be more like Japan, Russia and Germany. And the country whose fate we need to avoid

02:31:56.900 --> 02:32:01.700
[Amit Varma]: is India. And as you point out, an implication that the yellow races are as talented as the

02:32:01.700 --> 02:32:06.220
[Amit Varma]: white but not the case with other races. And you quote from this very interesting article,

02:32:06.220 --> 02:32:11.180
[Amit Varma]: I think it's a 1906 article, a series of articles, which is called the causes for the demise

02:32:11.180 --> 02:32:16.780
[Amit Varma]: of India. And in that article, the author writes, quote, the word India is in fact nothing

02:32:16.780 --> 02:32:21.420
[Amit Varma]: but a name from history. Ah, yeah, their land is all smashed to pieces. This brown race

02:32:21.420 --> 02:32:25.860
[Amit Varma]: will be forever enslaved. Looking at China today, it is like India in the past. As a

02:32:25.860 --> 02:32:29.980
[Amit Varma]: matter of principle, it was the Indians who brought about the demise of India. The character

02:32:29.980 --> 02:32:33.580
[Amit Varma]: of the race is chaotic, their language is topsy turvy, their religions all separate

02:32:33.580 --> 02:32:38.300
[Amit Varma]: from each other. There is no unified spirit, no patriotic thinking, the elites are drowning

02:32:38.300 --> 02:32:43.820
[Amit Varma]: themselves in song and dance and know nothing of great purpose. Alas, India is lost, stop

02:32:43.820 --> 02:32:50.620
[Amit Varma]: quote. And later you point out sort of a similar tendency when Tagore visits in 1924. And there

02:32:50.620 --> 02:32:54.660
[Amit Varma]: are small groups of people who welcome him and give him the respect he deserves. But

02:32:54.660 --> 02:32:59.400
[Amit Varma]: you also point out, quote, he was roundly denounced and ridiculed, particularly by leftist

02:32:59.400 --> 02:33:04.340
[Amit Varma]: communist revolutionaries old and young, including former admirers and translators. He was seen

02:33:04.340 --> 02:33:10.420
[Amit Varma]: as extolling traditional feudal Asia and romanticizing the Orient against the material industrial

02:33:10.420 --> 02:33:16.740
[Amit Varma]: Occident, stop quote. And later you quote Ram Guha, quoting the Chinese scholar Wu

02:33:16.740 --> 02:33:22.140
[Amit Varma]: Qin Hui, and forgive me if I get the pronunciation wrong, where Wu Qin Hui says of Tagore, quote,

02:33:22.140 --> 02:33:27.140
[Amit Varma]: Mr. Tagore, a petrified fossil of India's national past, had retreated into the tearful

02:33:27.140 --> 02:33:31.780
[Amit Varma]: eyes and dripping noses of the slave people as a conquered country, seeking happiness

02:33:31.780 --> 02:33:37.140
[Amit Varma]: in a future life, squeaking like the hub of a wagon wheel that needs oil, stop quote,

02:33:37.140 --> 02:33:42.100
[Amit Varma]: all of which lovely little snippets. Now, my kind of question here is, and we've also

02:33:42.100 --> 02:33:46.900
[Amit Varma]: obviously at different times had sort of xenophobic views of them. You talk about how a lot of

02:33:46.900 --> 02:33:52.060
[Amit Varma]: Chinese came to Calcutta, settled there, especially in the Babazar area, the sort of frictions

02:33:52.060 --> 02:33:57.740
[Amit Varma]: that would often be there. But the other thing that I wonder about is, how much are contemporary

02:33:57.740 --> 02:34:03.500
[Amit Varma]: frictions or contemporary impressions shaped by things that happened in this distant past?

02:34:03.500 --> 02:34:08.540
[Amit Varma]: Like do these sort of narratives that are there in the popular culture, actually carry

02:34:08.540 --> 02:34:14.120
[Amit Varma]: on as a kind of oral history from father to child and so on all the way down so that one

02:34:14.120 --> 02:34:19.180
[Amit Varma]: generation will, in some way without knowing it by osmosis replicate the attitude of like

02:34:19.180 --> 02:34:25.500
[Amit Varma]: five generations ago? Or do some narratives just naturally get lost to history? And it

02:34:25.500 --> 02:34:31.540
[Amit Varma]: is the imperatives of a future time that they are perhaps revived in some way?

02:34:31.540 --> 02:34:38.700
[Guest]: Yeah, I think that, you know, you're right to shine the light on this issue of whether

02:34:38.700 --> 02:34:44.060
[Guest]: these negative views and disdain and so on, going back to the 19th century, still really

02:34:44.060 --> 02:34:50.860
[Guest]: alive and kicking in China. And likewise, whether elements of racism and so on, on our

02:34:50.860 --> 02:34:57.020
[Guest]: side too, and negative pictures of China persist from, you know, long ago, or even whether

02:34:57.020 --> 02:35:04.140
[Guest]: the regard remains on both sides and still affects us. I mean, I suppose I think they

02:35:04.140 --> 02:35:08.580
[Guest]: do. I mean, that's the whole premise of the chapter in a way, is that the something of

02:35:08.580 --> 02:35:15.740
[Guest]: that as a vestige, at least remains, some sort of collective consciousness is handed

02:35:15.740 --> 02:35:22.860
[Guest]: down from one generation to another. And they, they can be in very seemingly innocent, popular

02:35:22.860 --> 02:35:27.180
[Guest]: remarks and things, you know, Indian people are like this, or Chinese people are like

02:35:27.180 --> 02:35:33.700
[Guest]: that. So there are these tropes that are out there even now, you know, and I mean, very

02:35:33.700 --> 02:35:39.700
[Guest]: good natured Chinese have said, Oh, you Indians are also talkative and argumentative, to pick

02:35:39.700 --> 02:35:46.220
[Guest]: up Sen's word about Indians. That's there from somewhere. It may not necessarily be

02:35:46.220 --> 02:35:52.100
[Guest]: from, you know, received from or mediated through British influences. After all, they

02:35:52.100 --> 02:35:58.140
[Guest]: had their own popular kind of encounters with Indians who were in China. And likewise, I

02:35:58.140 --> 02:36:03.660
[Guest]: mean, Indians who had some contact with the Chinese here and there, might very well have

02:36:03.660 --> 02:36:09.460
[Guest]: kind of concluded that the elements of Chinese culture that seem strange and not so nice

02:36:09.460 --> 02:36:17.100
[Guest]: I mean, an extreme materialism is, I can't think, I suppose, a particular kind of trope

02:36:17.100 --> 02:36:22.940
[Guest]: or image that a lot of people have towards China. And I think there's an associated in

02:36:22.940 --> 02:36:28.940
[Guest]: India with a view that they're somehow very violent people, and can be very cruel or,

02:36:28.940 --> 02:36:35.180
[Guest]: you know, despotic. And I don't know quite where that comes from. But maybe it came from

02:36:35.180 --> 02:36:40.620
[Guest]: Indians who were also involved in the trade in China, might have run into troubles there,

02:36:40.620 --> 02:36:45.300
[Guest]: or soldiers that served there, and brought back some stories. We know now from a recent

02:36:45.300 --> 02:36:50.620
[Guest]: diary, of course, a different view. I forget the name of the diary that has been written

02:36:50.620 --> 02:36:56.060
[Guest]: by this Indian sepoy, which has now been translated and made available, which shows that actually

02:36:56.060 --> 02:37:00.460
[Guest]: there was a very great regard for his Chinese hosts, that he admired the ordinary Chinese

02:37:00.460 --> 02:37:05.820
[Guest]: people and their struggles against colonials. But yeah, I mean, I think overall, there's

02:37:05.820 --> 02:37:11.260
[Guest]: probably some basis for, you know, the kind of pictures we still have of each other. And

02:37:11.260 --> 02:37:16.500
[Guest]: just like in personal psychology, I mean, you may be early in your life, you receive

02:37:16.500 --> 02:37:21.020
[Guest]: certain kinds of cliches and prejudices from your parents and those around you. But your

02:37:21.020 --> 02:37:26.180
[Guest]: own experience gradually as an adult, gives you some more. And I suppose, in the life

02:37:26.180 --> 02:37:32.500
[Guest]: of a nation, that's true, too. So the 62 war, the terrible problems of the border, the sense

02:37:32.500 --> 02:37:38.740
[Guest]: of mutual betrayal on Tibet, you know, those kinds of things, in turn, has only amplified

02:37:38.740 --> 02:37:43.580
[Guest]: some original kinds of bad feelings on both sides over time. So I, you know, the reason

02:37:43.580 --> 02:37:51.540
[Guest]: that chapter is there first is because I wanted to show that over time, we do have evidence

02:37:51.540 --> 02:37:58.260
[Guest]: of these kinds of, at least ambivalences on both sides. And, you know, one section of

02:37:58.260 --> 02:38:05.380
[Guest]: the book in the modern period, I worked through three books, Vikram Seth's book of his travels

02:38:05.380 --> 02:38:10.380
[Guest]: through China, you know, it's Chinese views of India through Indian eyes. So Vikram Seth

02:38:10.380 --> 02:38:15.060
[Guest]: looking at interacting with Chinese people on his bus journey and all of that, and giving

02:38:15.060 --> 02:38:19.740
[Guest]: us a sense of how the Chinese look at India. And then this lady in Singapore, who I met

02:38:19.740 --> 02:38:25.300
[Guest]: Anurag Vishwanath, who over many years did research there, how she encountered Chinese

02:38:25.300 --> 02:38:31.020
[Guest]: people in China, and sometimes how they looked at India. And then lastly, Reshma Patil, the

02:38:31.020 --> 02:38:37.060
[Guest]: Hindustan Times correspondent in Beijing, and this very nice book she wrote, also recounting

02:38:37.060 --> 02:38:42.980
[Guest]: many stories of how the Chinese people looked at India. So I use that section to show how

02:38:42.980 --> 02:38:48.660
[Guest]: even now, I mean, from Vikram Seth's journey was in the early 80s or late 70s, through

02:38:48.660 --> 02:38:53.620
[Guest]: Anurag Vishwanath's journeys, which are through over many years up to a contemporary period,

02:38:53.620 --> 02:38:59.060
[Guest]: and then Reshma's just seven, eight years ago. But there is a thread there of negative

02:38:59.060 --> 02:39:04.340
[Guest]: views of India, but also some approbatory or positive views of India. So this ambivalence,

02:39:04.340 --> 02:39:11.340
[Guest]: at least, is quite deeply there, you know, and I don't have so much data on the Indian

02:39:11.340 --> 02:39:16.540
[Guest]: side, though I tell a few stories there. But I'm sure that there's a research project waiting

02:39:16.540 --> 02:39:22.620
[Guest]: to be done there, of mining Indian perceptions of China, even in the modern period after

02:39:22.620 --> 02:39:32.020
[Guest]: the 62 war, in novels or, you know, commentary, and stories of individual kind of encounters

02:39:32.020 --> 02:39:38.300
[Guest]: with Chinese people that we could put together. My guess is that both sides are at fault there,

02:39:38.300 --> 02:39:42.860
[Guest]: if that's the word. There are bad perceptions and some good perceptions on both sides.

02:39:42.860 --> 02:39:47.020
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and they come through in these books you mentioned, like in Vikram Seth's book,

02:39:47.020 --> 02:39:51.660
[Amit Varma]: From Heaven Lake, he writes about how he needed to get a permit to visit Tibet. And one thing

02:39:51.660 --> 02:39:56.300
[Amit Varma]: that enabled that was he discussed Awara with the Chinese official who was supposed to give

02:39:56.300 --> 02:40:01.340
[Amit Varma]: him the permit because they were big fans of Bollywood. And similarly, in counter view

02:40:01.340 --> 02:40:05.980
[Amit Varma]: to that is in Reshma's book, she writes about how, you know, she sort of asked the Chinese

02:40:05.980 --> 02:40:11.260
[Amit Varma]: broadcasting executive she meets about his views of India. And there are these two really

02:40:11.260 --> 02:40:17.900
[Amit Varma]: pithy lines which say so much, quote, children in India are naked, they piss on the streets,

02:40:17.900 --> 02:40:22.700
[Amit Varma]: stop quote, which is such a succinct way of just, you know, putting the impression of

02:40:22.700 --> 02:40:28.220
[Amit Varma]: a country. And then apparently he added, but all Indians have inner peace, which is like

02:40:28.220 --> 02:40:32.700
[Amit Varma]: a kind of a backhanded compliment. So I love these. And of course, you know, these three

02:40:32.700 --> 02:40:37.420
[Amit Varma]: books contain kind of, I guess, impressionistic accounts. And you've presented a lot more

02:40:37.420 --> 02:40:43.180
[Amit Varma]: systematic data on Chinese perceptions of India. There's Simon Shen's 2011 survey,

02:40:43.180 --> 02:40:47.820
[Amit Varma]: there's a survey Shen did with Debashish Roy Choudhury, where you wrote about their survey.

02:40:47.820 --> 02:40:52.140
[Amit Varma]: At a broad level, they found that the Indian media's coverage of military affairs is marked

02:40:52.140 --> 02:40:57.500
[Amit Varma]: by shrill jingoism and distrust, reflecting the paranoia at the heart of India's elite

02:40:57.500 --> 02:41:01.580
[Amit Varma]: perceptions. The Chinese media is more sober because it is under the watchful eye of the

02:41:01.580 --> 02:41:06.460
[Amit Varma]: government. But it has increased its coverage of India and feeds off what it reads in the

02:41:06.460 --> 02:41:11.900
[Amit Varma]: Indian media to produce its own brand of self-righteous anxieties, stop quote.

02:41:11.900 --> 02:41:15.980
[Amit Varma]: And this kind of worried me because then you feel that this might be a vicious circle forming

02:41:15.980 --> 02:41:22.620
[Amit Varma]: itself where, you know, the jingoism on each side is leading to increased reactive jingoism

02:41:22.620 --> 02:41:27.820
[Amit Varma]: from the other side. The other fascinating part of this chapter, and there's much within

02:41:27.820 --> 02:41:31.340
[Amit Varma]: this chapter alone that is fascinating, leave alone the rest of the book, is when you talk

02:41:31.340 --> 02:41:36.380
[Amit Varma]: about the three Indian worldviews and the three Chinese worldviews. So would you like to briefly

02:41:36.380 --> 02:41:41.100
[Amit Varma]: go through them? Because, you know, one of the conclusions that you later come to, and

02:41:41.100 --> 02:41:44.540
[Amit Varma]: it struck me, is that out of all these six worldviews, the three Indian and the three

02:41:44.540 --> 02:41:49.900
[Amit Varma]: Chinese, there is only one which, you know, can actually work for a positive future for

02:41:49.900 --> 02:41:54.460
[Amit Varma]: all of us. And that is the least likely to happen. So just take us through these worldviews.

02:41:54.460 --> 02:41:59.100
[Guest]: Yeah. So beginning with the Chinese, let's just begin there. I mean, I said they have

02:41:59.100 --> 02:42:03.420
[Guest]: three. I mean, obviously, there are probably more, but these are three big ones. The first

02:42:03.420 --> 02:42:08.300
[Guest]: is this idea of Tianxia, all under heaven, which is really the kind of view of China

02:42:08.300 --> 02:42:16.380
[Guest]: at the heart of the world and certainly of Asia. And mostly we know it as the tributary

02:42:16.380 --> 02:42:22.380
[Guest]: system. China sits in the middle, and there are all these smaller powers around it historically,

02:42:22.380 --> 02:42:28.540
[Guest]: and they send tribute to China. The tributary system had then China give something back,

02:42:28.540 --> 02:42:34.620
[Guest]: and generally it's accepted that the Chinese emperor gave back more than he received in

02:42:34.620 --> 02:42:39.260
[Guest]: the form of legitimacy to these smaller countries, sometimes interfering in their affairs to,

02:42:40.060 --> 02:42:45.740
[Guest]: you know, prop up rulers who wanted his help, and of course, mostly opening up Chinese markets

02:42:45.740 --> 02:42:52.380
[Guest]: to their exports. But this Tianxia system, if we go from that, then where is India in

02:42:52.380 --> 02:42:59.020
[Guest]: that worldview? India is another potential tributary, basically. And now, having said

02:42:59.020 --> 02:43:04.940
[Guest]: that, obviously, if you were Chinese looking at these tributaries around China, India is

02:43:04.940 --> 02:43:10.700
[Guest]: the biggest tributary by far. So, I mean, the Chinese are not foolish. Certainly India,

02:43:10.700 --> 02:43:14.220
[Guest]: and this is a thought experiment. I mean, I have to ask Chinese people this, but

02:43:14.220 --> 02:43:18.940
[Guest]: proceeding from this Tianxia view, India would be the biggest of the tributaries,

02:43:18.940 --> 02:43:24.540
[Guest]: and therefore it had to be given a certain kind of special position amongst the tributaries.

02:43:24.540 --> 02:43:31.260
[Guest]: It would be grander and deserving of a more respect and autonomy. But certainly, all

02:43:31.260 --> 02:43:36.780
[Guest]: tributaries were in a subordinate position, ultimately. So India appears there at best as

02:43:36.780 --> 02:43:43.980
[Guest]: a kind of junior partner. Then there's the kind of communist worldview and the republican worldview,

02:43:43.980 --> 02:43:49.740
[Guest]: where, you know, this Tianxia and all that is thrown out. The empire is dismantled. The

02:43:49.740 --> 02:43:56.780
[Guest]: emperor is bid adieu, made into an ordinary human being. And what replaces it is communism

02:43:56.780 --> 02:44:01.980
[Guest]: and basically a republican view, which is that people, by merit, will rule the country,

02:44:01.980 --> 02:44:08.540
[Guest]: either the republican view of the Kuomintang or the Communist Party. So there, I mean,

02:44:08.540 --> 02:44:14.300
[Guest]: again, you can see, let's just take the communists. The Chinese communists certainly thought that,

02:44:14.300 --> 02:44:20.060
[Guest]: you know, the great fight was with capitalism. Who would lead that fight? Well, the great centers

02:44:20.060 --> 02:44:27.020
[Guest]: of communism would enlist all the minor socialist and like-minded oppressed people

02:44:27.020 --> 02:44:34.140
[Guest]: and lead the fight. And very quickly, Mao decided that the Soviet Union under Khrushchev,

02:44:34.140 --> 02:44:41.500
[Guest]: he was a kind of, you know, he was too weak and cowardly. And the fallout with the Soviet Union

02:44:41.500 --> 02:44:46.700
[Guest]: at that time was that they were too cooperative with the West. And therefore, it was actually

02:44:46.700 --> 02:44:53.180
[Guest]: China that would be the leading edge of the revolutionary struggle with capitalism. Where

02:44:53.180 --> 02:44:59.740
[Guest]: would India appear in that? I mean, if the Chinese accepted, as some did, that eventually,

02:44:59.740 --> 02:45:05.980
[Guest]: not initially, that India could be a kind of ally, that it was a sort of socialist aspiring country,

02:45:05.980 --> 02:45:12.380
[Guest]: that it was not altogether, you know, a petty bourgeois, also ran, you know, a sort of running

02:45:12.380 --> 02:45:19.580
[Guest]: dog of imperialism, then India could be admitted again as a junior ideological partner and

02:45:19.580 --> 02:45:26.460
[Guest]: revolutionary partner of China. China would lead the struggle and provide leadership and

02:45:26.460 --> 02:45:32.140
[Guest]: backing to these minor powers. But India would not lead the struggle. India might, more than some

02:45:32.140 --> 02:45:38.060
[Guest]: other centers of socialism and resistance, be a partner, but a junior partner. The third is,

02:45:38.060 --> 02:45:44.780
[Guest]: of course, as China exited communism, mostly, the third great worldview is China's a great power.

02:45:45.660 --> 02:45:53.580
[Guest]: And there, too, China now, the only peer it recognizes is the United States. And if the

02:45:53.580 --> 02:46:00.860
[Guest]: China dream is correct, then under Xi Jinping, then China will be not just the peer, it will be

02:46:00.860 --> 02:46:07.020
[Guest]: the superior. It will be the hegemon. It will be the greatest power on earth. And even the Americans

02:46:07.020 --> 02:46:13.420
[Guest]: will be in second place. So where is India in that? I mean, very charitably, the Indians hardly

02:46:13.420 --> 02:46:19.580
[Guest]: see India as a great power. At best, they sort of see India as a aspiring power. Sometimes they

02:46:19.580 --> 02:46:25.420
[Guest]: call us an important power with a role in world affairs, very grudgingly. And even that's a kind

02:46:25.420 --> 02:46:32.940
[Guest]: of backhanded compliment. So in all three worldviews, India appears as a secondary junior

02:46:32.940 --> 02:46:42.460
[Guest]: partner at best, and maybe even ignorable at worst. So the Indian worldviews, likewise, if we

02:46:42.460 --> 02:46:50.140
[Guest]: go from this sort of mandala picture from Kautilya, well, there, I mean, China is a neighbor,

02:46:50.140 --> 02:46:57.900
[Guest]: and your neighbor is your enemy and should be conquered. And then, you know, the Vishwaguru,

02:46:57.900 --> 02:47:06.460
[Guest]: or before that, the Chakravartin, keeps expanding and takes dharma to successive entities that it

02:47:06.460 --> 02:47:13.100
[Guest]: conquers. But not even in the greatest Indian fantasy can one imagine Indian armies, even in

02:47:13.100 --> 02:47:19.820
[Guest]: the past, really, traversing the Himalayas into the great flat plains of Tibet, and then moving

02:47:19.820 --> 02:47:25.660
[Guest]: on and conquering China. So the mandala system, the best that can be imagined, is that India

02:47:25.660 --> 02:47:30.140
[Guest]: cultivates your neighbors' neighbors, and they become your friends. But that doesn't work too

02:47:30.140 --> 02:47:35.180
[Guest]: well for India, because if you follow the logic through, then the Russians should be our friends

02:47:35.180 --> 02:47:40.780
[Guest]: against the Chinese. But they've cut a deal with the Chinese, at least contemporaneously,

02:47:40.780 --> 02:47:47.180
[Guest]: and become the junior partners of the Chinese against the West, because their mandala is,

02:47:47.180 --> 02:47:53.020
[Guest]: or whatever their strategic, you know, kind of system is, is that the West is the bigger problem.

02:47:54.140 --> 02:48:00.060
[Guest]: They look westwards. Their neighbor that's threatening is the West, and the Chinese are,

02:48:00.060 --> 02:48:07.020
[Guest]: you know, the enemy's enemy, and so their friend. And India no longer really appears very important

02:48:07.020 --> 02:48:13.660
[Guest]: to them. So then Japan is a neighbor's neighbor. But Japan is separated from the great landmass

02:48:13.660 --> 02:48:18.940
[Guest]: of China by water. The stopping power of water prevents Japan playing a very big role on the

02:48:18.940 --> 02:48:25.580
[Guest]: landmass and can't help India out too much. So in the mandala scheme, the only people who can help

02:48:25.580 --> 02:48:32.300
[Guest]: India is, by extension, the West. And not surprisingly, America and the Western powers are

02:48:32.300 --> 02:48:37.740
[Guest]: our enemy's enemy, who become our friends. But in all of that, you know, China doesn't,

02:48:37.740 --> 02:48:45.980
[Guest]: never appears as a friend. Then if you look at the second worldview, which is the worldview of,

02:48:45.980 --> 02:48:52.860
[Guest]: kind of, India as, from the perspective of cosmopolitanism. You see, I almost forgot my

02:48:52.860 --> 02:48:58.380
[Guest]: own book. In this cosmopolitan Nehruvian-Tagore vision, see, that's the most soft-eyed,

02:48:59.020 --> 02:49:06.060
[Guest]: twinkly-eyed view of China as a fellow Asian civilization. It's a viewpoint where nationalism

02:49:06.060 --> 02:49:11.580
[Guest]: doesn't count for so much. In fact, nationalism beyond a point might be the problem. Then it's

02:49:11.580 --> 02:49:18.620
[Guest]: India looking at China through a different lens, as another potential civilizational partner,

02:49:18.620 --> 02:49:23.180
[Guest]: or another part, another civilization that deserves respect, that one can learn from,

02:49:23.180 --> 02:49:29.420
[Guest]: work with, et cetera, et cetera. And that's a worldview that can accommodate China,

02:49:29.420 --> 02:49:35.660
[Guest]: that can look at China as a friend, as a kin, through softer eyes. But then we come to India's

02:49:35.660 --> 02:49:43.900
[Guest]: third worldview, which is our great power view. And actually, here I club Nehru and Golwalkar,

02:49:43.900 --> 02:49:49.340
[Guest]: you know, the RSS supremo, in one bag, because I don't think Gandhi and Tagore would have talked

02:49:49.340 --> 02:49:54.540
[Guest]: about India as a great power. That wasn't their kind of vocabulary. But Nehru partook of that

02:49:55.180 --> 02:50:04.060
[Guest]: vocabulary, and Golwalkar did as well. So in that worldview, then China is a rival.

02:50:04.780 --> 02:50:10.140
[Guest]: And it's not geography that makes China a rival. It's the fact, so that's, you know,

02:50:10.140 --> 02:50:15.740
[Guest]: that's a mandala theory. But this great power view is that China's a rival because it's another great

02:50:15.740 --> 02:50:22.220
[Guest]: power. You see, just in that worldview, even the United States would be a challenge to India

02:50:22.220 --> 02:50:27.980
[Guest]: because it's another great power. So China, from this great power view, is that, well, great powers

02:50:27.980 --> 02:50:32.940
[Guest]: can never be really good friends. Although in Nehru, you know, you said earlier that he had this

02:50:32.940 --> 02:50:39.340
[Guest]: kind of nice view of China and a romantic view, but he also always had a doubt and worry about

02:50:39.340 --> 02:50:45.340
[Guest]: China as another great power. And some of his views are almost racist as well. And Golwalkar too,

02:50:46.060 --> 02:50:50.620
[Guest]: you know, wrote sometimes about China in a very bad way. And the book that he wrote it in has,

02:50:50.620 --> 02:50:55.900
[Guest]: you know, you can't buy that book. It's been taken away and hidden by the RSS and so on.

02:50:55.900 --> 02:51:02.940
[Guest]: So, you know, both of them, with their own great power view, could not look at China as anything

02:51:02.940 --> 02:51:07.660
[Guest]: but a kind of a rival, although their view was slightly different about where the rivalry came

02:51:07.660 --> 02:51:13.820
[Guest]: from. So you're right. The only, out of these six worldviews, three Chinese and three Indian,

02:51:13.820 --> 02:51:20.220
[Guest]: the only nice one was the Gandhi and Tagore one. Gandhi didn't know China that well, I think,

02:51:20.220 --> 02:51:24.140
[Guest]: just my sense of it. I don't know enough about his writings on China. But Tagore, of course,

02:51:24.140 --> 02:51:29.900
[Guest]: knew it much better. And then, you know, he started Chinabavan and the whole attempt to

02:51:29.900 --> 02:51:35.420
[Guest]: bring Chinese and Indian aesthetics and artists and writers and intellectuals together.

02:51:35.420 --> 02:51:42.780
[Guest]: You know, those were the only two who could really have a very nice accommodative kin view of China.

02:51:42.780 --> 02:51:48.700
[Guest]: And yet, as I point out, and you reminded me, that those are the only two who today,

02:51:49.260 --> 02:51:57.100
[Guest]: where do those worldviews figure? I mean, there's the obvious, you know, October 2 view of Gandhi,

02:51:57.100 --> 02:52:02.220
[Guest]: which even the right wing plays up. But there's no great affection or, you know,

02:52:02.220 --> 02:52:07.180
[Guest]: kind of partaking of Gandhi and thought beyond the point in India anymore. I mean, it's an

02:52:07.180 --> 02:52:12.860
[Guest]: obligatory schoolboy view, father of the nation view, but not a real engagement with Gandhi

02:52:12.860 --> 02:52:19.660
[Guest]: and his values. And likewise, where is Tagore today? I mean, and his thoughts about post

02:52:19.660 --> 02:52:26.140
[Guest]: nationalism or a worldview transcending nationalism. Again, sadly, I think probably

02:52:26.140 --> 02:52:32.060
[Amit Varma]: really not there very much. Yeah, and it's very interesting that you should, you know,

02:52:32.060 --> 02:52:35.340
[Amit Varma]: talk of Nehru and Golwalkar at the same breath. Like I often say that, you know,

02:52:35.340 --> 02:52:40.620
[Amit Varma]: Modi for all his rants against the Congress and the family is actually very Nehruvian and his

02:52:40.620 --> 02:52:46.300
[Amit Varma]: top down vision of how the state should rule society, and is very much like Indira in his

02:52:46.300 --> 02:52:51.500
[Amit Varma]: unquenching will to power as it were, and the desire to do anything to get there, that whole

02:52:51.500 --> 02:52:57.100
[Amit Varma]: oppressiveness and authoritarianism that comes from him. But Nehru and Golwalkar is an interesting

02:52:58.140 --> 02:53:04.380
[Amit Varma]: sort of connection there in this context as well. Let's let's kind of talk about perimeters there.

02:53:04.380 --> 02:53:08.220
[Amit Varma]: And I found that chapter really fascinating. And I have actually covered elements of it in

02:53:08.220 --> 02:53:13.580
[Amit Varma]: previous episodes with Manoj Kevalramani, Hamsini Hariharan and Shivani Mehta. I've done a bunch of

02:53:13.580 --> 02:53:20.700
[Amit Varma]: these episodes. But nevertheless, briefly, give us a sense of what actually happens. Like at one

02:53:20.700 --> 02:53:25.020
[Amit Varma]: point, you'll talk about, I'll quote from your book, because I found this a very illuminating

02:53:25.020 --> 02:53:29.020
[Amit Varma]: paragraph to which kind of sums a lot of things up, where you write, quote,

02:53:29.020 --> 02:53:33.740
[Amit Varma]: in the 1950s, both saw the other as insincere and stubborn in the border discussions.

02:53:33.740 --> 02:53:39.020
[Amit Varma]: They concluded that the other had failed to honor commitments on Tibet. And they came to regard the

02:53:39.020 --> 02:53:44.780
[Amit Varma]: other as militarily aggressive and themselves as militarily defensive. Having said that now and then

02:53:44.780 --> 02:53:50.460
[Amit Varma]: the differences on the border did narrow, they agreed on the status of Tibet in 1950, 51 and 54.

02:53:50.460 --> 02:53:56.620
[Amit Varma]: And they tried to avoid escalatory military actions. So it seems to me that one at a level

02:53:56.620 --> 02:54:01.260
[Amit Varma]: of where their posturing is that this belongs to us and that belongs to us. There's absolutely no

02:54:01.260 --> 02:54:06.860
[Amit Varma]: way that there is a common ground there that if you know, one army is an exposition, which the

02:54:06.860 --> 02:54:12.380
[Amit Varma]: other country claims belongs to them, it will be viewed as an act of aggression by one and as an

02:54:12.380 --> 02:54:17.980
[Amit Varma]: act of defense by the other. And there's no getting around that. Yet it seems for decades for large

02:54:17.980 --> 02:54:24.300
[Amit Varma]: parts of our history, there was a certain practicality about how far you can push these

02:54:24.300 --> 02:54:29.740
[Amit Varma]: differences, whether at Aksai Chin or Arunachal or whatever. And there weren't skirmishes. In fact,

02:54:29.740 --> 02:54:36.140
[Amit Varma]: at one point, there was a proposal of doing a kind of a swap. So tell me a little bit more about sort

02:54:36.140 --> 02:54:42.460
[Amit Varma]: of the arc of this relationship as regards to border differences. And, you know, the possible

02:54:42.460 --> 02:54:48.940
[Amit Varma]: reasons that it's kind of exploded, you know, in phases over the last decade, like really coming

02:54:48.940 --> 02:54:53.820
[Guest]: to a head last year, of course, in Ladakh. Yeah, the border issues and the perimeters

02:54:53.820 --> 02:54:59.260
[Guest]: issue and I call it perimeters just to stay with the peas. But it's an interesting one,

02:54:59.260 --> 02:55:06.620
[Guest]: because I think we've lost track of that it began as a cooperative venture. So definitely,

02:55:06.620 --> 02:55:14.620
[Guest]: the two sides did begin a process of negotiation and talks. And it seemed to go fairly well for

02:55:14.620 --> 02:55:21.420
[Guest]: about four or five years until about 1954. And the issue of of the border cannot be divorced

02:55:21.420 --> 02:55:29.100
[Guest]: from Tibet. Because obviously, Tibet is where India meets China. And so it was intimately

02:55:29.100 --> 02:55:35.100
[Guest]: connected with the status of Tibet as well. And again, the first four or five years brought

02:55:35.100 --> 02:55:42.380
[Guest]: cooperation on Tibet. India conceded that China basically owned Tibet, and concluded a treaty in

02:55:42.380 --> 02:55:49.580
[Guest]: 1954, and backed a certain agreement that the Chinese had with the Tibetans in 1950-51 as well.

02:55:49.580 --> 02:55:56.140
[Guest]: So it began well, you know, one might have expected that things would get better. And that

02:55:56.140 --> 02:56:01.820
[Guest]: was belied, obviously. And what I try to show in the book is as balanced in as balanced a way as

02:56:01.820 --> 02:56:10.060
[Guest]: possible, is that, in a sense, I mean, it wasn't maliciousness, and it wasn't point scoring. And

02:56:10.060 --> 02:56:15.740
[Guest]: it wasn't, you know, a desire altogether to hurt the other side. In those initial years,

02:56:15.740 --> 02:56:22.220
[Guest]: I pointed out that there was a kind of a split in the negotiating stance that they had. There was

02:56:22.220 --> 02:56:28.300
[Guest]: the so called sooner school, my term, and the later school on both sides. So my grandfather,

02:56:28.300 --> 02:56:35.340
[Guest]: Girija Bajpai, and KPS Menon, Shivshankar Menon's grandfather as well, they were two of the senior

02:56:35.340 --> 02:56:41.980
[Guest]: most foreign service people. And they were in the, with Sardar Patel, they were in the sooner school,

02:56:41.980 --> 02:56:47.180
[Guest]: negotiate with China, because the Chinese are going to raise the border issue, and twin an

02:56:47.180 --> 02:56:54.300
[Guest]: agreement of the border to the status of Tibet. We will agree to Chinese kind of sovereignty over

02:56:54.300 --> 02:56:59.740
[Guest]: Tibet, if they come to an accommodation on the border. But Panekar, who was our ambassador,

02:56:59.740 --> 02:57:06.620
[Guest]: the historian, geopolitical thinker, who was our ambassador in Beijing, he was of the later school,

02:57:06.620 --> 02:57:12.380
[Guest]: he said, don't raise the border issue, because we won't agree, and then be reforced to negotiate.

02:57:12.380 --> 02:57:18.620
[Guest]: And we don't want to negotiate, because in some ways, our position in administrative control in

02:57:18.620 --> 02:57:25.260
[Guest]: the furthest reaches, particularly in NIFA, which is Arunachal Pradesh today, is very weak. So we've

02:57:25.260 --> 02:57:32.060
[Guest]: got to buy time. It'll come, but let's, let's wait for the Chinese to raise it. And Nehru kind of

02:57:32.060 --> 02:57:37.980
[Guest]: oscillated between the two, and then eventually came out on the side of Panekar. And the Chinese,

02:57:37.980 --> 02:57:46.540
[Guest]: you see, I think, and I tried to show, had exactly the same debate. Their Tibetologists and their

02:57:46.540 --> 02:57:52.620
[Guest]: cartographers came to the view that China, that the Indians were not playing fair, the Chinese had

02:57:52.620 --> 02:57:58.460
[Guest]: a case, and they should raise it sooner rather than later. And the politicos, that is Zhou Enlai

02:57:58.460 --> 02:58:04.540
[Guest]: and Mao and others in the Communist Party felt that the time wasn't right, that China was too

02:58:04.540 --> 02:58:12.540
[Guest]: weak. And they would deal with India later on this matter, and not provoke. So the first five years,

02:58:12.540 --> 02:58:20.300
[Guest]: from 1949 to 1954, they were both tiptoeing around the issue, both kind of expecting to join the

02:58:20.300 --> 02:58:26.620
[Guest]: issue at some point. And probably, you know, they were still fairly friendly, rhetorically, and so

02:58:26.620 --> 02:58:31.340
[Guest]: on. And an accommodation might have been reached, but it wasn't. And then things got worse and worse.

02:58:31.340 --> 02:58:37.580
[Guest]: And, but when they did begin to talk, and then I'll roll the movie forward faster. When they did

02:58:37.580 --> 02:58:43.900
[Guest]: begin to talk in about 1954, both sides did things or said things that could be prone to

02:58:43.900 --> 02:58:49.740
[Guest]: misinterpretation by the other side. You know, Nehru insisted on issuing some maps where Aksai

02:58:49.740 --> 02:58:54.860
[Guest]: Chin seemed to be very much within our territory. And he did this just around the time of a meeting

02:58:54.860 --> 02:59:01.580
[Guest]: with Zhou Enlai. Zhou Enlai didn't take umbrage. But as soon as he went back, the Chinese began to

02:59:01.580 --> 02:59:07.100
[Guest]: issue maps of their own that contradicted that claim. And when India objected, the Chinese said,

02:59:07.100 --> 02:59:13.020
[Guest]: oh, no, no, these are the old Go Min Dang maps, give us time. So we did stuff with maps that they

02:59:13.020 --> 02:59:19.980
[Guest]: didn't, that caused suspicion amongst them. They did stuff with maps that we thought was dishonest

02:59:19.980 --> 02:59:26.700
[Guest]: as well. Nehru was not even sure that we really had a strong case on Aksai Chin. And some of his

02:59:26.700 --> 02:59:34.700
[Guest]: advisors also didn't think so. It was really only when S. Gopal, the historian, went to Britain

02:59:34.700 --> 02:59:40.860
[Guest]: and looked at the archives there and came back that India began to feel that it had a much

02:59:40.860 --> 02:59:45.740
[Guest]: stronger case on Aksai Chin. And Nehru began to make much stronger statements publicly about

02:59:45.740 --> 02:59:51.100
[Guest]: owning Aksai Chin. And the Chinese went through something similar. Their records also had been

02:59:51.100 --> 02:59:55.980
[Guest]: disrupted by the Civil War. At least that's a thought experiment that I do. Some records may

02:59:55.980 --> 03:00:01.100
[Guest]: have gone to Taipei, you know, when the Go Min Dang ran away with all those documents. Some may

03:00:01.100 --> 03:00:07.500
[Guest]: have been destroyed in the Civil War. So they had to reconstruct their stance as well. So, you know,

03:00:07.500 --> 03:00:13.180
[Guest]: I give both sides a long rope, in effect, saying let's not jump to this conclusion on both sides

03:00:13.180 --> 03:00:18.300
[Guest]: that the other was thoroughly dishonest and trying to outpoint the other. There were genuine

03:00:18.300 --> 03:00:24.700
[Guest]: administrative, political doubts, worries, weaknesses. They had come out, both had come

03:00:24.700 --> 03:00:29.900
[Guest]: out of a Civil War. In India, the Civil War was Congress Party and Muslim League. In China,

03:00:29.900 --> 03:00:35.180
[Guest]: it was Go Min Dang Communist Party, which is a literal Civil War. They had both come out of a

03:00:35.180 --> 03:00:40.220
[Guest]: partition. After all, the creation of Taiwan is a partition. And Hong Kong was still there,

03:00:40.220 --> 03:00:44.700
[Guest]: and Macau was still separate. They had both come out of a world war. They briefly fought on the

03:00:44.700 --> 03:00:49.020
[Guest]: same side against the Japanese, but they both came out of a chaos of a world war, the Chinese

03:00:49.020 --> 03:00:55.580
[Guest]: particularly, because they were occupied. We were not occupied. They both came out of a period of

03:00:55.580 --> 03:01:01.660
[Guest]: war. We were fighting the Pakistanis in 47, 48. They were fighting the Americans and South Koreans

03:01:01.660 --> 03:01:08.140
[Guest]: in Korea. Both were confronting the Cold War. So, you know, it's quite forgivable that they

03:01:08.140 --> 03:01:13.980
[Guest]: didn't know their minds altogether about the border themselves, each other, etc., etc. You

03:01:13.980 --> 03:01:18.380
[Guest]: know, so let's be a bit more forgiving of both sides and not jump to the conclusion they just

03:01:18.380 --> 03:01:24.380
[Guest]: wanted to screw each other. And that's what I tried to reconstruct. But of course, they also

03:01:24.380 --> 03:01:31.580
[Guest]: did, unfortunately, read each other in a negative light. What might have been innocent

03:01:32.300 --> 03:01:38.860
[Guest]: prevarications, contradictions, hesitations, was seen as the other side as you're trying to screw

03:01:38.860 --> 03:01:45.100
[Guest]: me and being dishonest with me and fooling me. So not surprisingly, things increasingly fell apart.

03:01:45.100 --> 03:01:50.780
[Guest]: And that brings us to the swap, which I suppose was the last great moment when things could have

03:01:50.780 --> 03:01:57.580
[Guest]: been salvaged. And it's true the Chinese under Zhou Enlai, when he came for that fateful summit

03:01:57.580 --> 03:02:03.260
[Guest]: in 1960 to Delhi, the Indians already knew that he was bringing a proposal like that.

03:02:03.820 --> 03:02:09.820
[Guest]: They weren't stupid. And this whole idea that Nehru and his advisor were naive, here was Chacha

03:02:09.820 --> 03:02:17.900
[Guest]: Nehru in his kind of slightly indulgent, benighted, faltering, foolish way. You know, he knew from

03:02:17.900 --> 03:02:23.100
[Guest]: the beginning, thanks to Panicker, that there was a problem. Thanks to G.S. Bajpai, thanks to Patel.

03:02:23.100 --> 03:02:28.780
[Guest]: The letter that Patel wrote in 1950, just before he died to Nehru, alerting him, was written by

03:02:28.780 --> 03:02:34.620
[Guest]: my grandfather, the draft, and then Patel played around with it and sent it off. They were not

03:02:34.620 --> 03:02:40.860
[Guest]: naive at all. But, you know, there were other considerations. Anyway, Zhou Enlai arrives in

03:02:40.860 --> 03:02:48.460
[Guest]: Delhi, as the Indians expected, with the proposal. But Nehru and his advisors already had lost courage.

03:02:48.460 --> 03:02:53.660
[Guest]: Nehru said famously, which I quote in the book, if I go for the swap, I will not survive as a

03:02:53.660 --> 03:02:57.820
[Guest]: prime minister. And who are the people who would have been his biggest critics? The right-wing

03:02:57.820 --> 03:03:03.180
[Guest]: critics in his own party, and the right-wing critics outside his party, the Jansang and others,

03:03:03.180 --> 03:03:09.180
[Guest]: but also perhaps the Swatantra party of Raja Gopalacharian, who were more America-inclined.

03:03:09.180 --> 03:03:15.260
[Guest]: And they turned out to be formidable forces, as Ram Guha shows in his work on this period. So

03:03:16.380 --> 03:03:22.860
[Guest]: they very quickly basically shut Zhou Enlai down. And, you know, they had reasons. It wasn't just

03:03:22.860 --> 03:03:29.020
[Guest]: the domestic political sphere. They had concerns of, as I think R.K. Nehru said, or was it B.K.

03:03:29.020 --> 03:03:34.620
[Guest]: Nehru at that time? I forget. I'm forgetting my own book here. And the foreign secretary of the

03:03:34.620 --> 03:03:39.980
[Guest]: time was saying, you know, in 1960, that if we give in to the Chinese now, under pressure,

03:03:39.980 --> 03:03:45.340
[Guest]: because border incidents were already occurring, what's to stop the Chinese learning the lesson

03:03:45.340 --> 03:03:51.580
[Guest]: that if you push the Indians militarily, they will give again? So we get a swap. And then they go,

03:03:52.380 --> 03:03:58.300
[Guest]: oh, no, we actually forgot we want some more territory. And then there's another set of

03:03:58.300 --> 03:04:01.900
[Guest]: border incidents. And they would be the expectation that the Indians would cave in again.

03:04:01.900 --> 03:04:08.060
[Guest]: And they also concluded that Zhou Enlai had never put anything down on paper. So this was a kind of

03:04:08.060 --> 03:04:15.180
[Guest]: chatty proposal. And what was really the, would Mao go for it? Were there other forces? Or was

03:04:15.180 --> 03:04:22.220
[Guest]: this more or less a good-natured proposal by Zhou Enlai, slightly intended to smoke the Indians out

03:04:22.220 --> 03:04:27.740
[Guest]: and buy time? So there are all kinds of reasons that India could worry about the status of the

03:04:27.740 --> 03:04:34.140
[Guest]: proposals. I mean, the Chinese concluded from this episode that the Indians were simply not willing

03:04:34.140 --> 03:04:40.300
[Guest]: to, A, enter into discussion seriously, you're not going for a reasonable proposal, they were

03:04:40.300 --> 03:04:45.820
[Guest]: imperialists, they wanted to take over Tibet, etc, etc. And you just couldn't do business with

03:04:45.820 --> 03:04:52.300
[Guest]: them. Even so, there was still some attempts to try and deal with it. But it collapsed, partly

03:04:52.300 --> 03:04:58.060
[Guest]: with these military moves that occurred. And so, you know, the chapter shows that one period of

03:04:58.060 --> 03:05:07.100
[Guest]: proto-cooperation through a collapse into war, peaking in 62, occurred. And just to take very

03:05:07.100 --> 03:05:14.460
[Guest]: quickly the story forward, after 62, we go through almost a similar arc. Again, almost immediately

03:05:14.460 --> 03:05:22.540
[Guest]: in 63-64, India sends out messages to try and get some talks going again. It has a certain amount of

03:05:22.540 --> 03:05:30.860
[Guest]: receptivity, an arc of cooperation begins, and it does well until a much longer timescale here,

03:05:30.860 --> 03:05:37.100
[Guest]: right up to about, I would say, the early 2000s. Maybe 2006 is the turning point when the Chinese

03:05:37.100 --> 03:05:44.380
[Guest]: ambassador in Delhi, very publicly at that time, says, by the way, we own all of Arunachal Pradesh,

03:05:44.380 --> 03:05:49.820
[Guest]: so please, you Indians, don't forget it. And there was consternation because we hadn't heard that

03:05:49.820 --> 03:05:55.820
[Guest]: kind of blunt statement for the Chinese for a long time. And from 2006 onwards, then, you can see a

03:05:55.820 --> 03:06:03.820
[Guest]: deterioration in the relationship. By 2010, India, perhaps in reaction, stops making fulsome

03:06:04.780 --> 03:06:09.500
[Guest]: statements in the joint statements that, you know, happened with summits about, oh, yeah, yeah,

03:06:09.500 --> 03:06:16.620
[Guest]: Tibet is yours. And so we stopped doing that. They keep insisting Arunachal is theirs. I mean,

03:06:16.620 --> 03:06:20.220
[Guest]: of course, they'd said it earlier, but there was a long period of time where they stopped insisting

03:06:20.220 --> 03:06:28.780
[Guest]: on it very publicly. That's 2010. 2013, we're almost back to where we are now. You have the

03:06:28.780 --> 03:06:36.620
[Guest]: Depsang Plains incident when Manmohan Singh is in his last year. That occurs just as Li Keqiang,

03:06:36.620 --> 03:06:43.580
[Guest]: the current premier, is coming to meet Manmohan Singh. 2014 is Chumar. Modi and Xi are sitting

03:06:43.580 --> 03:06:51.740
[Guest]: on a jhoola in Gandhinagar, and the troops are faced off in Chumar. 2015 is Burtsey. And this

03:06:51.740 --> 03:06:56.460
[Guest]: is an episode that people have sort of forgotten. I don't know why the Indian media has largely

03:06:56.460 --> 03:07:04.940
[Guest]: forgotten it. And so 2013, 14, 15, annually, there are these fracases or confrontation.

03:07:04.940 --> 03:07:11.660
[Guest]: 2017 is Doklam, 73 days of staring each other in the face. And 2020 is Ladakh,

03:07:11.660 --> 03:07:20.140
[Guest]: back in the eastern sector with Chumar, Depsang, and Burtsey. So that's the arc.

03:07:21.660 --> 03:07:27.900
[Guest]: So we didn't end up in the 1962 war. We ended up in Ladakh 2020. It's an arc of cooperation

03:07:27.900 --> 03:07:35.500
[Guest]: through attempts to settle the issue. There were very thorough border talks from 1981 onwards. We

03:07:35.500 --> 03:07:42.380
[Guest]: never stopped negotiating on the border after 1981, which people forget. But again, it degraded,

03:07:43.020 --> 03:07:52.620
[Guest]: and we went into near war in 2020. In 62, we went into war. So, you know, it's an odd thing that

03:07:52.620 --> 03:07:57.180
[Guest]: we've had two repeat cycles. And at the heart of it, I mean, I don't know exactly what the answer

03:07:57.180 --> 03:08:04.220
[Guest]: is, but fundamentally, there's an issue of trust there, which is a tautology, right? You don't

03:08:04.220 --> 03:08:07.980
[Guest]: cooperate because you don't trust, and you don't trust because you don't have a history of

03:08:07.980 --> 03:08:13.580
[Guest]: cooperation. So then, I mean, tautology is useful, because they make us ask, well, why don't you

03:08:13.580 --> 03:08:19.100
[Guest]: trust? How can I break out of this tautology? And here, I would just end with some thoughts,

03:08:19.100 --> 03:08:25.180
[Guest]: which is they're unprovable, but they're up for discussion, which is the political cultures of

03:08:25.180 --> 03:08:30.860
[Guest]: the two sides, really, in a sense. You've got liberal India working in constitutional ways,

03:08:31.420 --> 03:08:37.420
[Guest]: taking constitutional ways from the British, and that whole mindset from internal negotiations to

03:08:37.420 --> 03:08:43.980
[Guest]: external negotiations of a certain kind. You know, they're settled borders by treaty and customary

03:08:43.980 --> 03:08:49.820
[Guest]: understandings, and that's how you deal with the problem with China. That's Nehru. Whereas the

03:08:49.820 --> 03:08:57.100
[Guest]: Chinese, they're two revolutionaries there, hard-bitten, cold-eyed men who went through

03:08:57.100 --> 03:09:04.380
[Guest]: cataclysmic total warfare. They are deal-makers. They're strategic-minded people. They think that

03:09:05.180 --> 03:09:11.580
[Guest]: the liberal adornments of law and constitution and all of that is some bourgeois idea, which

03:09:11.580 --> 03:09:16.220
[Guest]: is supposed to mask reality. After all, what does the middle class do and the capitalists?

03:09:16.220 --> 03:09:21.660
[Guest]: They pretend to give you all these freedoms and protections of the law to make sure that they

03:09:21.660 --> 03:09:27.100
[Guest]: actually come out on top. So they looked at this whole insistence on constitutionalism and

03:09:27.100 --> 03:09:34.460
[Guest]: negotiation and insistence on rule of law and treaties as trying to fool the Chinese.

03:09:34.460 --> 03:09:39.900
[Guest]: So, you know, they just couldn't quite comprehend where Nehru was coming from,

03:09:39.900 --> 03:09:43.660
[Guest]: and likewise, the Nehruvians thought that they were dishonest. And then, as I said,

03:09:43.660 --> 03:09:49.900
[Guest]: all these hesitations and cartographic kind of weaknesses that they had made each suspicious

03:09:49.900 --> 03:09:56.860
[Guest]: of the other. Both sides, ironically, were weak states, and weak states find it difficult

03:09:56.860 --> 03:10:01.740
[Guest]: to cooperate with each other because they can't convince the other that their moves are, you know.

03:10:02.300 --> 03:10:06.860
[Guest]: Then there's history. The two countries I try and point out, or the two civilizations,

03:10:06.860 --> 03:10:13.580
[Guest]: their two heartlands never had a very rich diplomatic history. They traded, monks went back

03:10:13.580 --> 03:10:20.700
[Guest]: and forth, et cetera, et cetera. But empire to empire, they didn't have a long history of knowing

03:10:20.700 --> 03:10:26.940
[Guest]: each other's ways, which could see them through. And what do they get from that history? They get

03:10:26.940 --> 03:10:32.380
[Guest]: predictability of how the other, but most important, they learn a lesson about does the other

03:10:32.380 --> 03:10:39.340
[Guest]: side keep to commitments, i.e. promises. If you feel the other side keeps to promises, then you

03:10:39.340 --> 03:10:44.620
[Guest]: might begin to think, okay, if we did a stucco deal, they'll honor it. And the last point is,

03:10:44.620 --> 03:10:48.780
[Guest]: where does trust come from? It comes from, you know, if you're part of the same civilization

03:10:48.780 --> 03:10:53.500
[Guest]: or culture, you have a certain kind of sense of, I understand where you're coming from,

03:10:53.500 --> 03:10:58.300
[Guest]: we come from the same place kind of stuff. But for all that, China and India, you know,

03:10:58.300 --> 03:11:02.700
[Guest]: don't come from that place. They don't have that assurance, that immersion in a common culture.

03:11:03.420 --> 03:11:09.500
[Guest]: And so I think, you know, those are some reasons that they just, there was a lack of trust. And

03:11:09.500 --> 03:11:15.500
[Guest]: to some extent, all that continues to be the case. So your other two P's, of course, are about like,

03:11:15.500 --> 03:11:20.380
[Amit Varma]: one is about partnerships, which is about how geopolitical considerations have kind of kept

03:11:20.380 --> 03:11:25.180
[Amit Varma]: them on the opposite side with, you know, India will first go with Russia and then with the US

03:11:25.180 --> 03:11:29.260
[Amit Varma]: and, you know, and all of these things ensure that they never end up on the same side. I mean,

03:11:29.260 --> 03:11:32.460
[Amit Varma]: basically, like you pointed out, they're on the same side only once, which is in the Second World

03:11:32.460 --> 03:11:37.820
[Amit Varma]: War. Otherwise, they're never on the same side of a conflict. And your final chapter on power is

03:11:37.820 --> 03:11:43.260
[Amit Varma]: about the great power imbalance, where China has become a much more powerful country. And therefore,

03:11:43.260 --> 03:11:47.660
[Amit Varma]: China is saying we will not give any concessions because we are much more powerful. And India,

03:11:47.660 --> 03:11:52.220
[Amit Varma]: which recognizes that it is not as powerful, but it aspires to be, will say we will not make any

03:11:52.220 --> 03:11:57.100
[Amit Varma]: more concessions because you know, all kinds of reasons it looks bad. And, you know, what would

03:11:57.100 --> 03:12:01.820
[Amit Varma]: our voters say and all of that. I'll direct listeners to go and just buy the book and read

03:12:01.820 --> 03:12:07.020
[Amit Varma]: it because it's a fantastic one sitting read. And really, I don't think we'll do justice to it if we

03:12:07.020 --> 03:12:12.940
[Amit Varma]: try to really summarize it. But I'll end with a couple of final questions. And one of them is this

03:12:12.940 --> 03:12:17.900
[Amit Varma]: that it seems to me that post 1950s, what has happened to our relationship is almost like this

03:12:17.900 --> 03:12:24.540
[Amit Varma]: great tragedy where both countries for various reasons, various reasons which are rational and

03:12:24.540 --> 03:12:30.700
[Amit Varma]: understandable, have somehow gotten locked into this antagonistic relationship, where it has become

03:12:30.700 --> 03:12:35.500
[Amit Varma]: impossible to trust the other side, again, for good reasons. It's not as if there are any bad

03:12:35.500 --> 03:12:42.380
[Amit Varma]: actors in this, but it becomes impossible to trust the other side, and which led to that one eruption

03:12:42.380 --> 03:12:47.340
[Amit Varma]: of the 62 conflict. But what has happened since then, is that both sides seem to have recognized

03:12:47.340 --> 03:12:52.380
[Amit Varma]: that this is, you know, let's make a stable equilibrium out of this and not enter into any

03:12:52.380 --> 03:12:57.340
[Amit Varma]: more skirmishes because war after all is a negative sum game and blah, blah, blah. So let's just ignore

03:12:57.340 --> 03:13:02.220
[Amit Varma]: the problem. And we'll make occasional noises and we'll posture occasionally, but we won't actually

03:13:02.220 --> 03:13:06.780
[Amit Varma]: do anything against each other. And let's just keep it as it is. And it's it kind of stays that

03:13:06.780 --> 03:13:13.340
[Amit Varma]: way for decades. And yet over the last few years, it seems to have exploded into a different kind

03:13:13.340 --> 03:13:18.700
[Amit Varma]: of place where the Chinese clearly want something and these these border disputes don't just seem

03:13:18.700 --> 03:13:23.900
[Amit Varma]: to be about borders because, you know, I mean, these are, you know, Siachen is important for

03:13:23.900 --> 03:13:28.300
[Amit Varma]: India, Aksaichen is important for China, but they're not that important that you risk a full

03:13:28.300 --> 03:13:34.220
[Amit Varma]: fledged war or that you break this equilibrium. Also, the danger here is we enter a vicious cycle

03:13:34.220 --> 03:13:39.020
[Amit Varma]: where we have jingoism on one side met by jingoism on the other side, and it just escalates and

03:13:39.020 --> 03:13:45.420
[Amit Varma]: becomes worse and worse. So the first of my two questions is that why is this happening? Why the

03:13:45.420 --> 03:13:49.820
[Amit Varma]: sudden belligerence from them? Why have they kind of upped the game? What are the kind of

03:13:50.460 --> 03:13:54.380
[Amit Varma]: competing theories and what seems most plausible to you?

03:13:54.380 --> 03:13:58.140
[Guest]: Well, I'll go back to these four Ps, I want to investigate all four. But I think

03:13:58.780 --> 03:14:05.260
[Guest]: that, you know, in search of a fairly simple answer, I would go for the simplest, which is that

03:14:05.260 --> 03:14:11.980
[Guest]: it's the perimeters of Tibet, which is the Chinese built a lot of infrastructure in Tibet, which is

03:14:11.980 --> 03:14:16.700
[Guest]: relatively easy to do, because it's a plateau. And they did massive amounts of building there

03:14:16.700 --> 03:14:23.820
[Guest]: in the late 90s, early 2000s. India then alarmed by this suddenly started to get going on building

03:14:23.820 --> 03:14:27.980
[Guest]: its own infrastructure under the Manmohan Singh government first, a little bit under Vajpayee,

03:14:27.980 --> 03:14:32.940
[Guest]: and then again, with Modi. So all three governments have played their role in pushing

03:14:32.940 --> 03:14:38.940
[Guest]: or playing catch up. The difficulty on the Indian side is that our roads are twisting turning. We're

03:14:38.940 --> 03:14:43.660
[Guest]: going from the plains up in straight up into these massive hills. So our road building and

03:14:43.660 --> 03:14:49.580
[Guest]: infrastructure is much more difficult to do. And so it's not surprising that it's slower. I mean,

03:14:49.580 --> 03:14:52.700
[Guest]: there are other reasons too, we were reluctant to build it earlier, and so on and so forth. But

03:14:54.140 --> 03:14:59.020
[Guest]: so we've slowly started to catch up. We've rehabilitated some in our flatlands in Aksai

03:14:59.020 --> 03:15:06.700
[Guest]: Chin. We've rehabilitated some of the airfields going back to an earlier time, excuse me. And

03:15:08.220 --> 03:15:13.340
[Guest]: that has alarmed the Chinese, as we've caught up. Now, we can say it's unfair, because they did

03:15:13.340 --> 03:15:18.540
[Guest]: their infrastructure first. Why should they object to ours? But this is a strategic issue. There's

03:15:18.540 --> 03:15:25.340
[Guest]: no fairness issue here. This is again, you know, we're talking the fairness game. They're talking

03:15:25.340 --> 03:15:30.620
[Guest]: a strategic picture. And to understand what's strategic about it, which again, we don't

03:15:30.620 --> 03:15:34.940
[Guest]: appreciate enough, probably on our side is, and I've been saying this in some of the other talks

03:15:34.940 --> 03:15:40.060
[Guest]: is, when you think the border issue, when you think conflict with China, please think Tibet.

03:15:40.060 --> 03:15:46.700
[Guest]: They are so super sensitive about Tibet, in a way that we don't appreciate. You know, we think that,

03:15:46.700 --> 03:15:51.180
[Guest]: oh, we did that deal back in 54, that they should be happy with it. And that's the end of the story.

03:15:51.180 --> 03:15:56.060
[Guest]: No, there was a rebellion in Tibet after that, that they accused us of fostering and working

03:15:56.060 --> 03:15:59.980
[Guest]: with the Americans. And there's evidence that certainly the Americans very much pushed it.

03:16:00.620 --> 03:16:07.340
[Guest]: But beyond that, when you build these roads and infrastructure, I mean, they're reading that as

03:16:07.340 --> 03:16:13.260
[Guest]: not a defensive move, but potentially a move into Aksai Chin to again, endanger their road

03:16:13.260 --> 03:16:19.980
[Guest]: from Xinjiang down into Tibet, and to potentially at a moment of internal instability in Tibet.

03:16:19.980 --> 03:16:24.780
[Guest]: And I'll come to that in a minute, that India could play a role then. I mean, maybe not invade

03:16:24.780 --> 03:16:30.860
[Guest]: and take over, but cause significant trouble at the border, and send a message to rebellions

03:16:30.860 --> 03:16:37.980
[Guest]: within Tibet, which then the Chinese would have difficulty handling. So I think that's the thing

03:16:37.980 --> 03:16:43.660
[Guest]: that we have to keep in mind on the Indian side. And we're going into a dangerous period. So it's

03:16:43.660 --> 03:16:49.340
[Guest]: not just the roads per se, it's that for China, we're going into a dangerous period for them.

03:16:49.340 --> 03:16:54.140
[Guest]: What's that danger? Well, the Dalai Lama is a wonderful person, and I hope he lives for a very

03:16:54.140 --> 03:17:02.620
[Guest]: long time. But we know we're entering a period of transition. And he will depart this world,

03:17:02.620 --> 03:17:09.260
[Guest]: sadly, at some point. And then where are we? The Chinese will put up their successor.

03:17:10.620 --> 03:17:15.900
[Guest]: The overseas Chinese community, including very powerfully in India, will want to do their own

03:17:15.900 --> 03:17:22.460
[Guest]: succession planning and process. There may be Tibet diasporic communities in the West who will

03:17:22.460 --> 03:17:28.060
[Guest]: do their own search, which would not agree with either of the other two searches. So one can

03:17:28.060 --> 03:17:33.900
[Guest]: imagine a very difficult time if you put yourself in the place of Beijing. And strategic thinking,

03:17:33.900 --> 03:17:41.020
[Guest]: you have to think about how your adversary thinks about problems. So they can see a political

03:17:41.020 --> 03:17:49.820
[Guest]: strategic problem arising in the next 10, 15 years, perhaps sooner, where the Tibet issue boils up,

03:17:49.820 --> 03:17:55.420
[Guest]: the Indians have completed their infrastructure and are much more able to intervene or cause

03:17:55.420 --> 03:17:59.340
[Guest]: trouble at the border, coincident with an internal rebellion and uncertainties.

03:18:01.500 --> 03:18:08.700
[Guest]: And it may be that they would be generous towards us and say, whoever's ruling in Delhi would not

03:18:08.700 --> 03:18:15.420
[Guest]: deliberately stoke the problem, but would an Indian ruler, given public opinion in India,

03:18:15.420 --> 03:18:22.460
[Guest]: be able to handle the fallout of the succession and what it would mean with China? So from every

03:18:22.460 --> 03:18:29.020
[Guest]: point of view, they would be extremely worried about the Tibet problem. And that's the issue,

03:18:29.020 --> 03:18:34.860
[Guest]: you know, I think, which is that it's a bit incomprehensible to us that they're so substantially

03:18:34.860 --> 03:18:39.900
[Guest]: in charge of Tibet and all of that. What are they worried about? Why do they worry about the border?

03:18:39.900 --> 03:18:44.700
[Guest]: We can't invade them, et cetera. And as you said, the slices of territory that might be involved,

03:18:44.700 --> 03:18:51.020
[Guest]: barring Arunachal Pradesh, seem to be very small. But there's Tibet. There's their worry about

03:18:51.020 --> 03:18:58.780
[Guest]: Tibet. And this, I think, is the problem. And it's almost like a structural historical moment

03:18:58.780 --> 03:19:05.500
[Guest]: or a conjuncture that we've reached of the fatality of human beings, that the Dalai will

03:19:05.500 --> 03:19:13.020
[Guest]: leave this world, sadly, current Dalai Lama, and a decision has to be made about the future of

03:19:13.020 --> 03:19:19.820
[Guest]: Buddhism in Tibet and the governing arrangements, et cetera, et cetera. And the fatal problem,

03:19:19.820 --> 03:19:25.500
[Guest]: fatal meaning, it's out of our hands that there's a Tibetan community here who will want to have a

03:19:25.500 --> 03:19:32.540
[Guest]: say. Beijing can't do anything about that existential reality. Delhi can't do anything

03:19:32.540 --> 03:19:36.860
[Guest]: about it. We're not going to force out the Tibetans. We're not going to put all the Tibetans

03:19:36.860 --> 03:19:42.540
[Guest]: in jail so we can avoid a problem with the Chinese. The Chinese can't do something about

03:19:42.540 --> 03:19:48.940
[Guest]: the Tibetans in India beyond a point, et cetera, et cetera. So I think it's a real difficulty. And

03:19:48.940 --> 03:19:56.460
[Guest]: that may account for the very serious kind of problem that occurred last year. And you can see

03:19:56.460 --> 03:20:03.660
[Guest]: 2013, 2014, 2015, all in eastern Ladakh. 2017 is a bit different, but that's a different part of

03:20:03.660 --> 03:20:12.300
[Guest]: Tibet. It's still Tibet. And by the way, the problem is in eastern Ladakh. But going back to

03:20:12.300 --> 03:20:19.100
[Guest]: 62, Mao took a decision to hit India hardest in Nipah, in Arunachal, where India was probably

03:20:19.100 --> 03:20:23.660
[Guest]: strongest militarily because he wanted to make the point that if we're going to hit India, we're

03:20:23.660 --> 03:20:27.900
[Guest]: going to teach them a lesson. You can't do it where they're weak because they'll find excuses

03:20:27.900 --> 03:20:31.340
[Guest]: saying, oh, they beat us up where we're weak. No, we're going to beat you up where you're strong

03:20:32.220 --> 03:20:39.100
[Guest]: to really make the point that we are angry with you. So this may be, again, the problem.

03:20:39.100 --> 03:20:45.820
[Guest]: And the further issue is that they lay strong claim now as they didn't as much back in the 60s

03:20:45.820 --> 03:20:52.540
[Guest]: to Arunachal. They may see economic resources in Arunachal that they didn't earlier, river waters,

03:20:52.540 --> 03:20:59.980
[Guest]: agricultural lands, minerals, and all of that, timber. And it's symbolically important because

03:20:59.980 --> 03:21:06.380
[Guest]: coming back to Tibet, Tawang Monastery, that's there. They want it. We can't give it to them.

03:21:06.380 --> 03:21:13.820
[Guest]: When the next Dalai comes, it will be in the mix of things that might play a role.

03:21:14.540 --> 03:21:21.100
[Guest]: So Arunachal is important from that point of view as well. And lastly, where are their main

03:21:21.100 --> 03:21:29.420
[Guest]: military headquarters? They're near Arunachal Pradesh. I mean, Lhasa and all of that is near,

03:21:29.420 --> 03:21:37.100
[Guest]: it's not in Ladakh. They're not in eastern Ladakh. So the command headquarters are in Chengdu

03:21:37.100 --> 03:21:43.900
[Guest]: and neighboring areas like that. They only have one big command center, and that's in Hotan

03:21:43.900 --> 03:21:49.740
[Guest]: in Xinjiang, and that's quite a distance away from eastern Ladakh. So I mean, a common sense

03:21:49.740 --> 03:21:55.580
[Guest]: of prediction would be that if there is a problem, we could have a very serious problem in Arunachal

03:21:55.580 --> 03:21:59.660
[Guest]: Pradesh, because that's where their military strength and command strength is.

03:22:01.180 --> 03:22:05.500
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, I'll cheat. Before asking my last question, I'll ask a follow up question to this.

03:22:05.500 --> 03:22:11.020
[Amit Varma]: You've been so patient with me, my God. So, and here's a follow up question. The stakes are huge,

03:22:11.020 --> 03:22:17.260
[Amit Varma]: right? If you look at it as a negative sum game, as all conflict inevitably is, it can get just

03:22:17.260 --> 03:22:21.020
[Amit Varma]: much worse and worse. And it doesn't matter how bad it gets for China, it'll get much worse for

03:22:21.020 --> 03:22:26.140
[Amit Varma]: us, and we don't want conflict. And the positive sum game of cooperation and trade and all of that,

03:22:26.140 --> 03:22:31.660
[Amit Varma]: the benefits are also incredibly huge. So now the question is that, what should India do now?

03:22:31.660 --> 03:22:35.980
[Amit Varma]: Like, going by this analysis, that this is a problem, these are their worries,

03:22:35.980 --> 03:22:41.020
[Amit Varma]: there's historically been distrust, let's resolve it once and for all. And let's kind of move ahead

03:22:41.020 --> 03:22:44.140
[Amit Varma]: and let's do what it takes to resolve it. What should India do now?

03:22:45.100 --> 03:22:49.340
[Guest]: Yeah, I mean, having said all this stuff so passionately,

03:22:49.340 --> 03:22:54.140
[Guest]: and you put me on the spot, which is a difficult one for academics, particularly, but fair enough.

03:22:54.140 --> 03:22:59.740
[Guest]: I mean, you know, the book doesn't answer the question, really. So, because I got cowardly,

03:22:59.740 --> 03:23:04.620
[Amit Varma]: and I ran out of energy and time. You were more foxy than Fedgehoggy with this.

03:23:04.620 --> 03:23:11.660
[Guest]: Yeah, exactly. Thanks. You put me in my place there, anyway. But I guess that for me, ultimately,

03:23:12.700 --> 03:23:18.140
[Guest]: at this point, I would say, there has to be a thorough excavation domestically on both sides.

03:23:18.140 --> 03:23:23.420
[Guest]: And I think that, unfortunately, you know, on the Chinese side, even if it happens,

03:23:23.420 --> 03:23:27.100
[Guest]: we're not going to see it, because they don't do that kind of stuff. They don't open up in

03:23:27.100 --> 03:23:32.860
[Guest]: their system domestically, let it all hang out, and warts and all, you see their debate and

03:23:32.860 --> 03:23:40.860
[Guest]: their mayor culpers. But we can still do it, because we're still open enough, you know, and

03:23:41.740 --> 03:23:45.980
[Guest]: we still have a bit of a political culture, I would say, where we could open it up.

03:23:45.980 --> 03:23:51.740
[Guest]: So, I think that, you know, this is a difficult question. But probably, for me, the answer is that

03:23:53.260 --> 03:23:59.740
[Guest]: Beijing and China are not going to carry out this internal, somewhat public discussion,

03:23:59.740 --> 03:24:03.820
[Guest]: which is probably necessary. I mean, they may do it internally, and it could be effective.

03:24:03.820 --> 03:24:10.940
[Guest]: But in a sense, it can still happen in India more easily, given our relatively open system. And so,

03:24:10.940 --> 03:24:18.300
[Guest]: you know, it takes courage. But I think India has to begin to vent, to open, to excavate,

03:24:18.860 --> 03:24:25.580
[Guest]: to take a risk, to open up its archives more. Maybe some things can't altogether be opened up.

03:24:25.580 --> 03:24:30.300
[Guest]: But I see a kind of opening up already happening. I mean, you know, there have been some very

03:24:30.300 --> 03:24:34.700
[Guest]: interesting books just recently, Zorawar Dholat Singh's book. I know you interviewed, I think,

03:24:34.700 --> 03:24:36.140
[Guest]: Anand Krishnan, perhaps.

03:24:36.140 --> 03:24:41.340
[Amit Varma]: I haven't spoken to Anand, but I've spoken to Manoj Kevalramani on his book, Smokeless War.

03:24:41.340 --> 03:24:45.660
[Guest]: Right, Manoj's work, which I don't know yet, actually. And so, I must read that. Thanks for

03:24:45.660 --> 03:24:51.020
[Guest]: alerting me to it again. I know there are at least a couple of Indian diplomats, who are very soon

03:24:51.020 --> 03:24:56.140
[Guest]: going to come out with books. They're China, you know, at least three of them, very, very high

03:24:56.140 --> 03:24:59.020
[Guest]: ranking in diplomats. I'm not going to mention their names, because I don't think it's my

03:24:59.020 --> 03:25:04.300
[Guest]: call to mention it, when they still haven't come out very openly. But I know, you know,

03:25:04.300 --> 03:25:08.140
[Guest]: in a way, through them, we are beginning to open it out in a way that we haven't done for a very

03:25:08.140 --> 03:25:17.900
[Guest]: long time. And so, I'm kind of still hopeful that these books will start to open it out. And if my

03:25:17.900 --> 03:25:23.020
[Guest]: book also plays a bit of a role there, you know, in just provoking people, then I think that'll be

03:25:23.020 --> 03:25:29.580
[Guest]: mission accomplished. So, I think there's hope there. And this government and Shivshankar Menon

03:25:29.580 --> 03:25:35.340
[Guest]: and Manmohan Singh also began to open up the Indian archives. So, I think that, you know,

03:25:35.340 --> 03:25:39.820
[Guest]: both these last two governments have played a role in encouraging that. And I think

03:25:40.380 --> 03:25:45.660
[Guest]: Foreign Minister Jaishankar and Modi himself, to their credit, I think are sticking with it.

03:25:45.660 --> 03:25:50.620
[Guest]: Yeah, I think that's what's got to happen. If out of that debate, then, you know, you see,

03:25:50.620 --> 03:25:56.060
[Guest]: then it's not just Modi taking a case to the country. There's a whole range of people who

03:25:56.060 --> 03:26:01.820
[Guest]: will begin to open things up, talks like this and other settings. The Indian elite and middle class

03:26:01.820 --> 03:26:08.940
[Guest]: will begin to access these debates. So, by the time a Modi or his successor comes to really sort

03:26:08.940 --> 03:26:16.620
[Guest]: of go back to China with a possible deal, they will already be a kind of civic society support

03:26:16.620 --> 03:26:22.620
[Guest]: base, which will say, all right, we're kind of ready. And I think that maybe already,

03:26:22.620 --> 03:26:29.340
[Guest]: barring some real fanatics here and there, there is a willingness now in India to kind of revisit

03:26:29.340 --> 03:26:35.340
[Guest]: the whole thing. On the Chinese side too, I think there are constituencies there. But I think it

03:26:35.340 --> 03:26:41.340
[Guest]: probably take India to kickstart it at this point. I know that's a hard one for us to swallow on,

03:26:41.340 --> 03:26:46.780
[Guest]: because we think we've been wronged very badly by China, including last year. But from the spirit

03:26:46.780 --> 03:26:52.620
[Guest]: of your question, leaving aside, you know, this episode and that episode, and who was at fault

03:26:52.620 --> 03:26:57.820
[Guest]: altogether, do we fundamentally want a resolution of this issue so that we can all move forward and

03:26:57.820 --> 03:27:03.340
[Guest]: deal with other problems? I think from that much bigger strategic perspective, I think we will have

03:27:03.340 --> 03:27:08.540
[Guest]: to take the lead in opening this up. Fascinating. I mean, I obviously don't know India-China

03:27:08.540 --> 03:27:13.740
[Amit Varma]: relations remotely, as well as experts like you do. But I do know that there is a willingness

03:27:13.740 --> 03:27:18.780
[Amit Varma]: to take India-China relations remotely, as well as experts like you do. But from the little that

03:27:18.780 --> 03:27:23.820
[Amit Varma]: I know of Indian politics, somehow I'm a little less hopeful than you are. My final question is

03:27:23.820 --> 03:27:28.380
[Amit Varma]: this, given that the stakes are so high, a lot can happen suddenly, you know, the world can change in

03:27:28.380 --> 03:27:33.580
[Amit Varma]: a week, as it were. If I ask you to look forward to say 2030, in the context of India-China

03:27:33.580 --> 03:27:37.260
[Amit Varma]: relations, what's the best case scenario? And what's the worst case scenario?

03:27:37.260 --> 03:27:43.020
[Guest]: Well, the best case is kind of this increasing internal debate that, which, in a sense,

03:27:43.020 --> 03:27:49.980
[Guest]: was catalyzed by the events of last year. So, if one could put it that way, the Chinese may have

03:27:49.980 --> 03:27:56.620
[Guest]: done us a favor by that. They may have catalyzed an internal debate that will culminate by 2030

03:27:56.620 --> 03:28:02.060
[Guest]: in new perspectives in India. And, you know, I mean, I can't say I'm a big fan of this government,

03:28:02.060 --> 03:28:09.260
[Guest]: but the chances are that Mr. Modi or a successor will be re-elected. And if they come back fairly

03:28:09.260 --> 03:28:16.220
[Guest]: strongly, they might be able to take this change that is in motion in India. And it may be that,

03:28:16.220 --> 03:28:21.100
[Guest]: if it's Mr. Modi himself, that he would see that as part of a legacy, you know. So, to personalize

03:28:21.100 --> 03:28:25.980
[Guest]: the possibility, maybe that's the way it'll work out, is that he would take it forward. And by that

03:28:25.980 --> 03:28:32.060
[Guest]: time, who knows, Xi Jinping may also be looking at a legacy issue. And they decide to go for it, and

03:28:32.060 --> 03:28:36.780
[Guest]: it works. And we have catalyzed the debate enough internally that there'll be enough support for

03:28:36.780 --> 03:28:43.020
[Guest]: a Modi at that point. And so, we get an agreement. Does that mean all quarrels will be over? No,

03:28:43.020 --> 03:28:47.740
[Guest]: but it means that at least this big one will be over, and then we can see whether we can adjust

03:28:48.380 --> 03:28:53.260
[Guest]: other matters between us. The worst case is, of course, that, you know, that doesn't happen,

03:28:53.260 --> 03:29:01.580
[Guest]: and things get worse. And the Chinese, you know, going back to what you paraphrased nicely for me,

03:29:01.580 --> 03:29:05.740
[Guest]: just the gap between the two countries either remains substantially like this or gets worse.

03:29:06.540 --> 03:29:13.180
[Guest]: And if that happens, then the Chinese would be even less prone to concede to anything to us,

03:29:13.180 --> 03:29:17.580
[Guest]: and we would find it even more difficult to, you know, do a deal which wouldn't look like a

03:29:17.580 --> 03:29:25.100
[Guest]: surrender. And who knows? I mean, our nationalists, super nationalists, and their super nationalists

03:29:25.100 --> 03:29:31.020
[Guest]: might just, it might all explode. India might drift closer and closer to the United States to

03:29:31.020 --> 03:29:36.300
[Guest]: compensate for that power gap, which will antagonize the Chinese even more. The Chinese

03:29:36.300 --> 03:29:42.380
[Guest]: will overread it, and something will happen here or there on the border, and we could get into a

03:29:42.380 --> 03:29:48.140
[Guest]: serious problem. What might salvage it for India, of course, is that despite the disparity in power,

03:29:48.780 --> 03:29:56.780
[Guest]: geography, the Himalayas, and so on, will still play a role as a stopping factor. And, you know,

03:29:56.780 --> 03:30:03.340
[Guest]: it may be another stalemate, but it could be, if any, it could be a little war again. I mean,

03:30:04.060 --> 03:30:09.500
[Guest]: the optimistic part of that is 1962 war, we think of it as one month long, but it's actually only

03:30:09.500 --> 03:30:16.940
[Guest]: 11 days of fighting in two phases. And really, for such a massive border, sad as any casualties

03:30:16.940 --> 03:30:21.100
[Guest]: are, the casualties were relatively low in the history of warfare. And that's probably going to

03:30:21.100 --> 03:30:26.060
[Guest]: be the case again, it seems to me, you know, unless people lose their heads completely on both

03:30:26.060 --> 03:30:31.900
[Guest]: sides. So I think that's the worst case scenario, that we do actually go beyond what happened last

03:30:31.900 --> 03:30:39.740
[Guest]: summer to an actual fight, maybe mostly centered on the eastern sector. And that would be, you know,

03:30:39.740 --> 03:30:43.820
[Guest]: unpredictable exactly where it would go. But again, it would make the problem worse for another

03:30:43.820 --> 03:30:51.100
[Guest]: 2030 years. Yeah. And if other countries get drawn into it, to some extent, then it affects Asia,

03:30:51.100 --> 03:30:58.940
[Guest]: it has Asia-wide ramifications. But I still remain somewhat optimistic that the events of, oddly

03:30:58.940 --> 03:31:04.460
[Guest]: enough, of last year may have catalyzed something, particularly on the Indian side, who knows how

03:31:04.460 --> 03:31:12.540
[Guest]: much on the Chinese side, and out of this something positive may come. And we could now, one last

03:31:12.540 --> 03:31:18.940
[Guest]: thought on again, to personalize it, both Xi and Modi have shown that they can make dramatic moves,

03:31:19.500 --> 03:31:26.060
[Guest]: either in their internal politics or externally. In India, you know, demonetization, GST, you know,

03:31:26.060 --> 03:31:31.100
[Guest]: certain kinds of other decisions that have been taken. One day, Modi flies to Pakistan to make

03:31:31.100 --> 03:31:37.660
[Guest]: peace in 2015. The next day, we do Balakot or whatever, you know, provoked by the Pakistanis.

03:31:37.660 --> 03:31:44.460
[Guest]: One day, there's Doklam. The next day, Modi is meeting Xi Jinping in Wuhan and then Mamlapuram.

03:31:44.460 --> 03:31:49.500
[Guest]: The Chinese, likewise, do all kinds of, one day is full four-year diplomacy. The next day, Xi Jinping

03:31:49.500 --> 03:31:54.940
[Guest]: is telling his diplomats, can you please ease back and use less harsh language and be nice,

03:31:54.940 --> 03:32:01.100
[Guest]: play nice. So, you know, we could see a dramatic reversal to Wuhan, the spirit of Wuhan and

03:32:01.100 --> 03:32:05.260
[Guest]: Mamlapuram at a moment. And you know, we have ambivalences about the relationship with the

03:32:05.260 --> 03:32:12.780
[Guest]: Americans. So, you never know, it might turn on these leaders suddenly making a switch strategically.

03:32:13.660 --> 03:32:17.420
[Amit Varma]: I'm struck by the fact that even in your worst case scenario, it doesn't get too bad because

03:32:17.420 --> 03:32:22.300
[Amit Varma]: of geography, as H.P. Lovecraft himself might have put it, the mountains of madness save Chinese

03:32:22.300 --> 03:32:27.660
[Amit Varma]: tentacles from entering Indian arteries. And, you know, but I'm also struck by the fact that some of

03:32:27.660 --> 03:32:33.260
[Amit Varma]: the hope comes from the possibility of small men looking for big legacies. So, who knows what will

03:32:33.260 --> 03:32:37.260
[Amit Varma]: happen. But, you know, I've learned so much by reading your book. I've learned so much by talking

03:32:37.260 --> 03:32:41.980
[Amit Varma]: to you for almost four hours today. So, thank you so much, Kanti, for your time and insights.

03:32:41.980 --> 03:32:47.340
[Guest]: Thank you very much. It's been a wonderful tour. I must say, revisiting my own life and

03:32:47.340 --> 03:32:53.260
[Guest]: learning from you. And I thoroughly enjoyed it. And thanks for talking about the book as well.

03:32:53.260 --> 03:33:20.220
[Amit Varma]: It's a wonderful forum that you have here.

